edes-Benz vehicles}}\n{{Mercedes-Benz S-Class lineage}}\n\n[[Category:Mercedes-Benz vehicles|W116]]\n[[Category:Mercedes-Benz model codes|W116]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1972]]\n[[Category:1970s cars]]\n[[Category:1980s cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Limousines]]\n", "name_user": "Maxq32", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePrice and interior features", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mercedes-Benz_W116"}
{"title_page": "List of Nebraska Civil War units", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe following is a list of [[Nebraska Territory]] units formed during the [[American Civil War]]. Some saw action only on the frontier in the [[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]]. The state raised one regiment of infantry (subsequently converted to cavalry), two regiments (including the converted infantry) and a battalion of cavalry (successor of the second cavalry regiment), several companies of militia, and two scout companies.\n\n==Infantry==\n* [[1st Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[First Nebraska Militia]]\n\n==Cavalry==\n* [[1st Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[1st Battalion Nebraska Veteran Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[2nd Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[Pawnee Scouts|Independent Company \"A\" Pawnee Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n* [[Independent Company Omaha Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n* [[Stuff'ts Independent Company of Indian Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lists of American Civil War regiments by state]]\n* [[Nebraska in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n* {{ cite book\n| title=Johnson's History of Nebraska\n| last=Johnson\n| first=Harrison\n| year=1880\n| publisher=Henry Gibson\n| location=Omaha, NE\n}} \n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionne.htm The Civil War Archive]\n\n[[Category:Nebraska Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Lists of military units and formations of the American Civil War|Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Nebraska-related lists|Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{main|Nebraska in the American Civil War}}\nThe following is a list of Nebraska units formed during the [[American Civil War]]. Some saw action only on the frontier in the [[American Indian Wars|Indian Wars]]. The state raised one regiment of infantry (subsequently converted to cavalry), two regiments (including the converted infantry) and a battalion of cavalry (successor of the second cavalry regiment), several companies of militia, and two scout companies.\n\n==Infantry==\n* [[1st Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[First Nebraska Militia]]\n\n==Cavalry==\n* [[1st Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[1st Battalion Nebraska Veteran Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[2nd Regiment Nebraska Volunteer Cavalry]]\n* [[Pawnee Scouts|Independent Company \"A\" Pawnee Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n* [[Independent Company Omaha Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n* [[Stuff'ts Independent Company of Indian Scouts, Nebraska Cavalry]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lists of American Civil War regiments by state]]\n\n==References==\n* {{ cite book\n| title=Johnson's History of Nebraska\n| last=Johnson\n| first=Harrison\n| year=1880\n| publisher=Henry Gibson\n| location=Omaha, NE\n}} \n*[http://www.civilwararchive.com/unionne.htm The Civil War Archive]\n\n[[Category:Nebraska Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Lists of military units and formations of the American Civil War|Nebraska]]\n[[Category:Nebraska-related lists|Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "GELongstreet", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikify / shift", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Nebraska_Civil_War_units"}
{"title_page": "Human rights in Saudi Arabia", "text_new": "{{Politics of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:Ensaf Haidar, wife of Raif Badawi speaking in 2015.jpg|thumb|[[Ensaf Haidar]], who is the wife of [[Raif Badawi]], was sentenced to 15 years in prison and 1,000 lashes for \"insulting Islam\" and \"blasphemy\".]]\nHuman rights in Saudi Arabia for the most part do not exist. The state of '''human rights in Saudi Arabia''' is consistently ranked as one of the worst in the world. The Saudi government, which enforces [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi sharia law]] under the [[Absolute monarchy|absolute rule]] of the [[House of Saud]], have been accused of and denounced by various international organizations and governments for violating multiple human rights within the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2004/41731.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices \u2013 2004|author=Unattributed|first=|date=February 28, 2005|work=|accessdate=2008-06-02|publisher=US Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labour}}</ref> The [[totalitarian]] regime ruling the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia is consistently ranked among the \"worst of the worst\" in [[Freedom House]]'s [[Freedom in the World|annual survey of political and civil rights]].<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/sites/default/files/inline_images/Worst%20of%20the%20Worst%202010.pdf Worst of the Worst 2010. The World's Most Repressive Societies]. freedomhouse.org</ref> Qorvis [[MSLGROUP|MSLGroup]], a U.S. subsidiary of [[Publicis Groupe]], has been working with [[Saudi Arabia]] amidst its executions of political protesters and opponents for more than a decade to [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] its record of [[human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Chris|title=PR firm accused of helping Saudi Arabia 'whitewash' its human rights record|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/pr-firm-accused-of-helping-saudi-arabia-whitewash-its-human-rights-record-a6937271.html|accessdate=18 May 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|date=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Supplemental Statement Pursuant to the Foreign Agents Registration Act of 1938|url=http://www.fara.gov/docs/5483-Supplemental-Statement-20150504-19.pdf|website=fara.gov|publisher=[[Foreign Agents Registration Act]]|accessdate=18 May 2016|page=12|date=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSaudi Arabia is one of approximately 30 countries in the world with [[judicial corporal punishment]]. In Saudi Arabia's case this includes [[amputation]]s of [[hands]] and feet for [[robbery]], and [[flogging]] for lesser crimes such as \"sexual deviance\" and [[drunkenness]].  In the 2000s, it was reported that women were sentenced to lashes for adultery; the women were actually victims of rape, but because they could not prove who the perpetrators were, they were deemed guilty of committing adultery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/story?id=3899920|title=Exclusive: Saudi Rape Victim Tells Her Story|author=ABC News|work=ABC News|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> The number of lashes is not clearly prescribed by law and is varied according to the discretion of judges, and ranges from dozens of lashes to several hundred, usually applied over a period of weeks or months.  In 2004, the [[United Nations Committee Against Torture]] criticized Saudi Arabia over the [[amputations]] and [[flogging]]s it carries out under [[Sharia]]. The Saudi delegation responded defending \"legal [[traditions]]\" held since the inception of Islam 1,400 years ago and rejected interference in its legal system.\n\nThe courts continue to impose sentences of flogging as a principal or additional punishment for many offences. At least five defendants were sentenced to flogging of 1,000 to 2,500 lashes. Flogging was carried out in prisons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnestyusa.org/research/reports/annual-report-saudi-arabia-2013?page=3 |title=Annual Report: Saudi Arabia 2013 &#124; Amnesty International USA |publisher=Amnestyusa.org |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Mazen Abdul-Jawad was sentenced to 1,000 lashes and five years in prison for bragging on a Saudi TV show about his sexual exploits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/6269161/Saudi-man-jailed-and-gets-1000-lashes-for-talking-about-sex.html|title=Saudi man jailed and gets 1,000 lashes for talking about sex|date=7 October 2009|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/150525|title=Saudi man gets 1,000 lashes and five years for TV sex boasts|website=www.thesundaily.my|access-date=2016-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123060151/http://www.thesundaily.my/node/150525|archive-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Saudi blogger [[Raif Badawi]]'s sentence was increased to 1,000 lashes and ten years' imprisonment after he was accused of [[apostasy]] in 2012. The lashes were due to take place over 20 weeks. The first round (50) were administered on January 9, 2015, but the second round has been postponed due to medical problems. The case was internationally condemned and put a considerable amount of pressure on the Saudi legal system.\n\nIn October 2015, [[United Kingdom|UK]] pensioner and cancer victim Karl Andree, then 74, faced 360 lashes for home brewing alcohol.  His family feared the punishment could kill him. However, he was released and returned home in November that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34513096 |title=UK pensioner Karl Andree faces 360 lashes over Saudi wine |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a Saudi man was sentenced to 2,000 lashes, ten years in prison and a fine of 20,000 [[Saudi riyal|riyal]]s (US $5,300) for making tweets critical of Islam, and denying the existence of [[God]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/saudi-arabia-sentenced-man-to-10-years-in-prison-and-2000-lashes-for-atheist-tweets|title=Saudi Arabia Sentenced a Man to 10 Years in Prison and 2,000 Lashes for Atheist Tweets|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/saudi-court-sentences-man-to-10-years-2000-lashes-for-atheist-tweets/|title=Saudi court sentences man to 10 years, 2,000 lashes for atheist tweets|website=PBS NewsHour}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the official Twitter account of the Saudi Arabia prosecutors issued a warning to punish those who share anything satirical on social media that \"affects public order, religious values and public morals\". The punishment included a five-year prison term and a fine of 3 million riyals (US $800,000). The government of Saudi Arabia arrested a few intellectuals, businessmen and activists last year for the same reason.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-04/jail-sentence-steep-fines-for-disrupting-saudi-public-order|title=Saudi Arabia Threatens Prison Time for Satire 'Disturbing Public Order'|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Torture==\nWhile Saudi Arabia's Criminal Procedure Code prohibits \"torture\" and \"undignified treatment\" (art. 2) in practice torture and using torture to extract forced confessions of guilt remains common.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/|title=Saudi Arabia 2017/2018|website=www.amnesty.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2016/04/26/un-committee-against-torture-review-saudi-arabia|title=UN Committee against Torture: Review of Saudi Arabia|date=26 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/378927-saudi-arabia-maids-abuse/|title=Torture, abuse, & harassment: ex-housemaids describe horrors of working in Saudi Arabia to RT|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/society/2017/5/2/hundreds-of-tortured-bangladeshi-women-flee-saudi-arabia|title=Hundreds of 'tortured' Bangladeshi women flee Saudi Arabia|first=Diana|last=Alghoul|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/11/19/indonesia.saudi.maid.abuse/index.html|title=Indonesian maid dies after abuse in Saudi Arabia, rights group says|author1=Kathy Quiano |author2=Moni Basu|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/blog/saudi-arabia-s-record-torturing-those-who-dare-critique-it|title=Saudi Arabia's Record of Torturing Those Who Dare to Critique It|website=Human Rights First}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Amnesty International]], security forces continued to torture and ill- treat detainees to extract confessions to be used as evidence against them at trial. According to the organization, 32 defendants accused of spying for Iran were subjected to torture and forced to confess. Detainees were held incommunicado and denied access to their families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/| title= SAUDI ARABIA 2016/2017 |access-date=2017-11-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a UN panel that visited Saudi Arabia after the kingdom\u2019s invitation to conduct an inspection, revealed that the country has been systematically using anti-terror laws to justify torture.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-torture-political-dissidents-anti-terror-laws-un-mohammad-bin-salman-a8388226.html|title=Saudi Arabia using anti-terror laws to detain and torture political dissidents, UN says|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> The report found that Saudis, who have been exercising their right to freedom of expression peacefully and calmly in the kingdom, have been systematically persecuted by the authorities.<ref>{{cit web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/un-accuses-saudi-arabia-of-using-anti-terror-laws-to-justify-torture|title=UN accuses Saudi Arabia of using anti-terror laws to justify torture|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Walid Fitaihi]] is a [[physician]] who studied and worked in the USA in the 1980s.<ref name='A1'>{{cite news |last1=Bohn |first1=Kevin |last2=Robertson |first2=Nic |title=Family of dual US-Saudi citizen being held in Saudi Arabia believes he has been tortured |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/03/politics/walid-fitaihi-us-citizen-saudi-arabia/index.html |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=CNN |publisher=edition.cnn.com |date=3 March 2019}}</ref> He was born in 1964 in [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]]. He went back to Saudi Arabia in 2006. Dr. Fitaihi was arrested at the [[Ritz Carlton]] hotel in November 2017 and moved to [[al-Ha'ir Prison|al-Hair prison]] south of the capital.<ref name='A1'/><ref name='A2'>{{cite news |last1=Dahan |first1=Nadine |title=Famous Saudi doctor moved to high-security jail, source says |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/famous-saudi-doctor-moved-high-security-jail-source-says |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=middleeasteye |publisher=middleeasteye.net |date=1 February 2018}}</ref> The Ritz-Carlton hotel was used to hold many of the prominent prisoners of the [[Saudi government]] in 2017, according to Saudi activists.<ref name='A2'/>\n[[Aljazeera]] reported, Dr.Fitaihi told a friend he was \"blindfolded, stripped of his underwear and bound to a chair\".<ref name='A4'>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia tortured US citizen: Report |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/saudi-arabia-reportedly-tortured-citizen-nyt-190302191550541.html |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=Aljazeera |publisher=aljazeera.com |date=3 March 2019}}</ref><ref name='A7'>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |title=Saudi Arabia Is Said to Have Tortured an American Citizen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/02/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-torture-american-citizen.html |accessdate=17 March 2019 |agency=nytimes |newspaper=nytimes.com |date=2 March 2019}}</ref> The daily report also said that, the Saudi government tortured him with electrical shocks, \"what appears to have been a single session of torture that lasted about an hour\".<ref name='A4'/><ref name='A7'/> Reports also said, he was whipped so severely, he could not sleep on his back for days.<ref name='A4'/><ref name='A7'/>\n\nIn August 2019, a news article released in ''[[The Independent]]'' reported that more than 100 female migrants of Bangladeshi descent and some 45 male migrants fled from [[Saudi Arabia]] following psychological and [[sexual harassment]] from employers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/saudi-arabia-bangladesh-women-migrants-abuse-sexual-harrasment-brac-a9080701.html|title=More than 100 Bangladeshi migrant women 'abused and harassed' return home from Saudi Arabia|accessdate=28 August 2019|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Capital punishment; right to representation==\n{{Further|Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:AliMohammedAlNimrSchoolPhoto.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr|Ali al-Nimr]] was arrested at the age of 17 for his participation in the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|2011 Arab Spring protests]], and was sentenced to death by beheading at the age of 18.]]\nSaudi Arabia regularly engages in [[capital punishment]], including public executions by [[decapitation|beheading]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rights group condemns Saudi beheadings|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27184784|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2008-10-14}}</ref> The death penalty can be imposed for a wide range of offenses,<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi system condemned |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/aug/09/saudiarabia.brianwhitaker |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 August 2003 |accessdate=27 July 2011 |location=London |first=Brian |last=Whitaker}}</ref> including murder, rape, armed robbery, repeated drug use, [[apostasy]],<ref name= BBCexecutioner>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2966790.stm |title=Saudi executioner tells all |date=5 June 2003 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> adultery,<ref name= FRD306>{{cite book |title=Saudi Arabia A Country Study |last=Federal Research Division |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-4191-4621-3 |page=304}}</ref> witchcraft and sorcery<ref name= Miethe>{{cite book |title=Punishment: a comparative historical perspective  |last=Miethe |first=Terance D. |author2=Lu, Hong |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-521-60516-8 |page=63}}</ref> and can be carried out by beheading with a sword,<ref name= BBCexecutioner/> [[stoning]] or firing squad,<ref name= FRD306/> followed by crucifixion.<ref name= Miethe/> In 2005 there were 191 executions, in 2006 there were 38, in 2007 there were 153, and in 2008 there were 102.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International Report 2009, Saudi Arabia |url=http://thereport.amnesty.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/saudi-arabia#death-penalty |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=2009-08-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724104756/http://thereport.amnesty.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/saudi-arabia |archivedate=2009-07-24}}</ref>\n\nA spokesman for the [[National Society for Human Rights]], an organisation which is funded by the Saudi Government, said that the number of executions is rising because crime rates are rising, that prisoners are treated humanely, and that the [[Decapitation|beheading]]s deter crime, saying, \"Allah, our creator, knows best what's good for His people...Should we just think of and preserve the rights of the murderer and not think of the rights of others?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;jsessionid=45BQVYBAZNEV1QFIQMGCFFWAVCBQUIV0?xml=/news/2007/07/16/wsaudi116.xml|title=Saudis prepare to behead teenage maid|author=Tim Butcher|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2008-10-14 | location=London | date=July 16, 2007|author-link=Tim Butcher}}</ref>\n\n[[Saudi Arabian police]] and immigration authorities routinely abuse people who are stopped or detained, especially workers from developing countries. Earlier in November 2013, the authorities received criticism for the way they have planned and handled the crackdown on illegal workers. Saudi authorities \u2013 in some cases with the help of citizens \u2013 rounded up many illegal workers and physically abused them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kumera-genet/beyond-outrage-how-the-af_b_4319840.html | work=Huffington Post |first=Kumera |last=Genet |title=Beyond Outrage: How the African Diaspora Can Support Migrant Worker Rights in the Middle East |date=2013-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/saudi-services-suffer-under-visa-clampdown-525713.html|title=Saudi services suffer under visa clampdown|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019, Saudi Arabia carried out [[2019 Saudi Arabia mass execution|mass executions of 37 imprisoned civilians]] who had been convicted mostly on the basis of confessions obtained under torture or written by the accused's torturers.<ref>{{cite news | last1= Qiblawi | first1= Tamara | last2= Balkiz | first2= Ghazi | pages= | language = | title= Exclusive: Saudi Arabia said they confessed. But court filings show some executed men protested their innocence |trans-title = | date= 2019-04-26 | publisher= [[CNN]] | url= https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/26/middleeast/saudi-executions-court-documents-intl/index.html |accessdate= 2019-04-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190426055318/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/26/middleeast/saudi-executions-court-documents-intl/index.html |archivedate= 2019-04-26}}</ref> Most of the executed belonged to the country's [[Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia|Shia minority]].<ref name=\"midd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-executions-dozens-killed-included-some-arrested-juveniles |title=Saudi executions: Dozens killed included some arrested as juveniles |publisher=[[Middle East Eye]] |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Human trafficking==\n{{Main|Human trafficking in Saudi Arabia}}\nSaudi Arabia is a notable destination country for men and women trafficked for the purposes of [[slavery|slave labour]] and commercial sexual exploitation. Men and women from [[Central Asia]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Africa]], and many other countries voluntarily travel to Saudi Arabia as domestic servants or other low-skilled labourers, but some subsequently face conditions indicative of involuntary servitude.<ref name=\"factbook\">{{cite web|title=Trafficking In Persons|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/print_2196.html|website=cia.gov|publisher=[[The World Factbook]]|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nWomen, primarily from Asian and African countries are trafficked into Saudi Arabia for commercial sexual exploitation; others were kidnapped and forced into prostitution after running away from abusive employers.<ref name=\"factbook\"/>\n\n===Sexual slavery===\nSome Saudi men have also used contracted \"temporary marriages\" in countries such as Mauritania, Yemen, and Indonesia as a means by which to sexually exploit migrant workers. Females are led to believe they are being wed in earnest, but upon arrival in Saudi Arabia subsequently become their husbands' sexual slaves, are forced into domestic labor and, in some cases, prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2014/226806.htm |title=Saudi Arabia |publisher=State.gov |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref> Prostitution is illegal in Saudi Arabia.\n\n== Women's rights ==\n{{Main|Women's rights in Saudi Arabia}}\n\n===Guardianship system, segregation, and restrictions===\nSaudi women face [[discrimination]] in many aspects of their lives, such as the [[justice system]], and under the [[Wali (Islamic legal guardian)|male guardianship system]] are effectively treated as [[minor (law)|legal minors]].<ref name=\"HRW2016\" /> Although they make up 70% of those enrolled in universities, for social reasons, women make up 5% of the workforce in Saudi Arabia,<ref>Al-Sharq Al-Awsat (London), July 23, 2006, translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> the lowest proportion in the world.\nThe treatment of women has been referred to as \"[[sex segregation]]\",<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.hri.ca/pdfs/HRT%20Spring,%20Volume%208,%20No.%201,%202001.pdf \n |accessdate=2007-08-21 \n |title=Human Rights Tribune \u2013 ed. Spring 2001 \n |work=Human Rights Tribune \n |date=Spring 2001 \n |publisher=International Human Rights Documentation Network \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002083608/http://www.hri.ca/pdfs/HRT%20Spring%2C%20Volume%208%2C%20No.%201%2C%202001.pdf \n |archivedate=2008-10-02 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.nostatusquo.com/ACLU/dworkin/WarZoneChaptIIIA.html\n|title=A Feminist Looks at Saudi Arabia\n|year=1978\n|author=Andrea Dworkin\n|publisher=Andrea Dworkin on nostatusquo.com\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref>\"gender [[apartheid]]\",<ref name=Handrahan>{{cite journal |author=Handrahan LM |title=Gender Apartheid and Cultural Absolution: Saudi Arabia and the International Criminal Court |publisher=Human Rights Internet |journal=Human Rights Tribune' |volume=8 |issue=1 |date=Spring 2001}} {{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/the-australian-who-has-become-a-prisoner-of-gender-apartheid-20091113-ier0.html|title= The Australian who has become a prisoner of gender apartheid |date=November 14, 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=March 6, 2010}}</ref> and of some women being \"prisoners\" of their male relatives.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> Implementation of a government resolution supporting expanded employment opportunities for women met resistance from within the labor ministry,<ref>Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia), May 18, 2006 translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> from the religious police,<ref>Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia), June 26, 2006 translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> and from the male citizenry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islamlight.net/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=2519&Itemid=27%5D|title=:: \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0646\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a|website=www.islamlight.net}}</ref>\n\nIn many parts of Saudi Arabia, it is believed that a woman's place is in the home caring for her husband and family, yet there are some women who do not adhere to this view and practice, and some run the house instead of the husband himself. Moreover, there is also some type of segregation at homes, such as different entrances for men and women.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\">{{cite news|title= Women Speak Out In Saudi Arabia |url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/03/23/60minutes/main682565.shtml |publisher= CBS News |date=March 24, 2005|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\nWomen's rights are at the heart of calls for [[Reform movement|reform]] in Saudi Arabia \u2013 calls that are challenging the kingdom's political status quo.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\"/> Local and international women's groups are also pushing governments to respond, taking advantage of the fact that some rulers are eager to project a more progressive image to the West. Since 2009, women and their male supporters have been organizing an [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|anti male-guardianship campaign]].<ref name=\"CNN_right_to_travel\" /><ref name=\"Guardian_2016_petition\" /> Female leaders of this movement have been imprisoned without charge. Women in general who challenge the guardianship system may be sent to shelters for troubled women, where according to human rights activists they face torture and sexual abuse.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2019/02/01/mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-entertainment/|title=Mohammed bin Salman Is Running Saudi Arabia Like a Man Who Got Away With Murder|first=Sarah|last=Aziza|date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Men are free to abuse women in Saudi Arabia, with reports of women being locked in their rooms for months or threatened with starvation or shooting for offenses such as getting the wrong kind of haircut or being in a relationship with a man the family has not approved.<ref name=\"onpoint\" />  Women cannot file police reports without the permission of a male guardian, and may end up being imprisoned by the government for complaining.<ref name=\"onpoint\" />  Women are prohibited from certain professions (such as [[optometry]]) and may be prohibited from mixing with men at work, but according to the government as of 2017 compose 30% of workers in the private sector<ref name=\"bi\" /> (which is 40% of GDP).\n\nThe presence of powerful businesswomen\u2014still a rare sight\u2014in some of these groups helps get them heard.<ref name=\"economist1\">{{cite news|title= Women in the Middle East, A weak breeze of change |url= http://www.economist.com/world/africa/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10632747 |newspaper= The Economist |date=February 2, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-26}}</ref> Prior to 2008, women were not allowed to enter hotels and furnished apartments without a chaperone or [[mahram]]. With a 2008 Royal Decree, however, the only requirement for a woman to be allowed to enter hotels is a national ID card, and (as with male guests) the hotel must inform the nearest police station of their room reservation and length of stay.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/jan/25/yehey/top_stories/20080125top4.html\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402064855/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/jan/25/yehey/top_stories/20080125top4.html\n|archivedate=2009-04-02\n|date=January 25, 2008\n|title=Saudi prince assures RP govt they respect rights of women\n|author=Jomar Canlas, Reporter\n|newspaper=The Manila Times\n|accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref> In April 2010, a new, optional ID card for women was issued which allows them to travel in countries of the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|Gulf Cooperation Council]]. The cards include [[GPS tracking unit|GPS tracking]], fingerprints and features that make them difficult to forge. Women do not need male permission to apply for the card, but do need it to travel abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Saudi women get ID cards for GCC travel|url=http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=1093319416|accessdate=21 September 2010|newspaper=The Peninsula|date=4 May 2010}} {{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Proponents argue that new female identity cards enable a woman to carry out her activities with ease, and prevent forgeries committed in the name of women.\n\nWomen first joined the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia]] in 2013, occupying thirty seats.<ref name=\"saudigazette.com.sa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130225154468 |title=Women on 3 Shoura panels |author=Saudi Gazette |publisher= |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218023529/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130225154468 |archivedate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, that year three women were named as deputy chairpersons of three committees. Dr. Thurayya Obeid was named Deputy Chairwoman of the Human Rights and Petitions Committee, Dr. Zainab Abu Talib, Deputy Chairwoman of the Information and Cultural Committee, and Dr. Lubna Al-Ansari, Deputy Chairwoman of the Health Affairs and Environment Committee.<ref name=\"saudigazette.com.sa\"/>\n\n[[File:Loujain Alhathloul.jpg|thumb|upright|Women's rights activist [[Loujain al-Hathloul]] was arrested in May 2018]]\nIn 2013 the Directorate General of Passports allowed Saudi women married to foreigners to sponsor their children, so that the children can have residency permits (iqamas) with their mothers named as the sponsors, and have the right to work in the private sector in Saudi Arabia while on the sponsorship of their mothers, and the mother can also bring her children who are living abroad back to Saudi Arabia if they have no criminal records. Foreign men married to Saudi women were also granted the right to work in the private sector in Saudi Arabia while on the sponsorship of their wives on condition that the title on their iqamas should be written as \"husband of a Saudi wife\" and that they should have valid passports enabling them to return to their homes at any time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152985 |title=Women married to foreigners can now sponsor kids, spouse |author=Saudi Gazette |publisher= |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730233947/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152985 |archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Saudi women married to foreigners, however, still face difficulty in passing their nationality to their children.\n\nAlso in 2013, Saudi Arabia registered its first female trainee lawyer, Arwa al-Hujaili.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=58013|title=.:Middle East Online::New victory for Saudi women: First female lawyer registered :.|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>  In Saudi courts, the testimony of women is weighted half that of a man's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/outrageous-facts-about-saudi-arabia/|title=15 outrageous facts about Saudi Arabia|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[CIA world factbook]], 82.2% of females are literate, in comparison to 90.8% literacy rates in males.<ref name=\"CIA Saudi\">{{cite web| title =CIA The World Factbook, Saudi Arabia|work=CIA| publisher =| date= September 20, 2007| url =https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sa.html| doi =|accessdate=2008-06-02 }}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2018, the Saudi government changed several policies, allowing women to drive with the permission of their guardian, attend sporting events in gender-segregated area, participate in sports (including exercising on public streets), and eliminated the need for male permission to receive education, get healthcare, or open a business.<ref name=\"bi\" /> It began offering physical education for girls and said it would start licensing female-only gyms.<ref name=\"bi\" /> The government opened the military to women in March, who can serve if they meet certain physical and educational requirements, continue to live with their male guardian in the province of service, and get male permission.<ref name=\"bi\" /> It also granted divorced women the ability to retain custody of children without petitioning.<ref name=\"bi\" /> Male permission is still required to apply for a passport, travel, marry, divorce, or leave jail.<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/womens-rights-in-saudi-arabia-driving-ban-2018-3|title=Saudi Arabian women can now drive \u2014 here are the biggest changes they've seen in just over a year |publisher= Businessinsider|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> Men and women are also still segregated on public transport, beaches, and pools.<ref name=\"bi\" /> In practice, some doctors still require male permission before providing services,<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> and male permission may be needed to rent an apartment or file a legal claim.<ref name=\"bi\" /> In 2019, the Saudi government has been taken new measures to release male gardianship. Thus, women will be soon allowed to travel abroad without the need of getting the permission of their male guardians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudis-plan-to-ease-travel-restrictions-on-women-11562837401|title=Saudis Plan to Ease Travel Restrictions on Women|last=Said|first=Summer|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, two prominent female human rights activists, [[Samar Badawi]] and [[Nassima al-Sada]], were arrested for challenging Saudi Arabia's male guardianship laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/08/saudi-arabia-two-more-women-human-rights-activists-arrested-in-unrelenting-crackdown/|title=Saudi Arabia: Two more women human rights activists arrested in unrelenting crackdown |publisher= Amnesty International|accessdate=1 Aug 2018}}</ref> According to [[Amnesty International]], several arrested womens' rights activists detained without charge in Dhahban Prison are enduring torture by electrocution, flogging, hanging from the ceiling, sexual assault.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/11/saudi-arabia-reports-of-torture-and-sexual-harassment-of-detained-activists/ |title=Saudi Arabia: Reports of torture and sexual harassment of detained activists  |date=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, under the predominant male guardianship system, a Saudi woman lost a legal battle to marry the man she wanted to because he played a musical instrument, many conservative Muslims in the kingdom consider music to be \u201charam\u201d (forbidden). The male relative of the woman did not allow her to marry the man of her choice citing religious incompatibility as the man played [[oud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45724710?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cwlw3xz0zl4t/saudi-arabia&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=Saudi woman 'barred from marrying man who played musical instrument'|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia is not a party to the [[International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights]], which among many other issues prohibits forced marriages. However, it is part of the Human Rights council.\n\nThe [[World Economic Forum]] in its [[Global Gender Gap Report]] 2018 ranked Saudi Arabia 141 out of 149 countries on gender equality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/reports/the-global-gender-gap-report-2018|title=The Global Gender Gap Report 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018|publisher=World Economic Forum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/with-spotlight-back-on-saudi-women-s-rights-loujain-al-hathloul-s-fate-remains-unknown-1.4981281|title=With spotlight back on Saudi women's rights, Loujain al-Hathloul's fate remains unknown|accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the government also stated that women can start working in the military. In the past they could only work in police.<ref>https://m.khaleejtimes.com/region/saudi-arabia/saudi-women-can-now-join-the-armed-forces</ref>\n\n===Driving===\n{{main|Women to drive movement}}\nSaudi Arabia was the only country in the world where women were forbidden to drive motor vehicles until June 2018.<ref name=bashraheel/> The motoring ban was not in statute law, but was an \"informal\" religious [[fatwa]] imposed by conservative Muslim clerics<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia women drive cars in protest at ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13809684|work=17 June 2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 October 2013|date=2011-06-17}}</ref> in order to maintain the country's tradition of gender segregation, although this religious view has changed in recent years.<ref name= Alarabia>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2010/05/25/109562.html|title=Women driving issue needs no fatwa: Saudi cleric|date=May 25, 2010|website=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062a}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, when 47 Saudi women drove cars through the streets of Riyadh in protest against the ban, protestors were punished. \"All the drivers, and their husbands, were barred from foreign travel for a year. Those women who had government jobs were fired, once their employers found out. And from hundreds of mosque pulpits, they were denounced by name as immoral women out to destroy Saudi society.\"<ref name=NPR>{{cite web|last=Murphy|first=Caryle|title=Saudi Women Reunite To Remember Driving Protest|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97541372|work=December 16, 2008|publisher=NPR|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the driving ban was enforced, women complained that \"we can't move around without a male.\"<ref name=BBC/> Many could not afford chauffeurs, and the few buses that do operate in cities and towns across the Kingdom do not follow a set schedule.<ref name=bashraheel>{{cite news|title= Women's transport: Solutions needed|author=Laura Bashraheel|url= http://www.arabnews.com/node/325728|newspaper=[[Arab News]]|date=June 27, 2009|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> On October 26, 2013, a group of women started a movement to defy the ban by driving themselves. However, on October 23, in a \"rare and explicit restating of the ban\", Interior Ministry Spokesman General Mansur al-Turki warned, \"It is known that women in Saudi are banned from driving and laws will be applied against violators and those who demonstrate support.\"<ref name=Casey>{{cite web|last=Casey|first=Mary|title=Saudi Arabia issues warning against women's driving campaign|url=http://mideast.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/10/25/saudi_arabia_issues_warning_against_women_s_driving_campaign|work=October 25, 2013|publisher=Foreign Policy magazine|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref> In December 2014, two women were arrested and sentenced to almost a month of prison for defying the female driving ban.<ref name=\"chronicle.fanack.com\">{{cite web|last1=Fanack|title=Saudi Arabia's Human Rights Record Under International Fire|url=https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/saudi-arabias-human-rights-record/|website=fanack.com|accessdate=13 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518082508/https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/saudi-arabias-human-rights-record/|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWomen are allowed to fly aircraft, though they must be chauffeured to the airport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia gets its first woman pilot|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/003200701121543.htm|newspaper=The Hindu|date=2007-01-12|accessdate=2008-06-02 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071026003928/http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/003200701121543.htm |archivedate = October 26, 2007|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> A Saudi woman made news in 2007 when she became the first woman to get her pilot's licence. The woman, [[Hanadi al-Hindi]] works for Saudi Prince [[Al-Waleed bin Talal|Al Waleed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/saudi-arabia-s-first-female-pilot-soars-high-2013-05-05-1.505229|title=Saudi Arabia's first female pilot soars high|last=Staff|date=5 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Hisham Fageeh]], a Saudi living in the US, has created a video which makes a reference to the Government's rules which prevented women from driving. The video was released the same day many women in Saudi Arabia staged a nationwide protest against the Government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2013/10/26/no-woman-no-drive-saudi-women-battle-to-take-the-wheel/|title='No Woman, No Drive': Saudi women battle to take the wheel|work=euronews|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a Saudi woman working in neighbouring UAE was arrested as she tried to enter Saudi Arabia. She had her passport taken from her and was forced to wait at the Saudi-UAE border without any food or water. She claimed that her UAE drivers licence was valid in all GCC countries, but the Saudi border authorities refused to acknowledge its legitimacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/saudi-woman-arrested-driving-2014121165739368209.html|title=Saudi woman 'arrested' for driving|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/25/women-charged-saudi-arabia-driving-ban-terror-court| title=Two women referred to 'terror' court for driving in Saudi Arabia| work=the Guardian|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a royal decree was issued to allowing women to drive.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaouette|first=Nicole|last2=Labott|first2=Elise|date=27 September 2017|title=Saudi Arabia to let women drive at last|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/26/politics/saudi-arabia-woman-drive/index.html|website=CNN politics|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> The first driving license was issued to a Saudi woman in June 2018 and the ban on driving was lifted on June 24, 2018.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-44367981| title=Saudi Arabia issues first driving licences to women| date=5 June 2018| website=bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-44576795| title=Saudi Arabia's ban on women driving officially ends| date=24 June 2018| website=bbc.com}}</ref> Between the announcement and the lifting of the ban, the leaders of the Women to Drive campaign who violated the ban were arrested and tortured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-accused-of-torturing-women-activists-in-widening-crackdown-on-dissent-1542743107|title=Saudi Arabia Accused of Torturing Women\u2019s-Rights Activists in Widening Crackdown on Dissent|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMale permission is still required to travel outside the home, so many women in conservative families are still not allowed to drive.<ref name=\"onpoint\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/onpoint/2019/01/17/rahaf-mohammed-alqunun-asylum-canada-saudi-arabia-women|title=After Saudi Teen Granted Aslyum, A Look At Life For Women In The Kingdom|website=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\n==Racism==\n{{main|Racism in Saudi Arabia}}Racism in Saudi Arabia extends to allegations of imprisonment, physical abuse, rape,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/13/saudi-arabia-treatment-foreign-workers|title=Saudi Arabia's treatment of foreign workers under fire after beheading of Sri Lankan maid|last=Chamberlain|first=Gethin|date=13 January 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref> overwork and wage theft, especially of foreign workers who are given little protections under the law.\n\n===Antisemitism===\n{{main|Antisemitism in Saudi Arabia}}Saudi Arabian media often attacks Jews in books, news articles, at their Mosques and with what some describe as antisemitic satire. Saudi Arabian government officials and state religious leaders often promote the idea that Jews are conspiring to take over the entire world; as proof of their claims they publish and frequently cite ''[[The Protocols of the Elders of Zion]]'' as factual.<ref>[http://www.edume.org/reports/10/38.htm CMIP report: The Jews in World History according to the Saudi textbooks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928005805/http://www.edume.org/reports/10/38.htm |date=2007-09-28 }}. ''The Danger of World Jewry'', by Abdullah al-Tall, pp. 140\u2013141 (Arabic). ''Hadith and Islamic Culture'', Grade 10, (2001) pp. 103\u2013104.</ref><ref>2006 Saudi Arabia's Curriculum of Intolerance, Report by Center for Religious Freedom of Freedom House. 2006</ref>\n\n==Rights of foreigners==\n=== Migrant workers' rights ===\n{{main|Kafala system#Saudi Arabia}}\nAccording to the 2016 [[Amnesty International]] annual report, Saudi authorities detained and deported hundreds of thousands of irregular migrants, while tens of thousands were fired without having been paid for months and were left stranded without food, water or exit visas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/|title=Saudi Arabia 2016/2017|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\n===Stateless people===\nThere are 70,000 [[Statelessness|stateless]] people in Saudi Arabia, also known as [[Bedoon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refugeesinternational.org/blog/stateless-saudi-driven-self-immolation|title=Blog \u2013 Stateless Saudi Driven to Self-Immolation \u2013 Refugees International|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424140108/http://refugeesinternational.org/blog/stateless-saudi-driven-self-immolation|archive-date=24 April 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some stateless are Yemenis who moved to Saudi Arabia, before the borders were in place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/07/18/saudi-but-stateless-born-on-margins-society.html|title=Saudi but stateless: born on the margins of society|date=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThis is also prevalent in neighbouring UAE, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21710679-many-are-left-stateless-result-silence-dissidents-gulf-states-are|title=To silence dissidents, Gulf states are revoking their citizenship}}</ref>\n\n=== Labors Rights ===\nEvery summer, the Saudi Ministry of Labor and Social Development enforce a 3-months midday outdoor work ban. The main aim of this ban is to protect labors from being directly exposed to the sun and high-temperature. Labor' either Saudi Nationals or foreigners, are welcomed to file any violations through the ministry's portal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/568463/SAUDI-ARABIA/Three-month-mid-daywork-ban-from-June-15|title=Three-month mid-day work ban from June 15|date=2019-06-09|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==Sectarianism and freedom of religion==\n{{Main|Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nSaudi Arabian law does not recognize religious freedom, and the public practice of non-Muslim religions is actively prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/nea/136079.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315154836/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/nea/136079.htm |archive-date=2010-03-15 |title=2009 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[United States Department of State]]}}</ref>\n\nNo law specifically requires citizens to be Muslims, but article 12.4 of the Naturalization Law requires that applicants attest to their religious affiliation, and article 14.1 requires that applicants get a certificate endorsed by their local cleric.<ref name=IRFR>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127357.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031224344/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127357.htm |archive-date=October 31, 2009|title=2009 International Religious Freedom Report 2009: Saudi Arabia|date=October 26, 2009|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]}}</ref> The Government has declared the Quran and the Sunna (tradition) of the Prophet Muhammad to be the country's constitution. Neither the Government nor society in general accepts the concepts of separation of religion and state, and such separation does not exist. The legal system is based on Shari'a (Islamic law), with Shari'a courts basing their judgments largely on a code derived from the Quran and the Sunna. According to Human Rights Watch, Saudi Arabia \"systematically discriminates against its Muslim religious minorities, in particular Shia and Ismailis\",<ref name=HRW-2013>{{cite web|title=World Report 2013, Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2013/country-chapters/saudi-arabia?page=3|work=2013|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> but the Government permits Shi'a Muslims to use their own legal tradition to adjudicate noncriminal cases within their community.<ref name=IRFR/>\n\nIn 2014, Saudi Arabia enacted new \"anti-terrorism\" legislation. [[Human Rights Watch]] criticized the broad language of the legislation and related government decrees, which have been used to prosecute and punish peaceful political activists and dissidents.<ref name=\"Withnall\">Adam Withnall, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-declares-all-atheists-are-terrorists-in-new-law-to-crack-down-on-political-dissidents-9228389.html Saudi Arabia declares all atheists are terrorists in new law to crack down on political dissidents], ''Independent'' (April 1, 2014).</ref> HEW stated, \"these recent laws and regulations turn almost any critical expression or independent association into crimes of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"Withnall\"/> A number of prominent [[human rights activists]] were detained under the new law, including [[Waleed Abulkhair]] and [[Mikhlif Alshammari]].<ref name=\"Withnall\"/> Interior Ministry regulations also defined \"calling for atheist thought in any form, or calling into question the fundamentals of the Islamic religion on which this country is based\" as terrorism.<ref name=\"Withnall\"/>\n\n===International law===\n\nSaudi Arabia abstained from the United Nations vote adopting the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], saying it contradicted [[sharia law]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Nisrine Abiad |title=Sharia, Muslim states and international human rights treaty obligations: a comparative study |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dex7TKuoUhgC |year=2008 |publisher=BIICL |isbn = 978-1-905221-41-7 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dex7TKuoUhgC&pg=PA60 60\u201365]}}</ref>\nIt is not a party to the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]], which includes freedom of religion.  The country holds a reservation to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] against any provisions that are in conflict with sharia law;<ref name=untreaty>United Nations Treaty Collection. ''[http://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-11&chapter=4&lang=en Convention on the Rights of the Child] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211151110/http://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-11&chapter=4&lang=en |date=11 February 2014 }}''. Retrieved 2 October 2015.</ref> Article 14 gives freedom of \"thought, conscience and religion\" to children. <!-- Unclear what its position was on the [[UN Declaration on the Elimination of All Forms of Intolerance and of Discrimination Based on Religion or Belief]]. -->\n\nSaudi Arabia and some of the Gulf states have been carrying out airstrikes on the Yemen, violating international laws and arresting anyone that criticises them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/05/09/asia/saudi-airstrikes-yemen/index.html|title=U.N. rep accuses Saudis of violating international law|author=Mariano Castillo|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45812399|title=The Jamal Khashoggi story so far|date=2018-12-11|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/10/26/18000880/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-mbs-dissidents-imprisoned|title=While the world focuses on Khashoggi, dozens of journalists and activists in Saudi Arabia are still behind bars|last=Underwood|first=Alexia|date=2018-10-26|website=Vox|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of Apartheid===\n[[Image:Christian Bypass.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Road sign on a highway into Mecca, stating that one direction is \"Muslims only\" while another direction is \"obligatory for non-Muslims\". [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|Religious police]] are stationed beyond the turnoff on the main road to prevent non-Muslims from proceeding into Mecca and Medina.<ref name=mackeymecca>[[Sandra Mackey]]'s account of her attempt to enter Mecca in {{cite book|last=Mackey|first=Sandra|title=The Saudis: Inside the Desert Kingdom|year=1987|pages=63\u201364|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0-393-32417-6}}</ref>]]\n''Saudi Arabia and the apartheid<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/2001/12/22/saudi-arabias-apartheid/6dc54ab8-37bc-4a87-86f4-c0b489fc8b8e/|title=Saudi Arabia's Apartheid|date=22 December 2001|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frontpagemag.com/fpm/219517/saudi-arabia-middle-easts-real-apartheid-state-daniel-greenfield|title=Saudi Arabia: The Middle East's Real Apartheid State|date=23 February 2014|publisher=}}</ref> analogy'' is a comparison of [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Religious segregation|treatment of minorities and non-Muslim foreigners]] with [[South Africa]]'s treatment of non-whites during its [[apartheid era]], or the description of Saudi [[Gender segregation and Muslims|treatment of women under Sharia Law]] with the concept of [[Gender apartheid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201804071063314007-feminism-saudi-society-gender-apartheid/|title=Despite Rising Feminism in Saudi Society, \"Gender Apartheid\" Is Still There|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n\n===Christians===\n{{Main|Christianity in Saudi Arabia|Persecution of Christians#Saudi Arabia}}\nAs an Islamic state, Saudi Arabia gives preferential treatment for Muslims. During [[Ramadan]], eating, drinking, or smoking in public during daylight hours is not allowed.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=52719&d=11&m=10&y=2004&pix=kingdom.jpg&category=Kingdom\n|title=Non-Muslims Urged to Respect Ramadan\n|author=P.K. Abdul Ghafour\n|newspaper=Arab News\n|date=October 11, 2004\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref> Foreign schools are often required to teach a yearly introductory segment on Islam.\nSaudi religious police have detained Shi'ite pilgrims participating in the [[Hajj]], allegedly calling them \"[[kafir|infidels]] in Mecca\".<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21680\n |title        = Saudi religious police accused of beating pilgrims\n |publisher    = Middle East Online\n |date         = August 7, 2007\n |accessdate   = 2008-06-02\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928023448/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21680\n |archive-date = 2007-09-28\n}}</ref> The restrictions on the Shi'a branch of Islam in the Kingdom along with the banning of displaying Jewish, Hindu and Christian symbols have been referred to as apartheid.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bascio|first=Patrick|title=Defeating Islamic Terrorism: An Alternative Strategy|publisher=Branden Books|year=2007|page=60|isbn=978-0-8283-2152-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bqJjhalQ3wkC&pg=PA60|accessdate=March 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government has gone further than stopping Christians from worshipping in publicly designated buildings to even raid private prayer meetings among Christian believers in their own homes.  On December 15, 2011, Saudi security forces arrested 35 Ethiopian Christians in Jeddah who were praying in a home, beating them and threatening them with death. When the Ethiopian workers' employers asked security forces for what reason they were arrested, they said \"for practising Christianity\".  Later, under mounting international pressure, this charge was changed to \"mixing with the opposite sex\".\n<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.persecution.org/2011/12/17/42-ethiopian-christians-arrested-in-saudi-arabia\n|title=42 Ethiopian Christians Arrested in Saudi Arabia\n|publisher=International Christian Concern\n|date=December 17, 2011\n|accessdate= 2011-12-24}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.persecution.org/2011/12/21/saudi-arabia-arrests-ethiopian-christians-for-mixing-with-opposite-sex/\n|title=Saudi Arabia Arrests Ethiopian Christians For \"Mixing With Opposite Sex\"\n|publisher=International Christian Concern\n|date=2011-12-21}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Saudi religious police detained more than 41 individuals after storming a house in the Saudi Arabian province of al-Jouf.  They were accused of \"plotting to celebrate Christmas,\" according to a December 26 statement released by the police branch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/14500 |title=Saudi detains dozens for \"plotting to celebrate Christmas\" |publisher=Al Akhbar English |date=2012-12-27 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101160358/http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/14500/ |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Proselytizing by non-Muslims, including the distribution of non-Muslim religious materials such as [[Bible]]s, is illegal in Saudi Arabia.\n\n===Shia Muslims===\n{{Main|Anti-Shi'ism#Saudi Arabia|Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia}}\nThe [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] government has often been viewed as an active oppressor of Shia Muslims because of the funding of the Wahabbi ideology which denounces the Shia faith.<ref name=syedjaffar/>\n\nIn 1988 [[fatwas]] passed by the country's leading cleric, [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Baaz|Abdul-Aziz ibn Baz]]  denounced the [[Shias]] as [[Apostates from Islam|apostates]]. Another by [[Abdullah Ibn Jibreen|Abdul-Rahman al-Jibrin]], a member of the Higher Council of Ulama is on record as saying\n\n<blockquote>Some people say that the rejectionists (''Rafidha'', i.e. Shia) are Muslims because they believe in God and [[Muhammad|his prophet]], pray and fast. But I say they are heretics. They are the most vicious enemy of Muslims, who should be wary of their plots. They should be boycotted and expelled so that Muslims be spared their evil.<ref name=HAKIM>[https://www.mail-archive.com/osint@yahoogroups.com/msg35080.html&#91;osint&#93; A top Saudi cleric declares Shiites to be infidels, calls on Sunnis to drive them out] {{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} 22 Jan 2007 (originally in iht.com)</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Vali Nasr, al-Jibrin's sanctioning of the killing of Shia was reiterated in Wahhabi religious literature as late as 2002.\n\nAccording to a 2009 [[Human Rights Watch]] report, Shia citizens in Saudi Arabia \"face systematic discrimination in religion, education, justice, and employment\".<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/en/news/2009/09/02/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally]|hrw.org| 2009/09/02</ref>\n\n[[Saudi Arabia]] has  no [[Shia]] cabinet ministers, [[mayors]] or police chiefs, according to another source, [[Vali Nasr]], unlike other countries with sizable [[Shia]] populations (such as [[Iraq]] and [[Lebanon]]). Shia are kept out of \"critical jobs\" in the armed forces and the security services, and not one of the three hundred [[Shia]] girls' schools in the Eastern Province has a [[Shia]] principal.\n\nPakistani columnist Mohammad Taqi has written that \"the Saudi regime is also acutely aware that, in the final analysis, the Shiite grievances ... stem from socioeconomic deprivation, as a result of religious repression and political marginalization bordering on [[Apartheid in South Africa|apartheid]].\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Mohammad Taqi |title=Saudi Arabia: the prized domino |date=March 10, 2011 |newspaper=Daily Times (Pakistan) |url=http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/editorial/10-Mar-2011/comment-saudi-arabia-the-prized-domino-dr-mohammad-taqi |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606211020/http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/editorial/10-Mar-2011/comment-saudi-arabia-the-prized-domino-dr-mohammad-taqi |archivedate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTestifying before the US [[Congressional Human Rights Caucus]], [[Ali al-Ahmed]], Director of the [[Institute for Gulf Affairs]], stated\n\n<blockquote>Saudi Arabia is a glaring example of [[religious apartheid]]. The religious institutions from government clerics to judges, to religious curriculums, and all religious instructions in media are restricted to the Wahhabi understanding of Islam, adhered to by less than 40% of the population. The Saudi government communized Islam, through its monopoly of both religious thoughts and practice. Wahhabi Islam is imposed and enforced on all Saudis regardless of their religious orientations. The Wahhabi sect does not tolerate other religious or ideological beliefs, Muslim or not. Religious symbols by Muslims, Christians, Jewish and other believers are all banned. The Saudi embassy in Washington is a living example of religious apartheid. In its 50 years, there has not been a single non-Sunni Muslim diplomat in the embassy. The branch of [[Imam Mohamed Bin Saud University]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]] instructs its students that Shia Islam is a [[Jewish conspiracy]].<ref>Human Rights in Saudi Arabia: The Role of Women, Congressional Human Rights Caucus, Testimony of Ali Al-Ahmed, Director of the Saudi Institute, June 4, 2002.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn November 2014 at [[al-Dalwah]] village in the eastern province of [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|al-Ahsa]], three unknown masked gunmen [[2014 al-Dalwah attack|opened fire]] at a Husseiniya, or Shi'ite religious center, killing eight and injuring dozens.<ref name=\"HRW killings\">{{cite web|last1=Coogle|first1=Adam|title=Dispatches: Killings of Saudi Shia a Wakeup Call|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/11/06/dispatches-killings-saudi-shia-wakeup-call|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile the government and the official media and religious establishment strongly condemned the attack, a handful of articles in the Saudi press argued that the attack \"had not come out of nowhere\", that there was anti-Shi'ite incitement in the kingdom on the part of \"the religious establishment, preachers, and even university lecturers \u2013 and that it was on the rise\".<ref name=memri>{{cite web|title=Saudi Columnists: There Is Anti-Shi'ite Incitement In Our Country|url=http://www.memri.org/report/en/0/0/0/0/0/0/8330.htm|accessdate=14 December 2014|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government has refused to allow Shia teachers and students exemption from school to partake in activities for the [[Day of Ashura]], one of the most important religious days for Shia Muslims which commemorates the martyrdom of [[Muhammad]]'s grandson, [[Husayn bin Ali]].<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica</ref>  In 2009, during Ashura commencements, Shia religious and community leaders were arrested.\n\nShiites are banned from building mosques and other religious centers, and are forced to perform Friday prayers in  homes (Al-Hassan).  In the Eastern city of [[Al-Khobar]], whose population is predominately Shia, there are no Shia mosques.<ref name=\"HRW\">[https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/09/02/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally]\" | [[Human Rights Watch]] |  3 Sept. 2009.</ref>  Saudi Arabia's religious police mandate prayers and all those in public buildings during prayer time are required to stop what they are doing to pray.  Because there are minor differences between the way that Shiites and Sunnis pray and between prayer times, Shiites are forced to either pray the Sunni way or take a break from work.\n\nIn 2009 a group of Shiites on their way to perform [[hajj]] pilgrimage (one of the five pillars of Islam that all able-bodied Muslims are required to perform once in their lives) in Mecca were arrested by Saudi religious police.<ref name=\"HRW\"/> Between February 20 and 24, 2009, Shia pilgrims from the heavily Shia Eastern Province who had come to Medina for the anniversary of the prophet Muhammad's death clashed with Sunni religious police at the Baqi' cemetery over doctrinal differences concerning the rituals surrounding commemoration of the dead. Security forces shot a 15-year-old pilgrim in the chest, and an unknown civilian stabbed a Shia religious sheikh in the back with a knife, shouting \"Kill the rejectionist [Shia].\" The authorities denied that anyone had been wounded, and played down the ensuing arrests of Shia pilgrims.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nReligious police have arrested Shia Women in the Eastern Province for matters as trivial as organizing classes for Quranic studies and selling clothing for religious ceremonies as if they were involved in political activities which are not allowed in KSA.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nIn the  eastern city of Dammam  where three quarters of the 400,000 residents are Shia, there are no Shia mosques or prayer halls, no Shia call to prayer broadcast on TV, and no cemeteries for Shia.\n\nLate 2011, a Shiite pilgrim was charged for being \"involved with blasphemy\" and sentenced to 500 lashes and 2 years in jail.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16064123 Australian faces lashes for blasphemy in Saudi Arabia]| 7 December 2011 |bbc news</ref> Also late 2011, a prominent Shiite Canadian cleric, [[Usama al-Attar]].<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/10/20111031226131935.html Saudi police arrest Canadian imam at Hajj] aljazeera.com| 31 Oct 2011</ref> He was released on the same day, declaring the arrest entirely unprovoked.<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/10/20111031175454687101.html Saudi police release Canadian Shia imam]| aljazeera.com| Last Modified: 31 Oct 2011</ref>\n\nMuch of education in Saudi Arabia is based on Sunni Wahhabi religious material.  From a very young age, students are taught that Shiites are not Muslims and that Shiism is a conspiracy hatched by the Jews, and so Shiites are worthy of death.<ref name=al-Hassan>[http://tryme3000.20megsfree.com/mystory2-eng.htm Discrimination against Shia Muslims in Saudi Arabia: The Old and New Reality] by Dr. Mohamed J. Al-Hassan ([[King Saud University]])</ref>  Government Wahhabi scholars, such as Abdulqader Shaibat al-Hamd, have proclaimed on state radio that Sunni Muslims must not \"eat their [Shia] food, marry from them, or bury their dead in Muslims' graveyards\".<ref name=al-Hassan/>\n\nThe government has restricted the names that [[Shias]] can use for their children in an attempt to discourage them from showing their identity. [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] textbooks are hostile to Shiism, often characterizing the faith as a form of heresy worse than [[Christianity]] and [[Judaism]].\n\nBecause anti-Shia attitudes are engrained from an early age, they are passed down from generation to generation.  This prejudice is found not only in textbooks, but also within the teachers in the classroom, and even in the university setting.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  (Wahhabi) teachers frequently tell classrooms full of young Shia schoolchildren that they are heretics.<ref name=syedjaffar>{{cite web|last=syedjaffar|title=The Persecution of Shia Muslims in Saudi Arabia|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-1015700|work=August 4, 2013|publisher=CNN Report|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Nasr 2006, p. 237\">Nasr, ''Shia Revival'', (2006), p. 237</ref> Teachers who proclaim that Shiites are atheists and deserve death have faced no repercussions for their actions, barely even receiving punishment.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  At a seminar about the internet, held in King Abdulaziz City of Science and Technology, professor Dr. Bader Hmood Albader explained that the internet was beneficial to society, but that there were many Shia websites claiming to be Muslim websites, which needed to be stopped.<ref name=al-Hassan/>\n\nMuch discrimination occurs in the Saudi workforce as well.  Shiites are prohibited from becoming teachers of religious subjects, which constitute about half of the courses in secondary education.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Shiites cannot become principals of schools.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Some Shiites have become university professors but often face harassment from students and faculty alike.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Shiites are disqualified as witnesses in court, as Saudi Sunni sources cite the Shi'a practise of 'Taqiyya'- wherein it is permissible to lie while they are in fear or at risk of significant persecution. Shia cannot serve as judges in ordinary court, and are banned from gaining admission to military academies,<ref name=\"HRW\"/> and from high-ranking government or security posts, including becoming pilots in Saudi Airlines.<ref>Meyer, Henry. \"[http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-02-20/saudi-arabia-risks-shiite-unrest-in-wake-of-bahrain-turmoil.html Saudi Arabia Risks Shiite Unrest in Wake of Bahrain Turmoil] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502172057/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-02-20/saudi-arabia-risks-shiite-unrest-in-wake-of-bahrain-turmoil.html |date=May 2, 2011 }} | Businessweek | 20 Feb. 2011.</ref>\n\n[[File:Dawoud Al Marhoon.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Dawoud al-Marhoon]], sentenced to death in September 2015]]\n[[Amir Taheri]] quotes a Shi'ite businessman from Dhahran as saying \"It is not normal that there are no Shi'ite army officers, ministers, governors, mayors and ambassadors in this kingdom. This form of religious apartheid is as intolerable as was apartheid based on race.\" <ref>Taheri, Amir. Apartheid, Saudi Style, New York Post, May 22, 2003.</ref>\n\n[[Human Rights Watch]] reports that Shiites want to be treated as equals and desire to be free from discrimination (Human Rights Watch).  However, the Shia minority is still marginalized on a large scale.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nThe Saudi government has often been viewed as an active oppressor of Shias<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/08/24/anti-shia-bias-driving-saudi-arabia-unrest|title=Anti-Shia Bias Driving Saudi Arabia Unrest|date=24 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> because of the funding of the Wahabbi ideology which denounces the Shia faith.  In 1988 [[fatwas]] passed by the country's leading cleric, [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Baaz|Abdul-Aziz ibn Baz]] denounced the [[Shias]] as [[Apostates from Islam|apostates]].<ref>[http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20141209181117/http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PolicyFocus70FinalWeb.pdf ''With Neighbors Like These Iraq and the Arab States on Its Borders'', edited by David Pollock, Washington Institute Policy Focus No 70, June 2007], p33.\n\nThis cited ''A Top Saudi Cleric Declares Shiites to Be Infidels, Calls on Sunnis to Drive Them Out'', Associated Press, 21 January 2017.</ref> [[Abdullah Ibn Jibreen|Abdul-Rahman al-Jibrin]], a member of the Higher Council of Ulama sanctioned the killing on Shiites in 1994. According to Vali Nasr, this was still be reiterated in Wahhabi religious literature as late as 2002.<ref name=\":0\">Nasr, ''Shia Revival'', (2006) p. 236</ref> By 2007 al-Jibrin wrote that [Shiites] \"are the most vicious enemy of Muslims, who should be wary of their plots.\"<ref name=\":0\" />  According to a 2009 [[Human Rights Watch]] report, Shia citizens in Saudi Arabia \"face systematic discrimination in religion, education, justice, and employment\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/09/03/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally|title=Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally|date=2009-09-03|newspaper=Human Rights Watch|language=en|access-date=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Saudi Arabia executed the prominent Shiite cleric [[Sheikh Nimr]], who had called for pro-democracy demonstrations, along with 47 other Saudi citizens [[2016 Saudi Arabia mass execution|sentenced]] by the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] on terrorism charges.<ref>{{cite web | title=Saudi execution of Shia cleric sparks outrage in Middle East |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/02/saudi-execution-of-shia-cleric-sparks-outrage-in-middle-east |work=[[The Guardian]]| date=2 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SKEW7RtQ_U|title='It's like war here': Saudi govt cracks down on Shia town as Riyadh welcomes Trump|last=RT|date=19 May 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fDeDA9JRRrA|title=20,000 residents flee deadly Saudi offensive|last=PressTV|date=10 August 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CfwFS_Ynn7g|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S3U8jHg-HNA|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X0W5z-6zKt8|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> in response to protests against the government, the predominantly Shia town of [[Al-Awamiyah]] has been put under full siege by the Saudi military. Residents are not allowed to enter or leave, and military indiscriminately shells the neighborhoods with [[airstrike]]s, [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.abna24.com/news/a-h-b-world-assembly/abwas-satement-on-condemnation-of-al-sauds-crimes-in-awamiyah_845264.html|title=ABWA's satement on condemnation of Al Saud's crimes in Awamiyah|last=ABNA24|date=31 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> and [[artillery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.abna24.com/news/middle-east/saudi-forces-shell-homes-in-awamiyah-two-killed-video-pics_844374.html|title=Saudi forces shell homes in Awamiyah, Two killed / Video & Pics|first=PressTV|last=ABNA24|date=26 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> fire along with [[sniper]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ifpnews.com/exclusive/snipers-injure-scores-civilians-saudi-arabias-qatif/|title=Snipers Injure Scores of Civilians in Saudi Arabia's Qatif|date=14 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> shooting residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/05/17/522264/Saudi-regime-forces-kill-Shia-man-Awamiyah-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces shot dead youth in restive Qatif|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://217.218.67.231/Detail/2017/05/18/522334/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-Shia-Qatif-Eastern-Province-crackdown|title=PressTV-Saudi regime offensive on Shia town enters week 2|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/388885-saudi-raid-siege-shiite-awamiyah/|title='You might get shot any time': Saudi forces raid Shia town as Riyadh welcomes Trump|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://en.abna24.com/news/middle-east/saudi-shia-town-under-siege-from-kingdom's-security-services-for-sixth-day_829902.html {{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> Dozens of Shia civilians were killed, including a three year old and<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/awamiyah-saudi-arabia-boy-killed-sniper-gun-shot-wounds-family-shot-at-open-fire-qatif-shia-nimr-al-a7886136.html|title=Three-year-old dies from wounds after Saudi security forces 'open fire on family'|publisher=}}</ref> a two-year-old children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://217.218.67.231/Detail/2017/05/12/521648/Saudi-kill-child-Shia-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces kill toddler, young man in Qatif|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.almanar.com.lb/260170|title=Saudi Forces Raid Al-Masoura in Awamiyah, Open Fire, Destroy Houses|publisher=}}</ref> The Saudi government claims it is fighting terrorists in al-Awamiyah.\n\nResidents also reported soldiers shooting at homes, cars and everyone in streets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/399222-saudi-forces-awamiyah-demolition/|title='Almost like war zone': Saudi 'renovation' of Shiite town decried as attempt to drive residents out|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-siege-town-own-citizens-government-kingdom-military-government-awamiyah-qatif-a7877676.html|title=Inside the Saudi town that's been under siege for three months by its own government|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the crackdown the Saudi government demolished several historical sites and many other buildings and houses in Qatif.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/saudi-awamiya-un-idINKBN18K1S0|title=U.N. slams erasing of \"cultural heritage\" in Saudi Arabia|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/06/14/525294/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-UN-Eastern-Province|title=PressTV- Saudi forces intensify attacks on Shia town|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/05/24/523077/UN-Saudi-Arabia-Shia-cultural-heritage|title=PressTV-'Riyadh erasing cultural heritage in Shia town'|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, Saudi authorities began refusing to give emergency services to wounded civilians. Saudi Arabia has also not provided humanitarian help to trapped citizens of Awamiyah.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al-Musawara neighborhood totally destroyed, Saudi Arabia says|url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/30097-al-musawara-neighborhood-totally-destroyed-saudi-arabia-says|website=Shiite News|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, it was reported that the Saudi government demolished 488 buildings in Awamiyah. This demolition came from a siege of the city by the Saudi government, as it continued to try to prevent the citizens of the city from gaining their rights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia demolishes 500 residential buildings in Awamiya|url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/30140-saudi-arabia-demolishes-500-residential-buildings-in-awamiya|website=Shiite News|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n20,000 residents were forced to flee from their homes to survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-security-awamiya-idUSKBN1AJ217|title=Saudi man killed trying help citizens flee Awamiya: sources|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.ir/Detail/2017/08/11/531369/UN-Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah|title=PressTV-UN finally breaks silence on Saudi razing of town|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nPresident of Quran Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/06/25/526476/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces kill head of Quran council in Qatif|publisher=}}</ref> and two cousins of executed [[Nimr al-Nimr]] were also killed by Saudi security forces in [[Qatif]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamidkarbalai.com/2017/03/saudi-regime-forces-kill-sheikh-nimrs.html|title=Saudi regime forces kill Sheikh Nimr's cousins in Qatif: Report|publisher=|access-date=2017-08-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806221347/http://www.hamidkarbalai.com/2017/03/saudi-regime-forces-kill-sheikh-nimrs.html|archive-date=2017-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/03/28/515921/Saudi-forces-shooting-Qatif-Eastern-Province-Sheikh-Nimr-cousins-killed|title=PressTV-'Saudi forces kill Nimr's cousins in Qatif'}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Saudi forces raided and \"violently ransacked\" the home of a Shia activist that had been executed the previous year. Saudi forces also arrested Zuhair Hussain bu Saleh, a Shia cleric, for organizing congregational prayers in his home in the city of [[Khobar]]. The Saudi government forbids Shia Muslims in Khobar from setting up a Mosque and gathering for worship.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi regime forces raid executed activist's home in Shia-populated Qatif |url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/34928-saudi-regime-forces-raid-executed-activist-s-home-in-shia-populated-qatif |website=Shiite News |publisher=Shiitenews.com |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi authorities announced in May 2019, the decision to extend the jailterm for a cleric, Sheikh Mohammad bin Hassan al-Habib, known for challenging the systematic discrimination of Shia minorities in Saudi Arabia. Hassan al-Habib has been serving a seven-year prison sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/05/03/saudi-arabia-second-case-against-jailed-shia-cleric|title=Saudi Arabia: Second Case Against Jailed Shia Cleric|accessdate=3 May 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n===\"Magic, witchcraft and sorcery\"===\n{{Main|Witchcraft#Saudi Arabia}}\n{{See also||Religious discrimination against Neopagans}}\nAccording to Sarah Leah Whitson, Middle East director at [[Human Rights Watch]] in 2009, \"Saudi judges have harshly punished confessed `witches` for what at worst appears to be fraud, but may well be harmless acts.\"<ref name=HRW-2009>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia: Witchcraft and Sorcery Cases on the Rise|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/11/24/saudi-arabia-witchcraft-and-sorcery-cases-rise|work=November 24, 2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  In 2009 the Saudi \"[[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|religious police]]\" established a special \"Anti-Witchcraft Unit\" to educate the public, investigate and combat [[witchcraft]].<ref name=MILLER/>\n\nAmong the people executed in Saudi for magic and sorcery (and often other charges) are Egyptian pharmacist Mustafa Ibrahim (beheaded in 2007 in Riyadh), Muree bin Ali bin Issa al-Asiri (found in possession of [[talisman]]s, and executed in [[Najran Region|Najran province]] in June 2012), Amina bin Salem Nasser<ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia execution of 'sorcery' woman condemned|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/8952641/Saudi-Arabia-execution-of-sorcery-woman-condemned.html|accessdate=13 Dec 2011|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=19 February 2014|location=London}}</ref> (executed in December 2011 in [[Al Jawf Region|Jawf]]), and Abdul Hamid Bin Hussain Bin Moustafa al-Fakki (a Sudanese migrant worker executed in a car park in [[Medina]] on September 20, 2011).<ref name=bbc-sorcery>{{cite news|title=Saudi man executed for 'witchcraft and sorcery'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-18503550|work=19 June 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 February 2014|date=2012-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Execution Central: Saudi Arabia's Bloody Chop-Chop Square|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/453240/20130403/saudi-arabia-chop-square-beheading.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102124924/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/453240/20130403/saudi-arabia-chop-square-beheading.htm|archivedate=2013-11-02}}</ref> [[Ali Hussain Sibat]], a Lebanese host of a popular fortune-telling TV program, was arrested while in Saudi in May 2008 on [[Umrah]] and sentenced to death but finally released sometime in 2011 or 2012.<ref name=Hilleary>{{cite web|last=Hilleary|first=Cecily|title=Saudi Arabia Morality Police Declare War on Witches |url=http://middleeastvoices.voanews.com/2012/03/saudi-arabia-morality-police-declare-war-on-witches-10918/|work=30 March 2012|publisher=Middle East Voices|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nMany convicted of magic receive lesser punishments of lashes and/or prison. In 2011, the \"Anti-Witchcraft Unit\" processed over 586 cases of magical crime.<ref name=Jacobs/> In 2012 there were 215 witchcraft arrests made.<ref name=Llanos>{{cite web|last=Llanos|first=Miguel|title=Saudi Arabia's religious police department has an Anti-Witchcraft Unit to combat sorcery. Arrests are on the rise and the penalty can be as severe as death.|url=http://news.msn.com/world/witchcraft-arrests-in-saudi-arabia-on-the-rise|work=8/20/13|publisher=MSN News|accessdate=20 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225175229/http://news.msn.com/world/witchcraft-arrests-in-saudi-arabia-on-the-rise|archive-date=25 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The majority of these offenders are foreign domestic workers from Africa and Indonesia.<ref name=Jacobs/>\nForeign domestic workers who bring unfamiliar traditional religious or folk customs are a disproportionately affected by the anti-witchcraft campaign according to Human Rights Watch researchers Adam Coogle and Cristoph Wilcke.  Saudis assume folk practices are \"some kind of sorcery or witchcraft\"<ref name=MILLER>{{cite news|last=MILLER|first=DAVID E.|title=Saudi Arabia's 'Anti-Witchcraft Unit' breaks another spell|url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Saudi-Arabias-Anti-Witchcraft-Unit-breaks-another-spell|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|quote=We hear time and again of foreigners, such as Ethiopians or Nigerians, accused of sorcery in Saudi Arabia because of traditional practices from their countries of origin. ... They are usually apprehended by the religious police, brought to court, and let off with a warning or lashes. [Cristoph Wilcke]|date=2011-07-20}}</ref><ref name=Jacobs>{{cite journal|last=Jacobs|first=Ryan|title=Saudi Arabia's War on Witchcraft|journal=The Atlantic|date=August 19, 2013|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/08/saudi-arabias-war-on-witchcraft/278701/|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> and widespread belief in witchcraft means it can be invoked as a defense in Sharia courts against workers complaining of mistreatment by Saudi employers.<ref name=Jacobs2>{{cite journal|last=Jacobs|first=Ryan|title=Saudi Arabia's War on Witchcraft|journal=The Atlantic|date=August 19, 2013|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/08/saudi-arabias-war-on-witchcraft/278701/|quote=\"If there's an employer dispute \u2013 say the migrant domestic worker claims she wasn't paid her wages or her conditions are unlivable \u2013 a lot of times what happens unfortunately is the defendant makes counterclaims against the domestic worker,\" Coogle said. \"And a lot of times they'll make counterclaims of sorcery, witchcraft, and that sort of thing.\"|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  Humans Rights Watch believes that the conviction of a Syrian national, `Abd al-Karim Mara'I al-Naqshabandi \u2013 executed in 1996 for undertaking `the practice of works of magic and spells and possession of a collection of polytheistic and superstitious books`\u2014was actually resulted from a dispute with his employer Prince Salman bin Sa'ud bin `Abd al`Aziz, a nephew of [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia|King Fahd]].\n<ref>''A Fury For God : the Islamist Attack on America'' by Malise Ruthven, 2002 p.178-9</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title     = 'Flawed Justice: the Execution of 'Abd al-Karim Maria'I al-Naqshbandi'\n |publisher = Human Rights Watch\n |date      = October 1997\n |url       = http://hrw.org/reports/1997/saudi/\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20010719090112/http://hrw.org/reports/1997/saudi/\n|archive-date = 2001-07-19\n}}</ref>\n\n== Freedom of press and communication ==\n{{main|Censorship in Saudi Arabia}}\n\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]] in 2017 Saudi Arabia continued to repress pro-reform activists and peaceful [[dissident]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2018/country-chapters/saudi-arabia|title=World Report 2018: Rights Trends in Saudi Arabia|first1=Human Rights Watch {{!}} 350 Fifth|last1=Avenue|first2=34th Floor {{!}} New|last2=York|first3=NY 10118-3299 USA |last3=t 1.212.290.4700|date=9 January 2018|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n[[File:London protest against Saudi Arabia's detention of prisoner of conscience Raif Badawi.jpg|thumb|A protest outside the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia, London|Saudi Arabian Embassy]] in London against detention of [[Raif Badawi]], 13 January 2017]]\nSpeech, the press and other forms of communicative media, including television and radio broadcasting and Internet reception, are actively censored by the government to prevent political dissent and anything deemed, by the government, to be offensive to Wahhabi culture or Islamic morality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/filtering/saudiarabia/|title=Documentation of Internet Filtering in Saudi Arabia|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a prominent Saudi [[Blogging in Arab countries|blogger]] and reformist, [[Fouad al-Farhan]], was jailed for posting comments online that were critical of Saudi business, religious and media figures, signifying a move by the government to step up its censorship of the Internet within its borders.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/02/27/saudi.blogger/index.html|title=No freedom for 'dean of Saudi bloggers'|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> He was released on April 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0428/p07s02-wome.html|title=Saudi official: why popular blogger Farhan was jailed|author=The Christian Science Monitor|work=The Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOnline social media has increasingly come under government scrutiny for dealing with the \"forbidden\" topics. In 2010 a Saudi man was fined and given jail time for his sexually suggestive YouTube video production. That same year another man was also jailed and ordered to pay a fine for boasting about his sex life on television.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/10/saudi-man-arrested-for-se_n_493473.html |title=Saudi Man Arrested For Sexually Suggestive YouTube Video (VIDEO) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |accessdate=2013-01-02 |first=Adam |last=Taylor |date=2010-03-10}}</ref>\n\n''D+Z'', a magazine focused on development, reports that hundreds were arrested in order to limit freedom of expression. Many of these individuals were held without trial and in secret. The torture of these prisoners was also found to be prevalent.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joseph |last=Miller |title=Open secrets |date=March 2003 |work=D+Z |publisher=Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ) GmbH |url=http://www.inwent.org/ez/articles/192821/index.en.shtml |accessdate=2011-04-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221070951/http://www.inwent.org/ez/articles/192821/index.en.shtml |archivedate=2011-02-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2012, blogger [[Raif Badawi]] was charged with apostasy, which carries the death penalty. Badawi is the editor and of co-founder of Free Saudi Liberals, a website for religious discussion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/22/net-us-saudi-website-apostasy-idUSBRE8BL0DA20121222|title=Saudi website editor could face death for apostasy-rights group|date=Dec 22, 2012|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg130812>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-12/saudi-court-condemns-editor-to-600-lashes-with-breaks.html|title=Saudi Court Condemns Editor to 600 Lashes With Breaks|date=August 12, 2013|newspaper=Bloomberg|author=Jeremy Gerard}}</ref> The organization Human Rights Watch has called for charges against him to be dropped.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Eric Goldstein |author2=deputy Middle East director |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/12/22/saudi-arabia-website-editor-facing-death-penalty |title=Saudi Arabia: Website Editor Facing Death Penalty &#124; Human Rights Watch |publisher=Hrw.org |date=2012-12-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> He had been sentenced to seven years in prison and 600 lashes for \"insulting Islam\", but this sentence was changed to 1,000 lashes, 10 years in prison, and additionally a fine of 1,000,000 Saudi riyals. The lashes are due to be administered every Friday for 20 weeks, 50 lashes at a time, but have not continued past the first flogging. The second flogging has been postponed more than twelve times; previous postponements were due to health reasons, but the reason behind the most recent postponement is unknown.\n\nSaudi novelist and political analyst [[Turki al-Hamad]] was arrested December 24, 2012 after a series of tweets on religion and other topics. The arrest was ordered by Saudi Interior Minister Prince [[Mohammed bin Nayef|Muhammad bin Nayef]]; however the charges against al-Hamad were not announced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/saudi-novelist-arrested-tweets-criticizing-islam |title=Saudi novelist arrested for tweets criticizing Islam |publisher=Al Akhbar English |date=2012-12-26 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101054807/http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/saudi-novelist-arrested-tweets-criticizing-islam |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has since been freed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/detained-saudi-writer-turki-al-hamad-freed-1.1193165|title=Detained Saudi writer Turki Al Hamad freed| date=June 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Abdullah al-Hamid at the ninth hearing session.JPG|thumb|170px|[[Abdullah al-Hamid]] has been imprisoned seven times for supporting the establishment of a [[constitutional monarchy]] in Saudi Arabia. He has been serving an 11-year jail sentence since 2013.]]\nIn July 2015, [[Waleed Abulkhair]], a prominent human rights lawyer, founder of Monitor of Human Rights in Saudi Arabia and recipient of 2012 of the Palm prize for human rights, was sentenced to 15 years of prison by a special criminal court in Riyadh for vague offences such as \"setting up an unlicensed organization.\"<ref name=\"chronicle.fanack.com\"/><ref name=\"hrw2\">{{ cite web | url = https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/04/17/saudi-arabia-free-prominent-rights-activist | title = Saudi Arabia: Free Prominent Rights Activist| publisher = [[Human Rights Watch]] | accessdate = 2014-04-17 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2015, [[Ashraf Fayadh]], a [[Palestinian refugee#Saudi Arabia|Palestinian]] poet and [[contemporary art]]ist, was sentenced to death for committing apostasy. Fayadh was detained by the country's religious police in 2013 in [[Abha]], in southwest Saudi Arabia, and then rearrested and tried in early 2014. He was accused of having promoted [[Atheism and Islam|atheism]] in his 2008 book of poems ''Instructions Within''. However, the religious police failed to prove that his poetry was atheist propaganda and Fayadh's supporters believe he is being punished by hardliners for posting a video online showing a man being lashed in public by the religious police in Abha. Adam Coogle, a Middle East researcher for Human Rights Watch, said Fayadh's death sentence showed Saudi Arabia's \"complete intolerance of anyone who may not share government-mandated religious, political and social views\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batty|first1=David|title=Saudi court sentences poet to death for renouncing Islam|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/20/saudi-court-sentences-poet-to-death-for-renouncing-islam?CMP=share_btn_tw|accessdate=21 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=McDowall|first1=Angus|last2=Evans|first2=Dominic|title=Saudi court sentences Palestinian poet to death for apostasy: HRW|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/20/us-saudi-rights-idUSKCN0T913X20151120#tMy7vQtVcR9dHHDm.97|accessdate=21 November 2015|work=[[Reuters]]|date=20 November 2015|location=[[Riyadh]]}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, [[Culture of Saudi Arabia#Literature|Saudi Arabian writer]] and commentator [[Zuhair Kutbi]] was sentenced to four years in prison without clear charges following an interview at the [[Rotana Group#Rotana TV channels|Rotana Khaleejia]] TV channel in which he discussed his ideas for peaceful reform in Saudi Arabia to become a [[constitutional monarchy]], and talked about combatting [[Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia|religious]] and [[political repression]]. Kutbi's lawyer and son said half the sentence was suspended, but that he was also banned from writing for 15 years and travelling abroad for five, and fined US$26,600.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia 'jails reformist writer Zuhair Kutbi'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-35154411|accessdate=1 April 2016|work=[[BBC]]|date=21 December 2015|page=bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia: Prominent Writer Detained \u2013 Discussed Peaceful Reform in TV Interview|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/08/10/saudi-arabia-prominent-writer-detained|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|accessdate=1 April 2016|location=[[Beirut]]|date=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFebruary 2017, [[Human Rights Watch]] issued a report regarding the violation of freedom of speech in Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/02/07/509481/Saudi-Arabia-repression-dissidents-activists-Human-Rights-Watch|title=PressTV-Saudi Arabia steps up repression in 2017: HRW|publisher=}}</ref> According to the report, since 2010, at least 20 prominent Saudi dissidents were sentenced to a long prison term or a travel ban for some years; the offenses ranged from breaking allegiance with the ruling family{{clarify|date=February 2019}} to participating in protests demanding rights be respected. According to the report, the government has been trying to silence people expressing dissenting views regarding religion, politics, and human rights. On April 17, 2011, Nadhir al-Majed, a prominent 39-year-old writer, was arrested at school and detained for 15 months. On January 18, 2017, he was sentenced to seven years in prison and a seven-year travel ban; he has also not been permitted to call his family or receive visits. The conviction was based on \"his participation in protests in 2011 over discrimination against [[Shia Islam|Shia]]\" and \"his communication with international media and human rights organizations\", supporting the right of Shia in the country. On 10 January, Abdulaziz al-Shubaily, a human rights activist, was re-sentenced to eight years in prison, an eight-year ban on using social media after his release and an eight-year travel ban; the charges included \"his incitement against the government and judiciary\" as well as \"his communication with international agencies against his government\". He remains free on bail, however. On 8 January, Essam Koshak, 45, was detained without charge; he used social medial to highlight Saudi Arabia's repression of dissident writers, activists, and advocates for their release. Since 2014, nearly all Saudi dissidents have been sentenced to a long jail term based on their activism in addition to arrest of all the activists associated with the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]], which was dissolved on March 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/06/saudi-arabia-intensified-repression-writers-activists|title=Saudi Arabia: Intensified Repression of Writers, Activists|date=2017-02-06|newspaper=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the [[Right Livelihood Award]] awarded three jailed Saudi human rights activists with the \"alternative Nobel prize\" award. [[Abdullah al-Hamid]], [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani]] and [[Waleed Abu al-Khair]] were jointly awarded one million kronor cash award \"for their visionary and courageous efforts, guided by universal human rights principles, to reform the totalitarian political system in Saudi Arabia.\" {{As of|2018|09}}, al-Hamid and al-Qahtani, founding members of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]], were serving prison sentences of 11 and 10 years respectively, according to the charges for \"providing inaccurate information to foreign media, founding and operating an unlicensed human rights organization\"; while al-Khair, a lawyer and activist, was serving a sentence of 15 years for \"disobeying the ruler\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/09/24/world/europe/ap-eu-sweden-alternative-nobel.html|title=3 Saudi Human Rights Activists Awarded 'Alternative Nobel'|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a Saudi American journalist, Jamal Khashoggi was murdered inside a foreign embassy. He was a critic of Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In June 2019, a 101-page report by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|OHCHR]] accused the kingdom of Saudi Arabia for the premeditated [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/19/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-evidence-un-report|title='Credible evidence' Saudi crown prince liable for Khashoggi killing \u2013 UN report|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> The same year, British media group, [[The Guardian]], claimed that it was being targeted by a cybersecurity unit in Saudi Arabia. The unit was directed to hack into the email accounts of the journalists probing into the various crises involving the royal court. The claim was made based on what is said to be a confidential internal order, signed in the name of [[Saud al-Qahtani]], a close aide of the crown prince [[Mohammed bin Salman]] also named in the murder of Khashoggi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/19/guardian-told-it-was-target-of-saudi-hacking-unit-after-khashoggi-killing|title=Guardian told it was target of Saudi hacking unit after Khashoggi killing|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, ''[[The Guardian]]'' revealed that [[Saudi Arabia]] had been allegedly [[Espionage|spying]] its citizens in the [[US]]. The [[Media of the United Kingdom|British media]] cited that the nation has been readily exploiting the weakness in global mobile telecom network called [[Signalling System No. 7|SS7]], and informed that the data reviewed by them shows millions of covert tracking requests for the US location of Saudi-registered phones since November 2019.<ref>{{cite_web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/29/revealed-saudis-suspected-of-phone-spying-campaign-in-us |title=Revealed:Saudis suspected of phone spying campaign in US |accessdate=29 March 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Extraterritorial harassment, forced repatriation, and killing==\n[[File:Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right| [[Jamal Khashoggi]] was murdered by Saudis in Turkey, because of his opposition to the government ]]\n\nAbout 1200 people fled Saudi Arabia and sought asylum in other countries in 2017, including many women fleeing forced marriages or abusive male family members.<ref name=\"silence\">{{cite magazine |magazine= [[The New Yorker]] |author=Sarah Aziza |date=15 Jan 2019 |title=The Saudi Government's Global Campaign to Silence Its Critics}}</ref>  The Saudi government has frozen bank accounts, arrested family members, and revoked official documents in an attempt to get fleeing citizens to return to the country or to a Saudi embassy.<ref name=\"silence\" /> Students studying abroad have been threatened with termination of scholarships in response to criticism of the Saudi government on social media, and in 2018 some studying in Canada were de-funded after the Canadian government criticized human rights in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"silence\" /> Women who have successfully gained asylum in Western countries report fearing for their personal safety after being harassed by Saudi government agents on social media, and sometimes in person, warning them that they will be sorry for their actions or be punished.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> Occasionally they are asked to go to Saudi embassies for no stated reason.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> One woman, unlike most, reported going to the embassy to try to end harassment of a firm she had left to her business partners, but she said authorities attempted to get her to return, threatened her, and said the business would continue to have problems as long as she remained in Germany.<ref name=\"silence\" />\n\nThe Saudi government is suspected of being behind the disappearance of its critic Naser al-Sa\u2019id from Lebanon in 1979.\nHuman rights activist Loujan al-Hathloul was forcibly repatriated from the United Arab Emirates in 2017, jailed for a short time, banned from future international travel, and then disappeared after being arrested again in 2018. Her husband was forcibly repatriated from Jordan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi Wasn't the First \u2014 Saudi Arabia Has Been Going After Dissidents Abroad for Decades |date=12 Oct 2018 |author=Sarah Aziza |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/10/12/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-dissidents/ |website=[[The Intercept]]}}</ref> In 2016, three women and seven children who fled to Lebanon were arrested by Lebanese police and returned to Saudi Arabia minutes after using a bank card.<ref name=\"silence\" />\n\n[[File:Lastknowphotoofdinaali2.jpg|thumb|Last known photo of [[Dina Ali]] (left), on April 10, 2017]]\n\nIn April 2017, 24-year-old [[Dina Ali]] attempted to flee from Saudi Arabia to Australia via the Philippines to escape a [[forced marriage]]. Despite her pleas for international assistance over social media, airport personnel in the Philippines blocked her from boarding her flight to Sydney, and handed her over to Saudi authorities. She was duct taped and forcibly repatriated to Saudi Arabia, where she feared her family would kill her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/forcibly-reptriated-saudi-woman-my-family-will-kill-me/a-38445701|title=Forcibly repatriated Saudi woman: 'My family will kill me' |date= 16 April 2017|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Rahaf Mohammed]] attempted a similar flight from a forced marriage, traveling to Australia via Kuwait and Thailand. She also said that her family threatened to kill her for leaving Islam (which is also a capital offense in Saudi Arabia). After her passport was taken and authorities in Manilla acted at the request of the Saudi government to stop her travel, she barricaded herself in her hotel room and pleaded on social media for international assistance.  The [[UNHCR]] and the government of Canada intervened, and Rahaf travelled successfully to Canada via South Korea. Other Saudi women have done the similar things.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/death-threats-for-sydney-activist-behind-saudi-women-s-driving-breakthrough|title=Death threats for Sydney activist behind Saudi women's driving breakthrough|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2018, [[Jamal Khashoggi]] entered the Saudi consulate in [[Istanbul]] in order to deal with paperwork related to his marriage. A veteran Saudi journalist who had become a vocal critic of Saudi regime, upon arrival Khashoggi [[killing of Jamal Khashoggi|was assassinated]] and dismembered.<ref name=\"bbc_khashoggi_181025\" /> In the previous September, Khashoggi had fled Saudi Arabia after the arrests of other Saudi intellectuals, clerics and activists, fearing that he too would be arrested or banned from travelling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/02/world/middleeast/journalist-saudi-consulate-istanbul.html|title=Journalist Detained in Saudi Consulate in Istanbul|work=The New York times|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/friends-fear-for-safety-of-prominent-saudi-writer-jamal-khashoggi/2018/10/02/f4d1cfbc-c66a-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Friends fear for safety of prominent Saudi writer Jamal Khashoggi|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> On 3 October, a Saudi official claimed that Khashoggi had been neither detained nor killed, saying \"He is not in the consulate nor in Saudi custody.\" [[Ibrahim Kalin]], Turkish presidential spokesman, said \"According to the information we have, this person who is a Saudi citizen is still at the Saudi consulate in Istanbul.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45744764|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Mystery over missing Saudi journalist deepens|work=BBC News|accessdate= 4 October 2018}}</ref> Three weeks after Khashoggi went missing, Saudi authorities acknowledged that he had been killed at the consulate and that his body was removed from the consulate. The killing was described as \"murder\" and \"a tremendous mistake\" by Saudi Foreign Minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]]. On 25 October 2018, one of the Saudi public prosecutors told the media that Khashoggi's murder was \"premeditated\".<ref name=\"bbc_khashoggi_181025\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45812399|title=Jamal Khashoggi: All you need to know about Saudi journalist's death|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 December 2019, [[Saudi Arabia]] sentenced five people to death for the [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]], while charged three others with a prison term of 24 years. The sentences did not include the names of previously accused masterminds, Mohammed al-Otaibi and Former royal adviser [[Saud al-Qahtani]]. Qahtani, who was under investigation earlier, was released with no evidence found against him.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/23/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-to-death-for-of-jamal-khashoggi|title=\nSaudi Arabia sentences five to death for murder of Jamal Khashoggi|accessdate=23 December 2019|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Political freedom ==\n{{See also|Saudi Arabian municipal elections, 2005|Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman (30421982117).jpg|thumb|On 16 October 2018, Saudi Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] met with U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] to discuss the [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]], who was a vocal critic of the Saudi regime.]]\nThe 1990s marked a slow period of political liberalization in the kingdom as the government created a written constitution, and the advisory ''[[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Consultative Council]]'', the latter being an appointed delegation of Saudi scholars and professionals that are allowed to advise the king.  Some political dissidents were released from prison, after agreeing to disband their political parties.  In 2005, adult male citizens were allowed to vote for some municipal seats, although plans for future elections, which may include adult women, have been put on hold indefinitely.\n\n[[List of political parties in Saudi Arabia|Political parties are banned]], but some political dissidents were freed in the 1990s on the condition that they disband their political parties.  Today, only the [[Green Party of Saudi Arabia]] remains, although it is an illegal organization.  Trade unions are also banned, but the government has granted permission for Saudi citizens to form some private societies, which are allowed to do some humanitarian work within the kingdom.\n\nPublic demonstrations or any public act of dissent are forbidden.  In April 2011, during the [[2011\u20132012 Saudi Arabian protests]], the kingdom made it a crime to publish any criticism harming the reputation of government or religious leaders, or which harms the interests of the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/05/23/136570798/saudis-impatient-for-kings-promised-reforms|title=Saudis Impatient For King's Promised 'Reforms'|accessdate=2011-06-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]] annual report 2016, [[Saudi Arabia]] continued to prosecute pro-reform activists and dissidents. Saudi Arabia's terrorism court sentenced Waleed Abu al-Khair, prominent activist, to 15 years. He was convicted on charges concerning his peaceful criticism of the human rights situation in his country. In July, authorities arrested Zuhair Kutbi, an activist, because of his discussion to a peaceful reform in media. In September 2015, all of banned \u2013Saudi Civil Political Rights Association (ACPRA) founders were jailed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia|date=2016-01-12|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Political prisoners===\n{{main|Political prisoners in Saudi Arabia}}\nDissidents have been detained as [[political prisoners in Saudi Arabia]] during the 1990s, 2000s and 2010s.<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\" /> Protests and [[sit-in]]s calling for political prisoners to be released took place during the [[2011\u20132012 Saudi Arabian protests]] in many cities throughout Saudi Arabia,<ref name=\"aljaz_20March\" /><ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\" /><ref name=\"HRW_Dec2011_protests\" /><ref name=\"presstv_RiyadhMakkah28Jul2012\" /><ref name=\"presstv_9Aug2012\" /> with security forces firing live bullets in the air on 19 August 2012 at a protest at [[al-Ha'ir Prison]].<ref name=\"ANHRI_19aug2012alHair\" /> {{As of|2012}}, recent estimates of the number of political prisoners in [[Mabahith]] prisons range from an estimate of zero by the [[Ministry of Interior]]<ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\" /><ref name=\"GulfNews_noprisonersinKSA\" /> to 30,000 by the [[United Kingdom|UK]]-based [[Islamic Human Rights Commission]]<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\" /> and the [[BBC]].<ref name=\"BBC_10to30k\" />\n\nAllegedly [[Jamal Khashoggi|Khashoggi]] was not the only dissident on Saudi's list to be abducted. Another Saudi prince, Khaled bin Farhan al-Saud, living in exile in [[Germany]], told [[The Independent]] that a similar kidnapping was planned against him by the Saudi authorities 10 days prior. \u201cOver 30 times the Saudi authorities have told me to meet them in the Saudi embassy but I have refused every time. I know what can happen if I go into the embassy. Around 10 days before Jamal went missing they asked my family to bring me to Cairo to give me a cheque. I refused,\u201d said Saud.  Five other royals, grandsons of [[Ibn Saud|King Abdul-Aziz]] were detained, when they raised their voice about Khashoggi's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-missing-khaled-farahan-saudi-arabia-crown-prince-mbs-mohammad-bin-salman-a8579746.html|title=Dissident Saudi royal claims he was targeted with plan to 'disappear him' just days before journalist vanished\n|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, a prominent Saudi cleric, Ahmed al-Amari, was detained by the Saudi authorities over the allegations of being associated with scholar and Saudi royal family critic [[Safar al-Hawali]]. Amari was held in solitary confinement since then. In January 2019, Amari died suffering a brain hemorrhage.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-arrests/saudi-cleric-detained-in-crackdown-dies-activists-idUSKCN1PF1QM|title=Saudi cleric detained in crackdown dies: activists|accessdate=21 January 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the [[Washington Post]] reported that about eight citizens of [[Saudi Arabia]] were detained within two weeks for making critical comments against the kingdom. Rights groups have condemned the act by calling it an escalation of an ongoing crackdown on dissent.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/11/26/saudi-arabias-crackdown-dissent-keeps-going-here-are-latest-arrests/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s crackdown on dissent keeps going. Here are the latest arrests.|accessdate=26 November 2019|website=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Human rights organizations==\n[[File:King Salman bin Abdulaziz of Saudi Arabia bids farewell to President Barack Obama at Erga Palace in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|[[Human Rights Watch]] criticized U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] for not addressing human rights concerns in Saudi Arabia.<ref>\"[https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/03/31/dispatches-obama-refuses-talk-human-rights-saudi-arabia Dispatches: Obama Refuses to Talk Human Rights in Saudi Arabia]\". Human Rights Watch. March 31, 2014.</ref>]]\n\n===Independent===\nThe [[Committee for the Defense of Human Rights in the Arabian Peninsula]] is a Saudi Arabian human rights organization based in [[Beirut]] since 1992.<ref name=\"WISER_CDHRAP_NGO\" /><ref name=\"ColumbiaLawSchool_CDHRAP\" />\n\nThe [[Human Rights First Society]] applied unsuccessfully for a governmental licence in 2002, but was allowed to function informally.<ref name=\"USStateD_2002licence\">{{cite web |title=2008 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[United States State Department]] |date=2009-02-25 |url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402081759/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archivedate=2011-04-02}}</ref> The [[Association for the Protection and Defense of Women's Rights in Saudi Arabia]] was created in 2007 and is also unlicensed.<ref name=\"USStateD_APDWRSA_nolicence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175245/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archive-date=2009-02-26 |title=2008 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=State.gov |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (ACPRA) was created in 2009.<ref name=\"acpra_founding\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association (ACPRA) (An Establishing Declaration) \u2014 Riyadh, Saudi Arabia \u2014 Monday, October 12, 2009 |publisher=[[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] |date=2009-10-12 |url=http://www.acpra.net/news_view_5.html |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010032401/http://www.acpra.net/news_view_5.html |archivedate=October 10, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> One of its co-founders, [[Mohammed Saleh al-Bejadi]], was [[arbitrary arrest|arbitrarily arrested]] by [[Mabahith]], the internal security agency, on 21 March 2011, during the [[2011 Saudi Arabian protests]].<ref name=\"acpra_albjady_arrested\">{{cite web| title =ACPRA demands the immediate unconditional release of its co-founder, Mohammed Al-Bjady| publisher =[[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]]| date=March 2011| url =http://www.acpra.net/news.php?action=list&cat_id=12| format =| doi =| accessdate =2011-03-24| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110314210519/http://www.acpra.net/news.php?action=list&cat_id=12| archivedate =2011-03-14}}</ref><ref name=\"hrfs_aims\">{{cite web |title=Human Rights First Society \u2013 Human Rights Monitoring and Advocacy in Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[Human Rights First Society]] |date=March 2011 |url=http://hrfssaudiarabia.org/ |format= |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302192030/http://hrfssaudiarabia.org/ |archivedate=2011-03-02}}</ref> Al-Bejadi was charged in the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] in August 2011 for \"insurrection against the ruler, instigating demonstrations, and speaking with foreign [media] channels.\"<ref name=\"HRW_albjady\">{{cite web |title=World Report 2012: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |year=2012 |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2012/world-report-2012-saudi-arabia |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126034621/http://www.hrw.org/world-report-2012/world-report-2012-saudi-arabia |archivedate=2012-01-26}}</ref> Another co-founder, [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani]], was charged for his human rights activities in June 2012.<ref name=\"AI_2012_charges\" /><ref name=\"alkarama_charges\" />\n\nSixteen people who tried to create a human rights organization in 2007 were arrested in February 2007, charged in August 2010, and convicted on 22 November 2011 of \"forming a secret [organization], attempting to seize power, incitement against the King, financing terrorism, and money laundering\" and sentenced by the Specialized Criminal Court to 5\u201330 years' imprisonment, to be followed by travel bans.<ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_sentenced\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Lengthy sentences for reformists a worrying development |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=2011-11-23 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-lengthy-sentences-reformists-worrying-development-2011-11-23 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302224042/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-lengthy-sentences-reformists-worrying-development-2011-11-23 |archivedate=2012-03-02}}</ref> They appealed on 22 January 2012.<ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_to_appeal\">{{cite web |title=Reform activists in Saudi Arabia must receive fair appeal hearings |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=2012-01-25 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/reform-activists-saudi-arabia-must-receive-fair-appeal-hearings-2012-01-25 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304144526/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/reform-activists-saudi-arabia-must-receive-fair-appeal-hearings-2012-01-25 |archivedate=2012-03-04}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Society for Development and Change]] was created in September 2011<ref name=\"presstv_created_sep2011\" /> and campaigns for equal [[human rights]] for [[Shia]] in [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"Fr24_ADC\" /> The organisation calls for a [[constitution]] and elected [[legislature]] for [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Eastern Province]].<ref name=\"indep_oct_livefire\" /> The [[European Saudi Organisation for Human Rights]], which started operating around 2013,<ref name=\"ESOHR_ListOf23\" /> campaigns for Saudi human rights in general, including reports on what its leader Ali Adubisi describes as the Saudi government's \"war\" against the Eastern Province.<ref name=\"DW_Awamiya2017\" /><ref name=\"ESOHR_AboutUs\" /> [[ALQST]] is a Saudi human rights organisation created in August 2014 by [[Yahya Assiri]], with a Saudi-based team for collecting evidence and a London-based team for reports and human rights campaigning.<ref name=\"RSF_createdAug2014\" /><ref name=\"MEE_YAssiri_founding\" />\n\n===Government-associated===\nIn 2004, the [[National Society for Human Rights]], associated with the Saudi government, was created.<ref name=\"karavali_hrfs_on_elections\">{{cite news |pages= |title=Saudi polls, aid sweeteners not enough: activists |date=2011-03-24 |publisher=[[Karavali Times]] |url=http://www.karavalitimes.com/middle-east/saudi-polls-aid-sweeteners-not-enough-activists/ |accessdate=2011-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321193438/http://www.karavalitimes.com/middle-east/saudi-polls-aid-sweeteners-not-enough-activists/ |archivedate=2012-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"ksa_embassy_NSHR\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/2004News/Press/PressDetail.asp?cIndex=193|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121163639/http://www.saudiembassy.net/2004News/Press/PressDetail.asp?cIndex=193 |title=First independent human rights organization in Saudi Arabia|archivedate=November 21, 2006}}</ref> Most of the commission's directors are members of the Saudi \"religious and political establishment\" according to [[John R. Bradley]].<ref name=bradley-expo->{{cite book|last=Bradley|first=John R.|title=Saudi Arabia Exposed : Inside a Kingdom in Crisis|url=https://archive.org/details/saudiarabiaexpos00brad|url-access=registration|date=2005|publisher=Palgrave |page=[https://archive.org/details/saudiarabiaexpos00brad/page/165 165] |quote= }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission (Saudi Arabia)|Human Rights Commission]] is a government organization established in September 2005. It claims to be fully independent from the government in performing its responsibilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrc.gov.sa/en-us/aboutHRC/AboutHRC/Pages/HRCvision.aspx|title=Human Rights Commission|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref> In March 2019 it opposed international investigation of the 2 October 2018 [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref name=\"NPR_commission_opposes_investigation\">{{cite news | last1=Romo | first1=Vanessa | last2= | first2= | pages= | language = | title= Saudi Arabia Rejects Calls For Independent Investigation Into Khashoggi Killing |trans-title = | date= 2019-03-14 | newspaper= [[NPR]] | url= https://www.npr.org/2019/03/14/703590542/saudi-arabia-rejects-calls-for-independent-investigation-into-khashoggi-killing |accessdate= 2019-10-15 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191014221210/https://www.npr.org/2019/03/14/703590542/saudi-arabia-rejects-calls-for-independent-investigation-into-khashoggi-killing |archivedate= 2019-10-14 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== LGBT rights ==\n{{Main|LGBT rights in Saudi Arabia|Death penalty for homosexuality}}\n[[LGBT]] [[Human rights|rights]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] are unrecognized. [[Homosexuality]] is frequently a taboo subject in Saudi Arabian society and is punished with imprisonment, [[corporal punishment]] and [[capital punishment]]. [[Transgender]] people are generally associated with homosexuality and doctors are banned by the Saudi Ministry of Health from giving [[hormone replacement therapy]] to transgender people seeking to medically transition.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} In 2017, two [[transgender]] Pakistanis were tortured to death by Saudi police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/transgender-pakistani-saudi-arabia-tortured-death-amna-meeno-11-custody-lgbt-rights-human-a7607446.html|title=Two transgender Pakistanis 'tortured to death' by police in Saudi Arabia|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== HIV/AIDS ==\nBy law, all Saudi citizens who are infected with HIV or AIDS are entitled to free medical care, protection of their privacy and employment opportunities. However, most hospitals will not treat patients who are infected, and many schools and hospitals are reluctant to distribute government information about the disease because of the strong taboos and stigma that are attached to how the virus can be spread.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=68051&d=7&m=8&y=2005\n|title=AIDS? What AIDS?\n|publisher=Arab news\n|author1=Manal Quota |author2=Maryam Yamani |date=August 7, 2005\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref>\n\nUntil the late 1990s, information on [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]] was not widely available to the public, but this has started to change.  In the late 1990s, the government started to recognize [[World AIDS Day]] and allowed information about the disease to be published in newspapers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}  The number of people living in the kingdom who were infected was a closely guarded secret.  However, in 2003 the government announced the number of known cases of HIV/AIDS in the country to be 6,700, and over 10,000 in June 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/08/world/middleeast/08saudi.html\n|title=Saudi Arabia Begins to Face Hidden AIDS Problem\n|newspaper=New York Times\n|author=Hassan M. Fattah|date=August 8, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n==International conventions==\nThe Kingdom of Saudi Arabia ratified the [[International Convention against Torture]] in October 1997 according to the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights. The Human rights of Saudi Arabia are specified in article 26 of the [[Basic Law of Saudi Arabia]]. Recently created human rights organisations include [[Human Rights First Society]] (2002),<ref name=\"USStateD_2002licence\" /> [[Association for the Protection and Defense of Women's Rights in Saudi Arabia]] (2007),<ref name=\"USStateD_APDWRSA_nolicence\" /> [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (2009)<ref name=\"acpra_albjady_arrested\" /><ref name=\"hrfs_aims\" /> and the government-associated [[National Society for Human Rights]] (2004).<ref name=\"karavali_hrfs_on_elections\" /><ref name=\"ksa_embassy_NSHR\" /> In 2008, the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Shura Council]] ratified the [[Arab Charter on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/2008News/News/RigDetail.asp?cIndex=7698|title=Shura Council ratifies Arab Charter on Human Rights}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2011, the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] was used to charge and sentence human rights activists.<ref name=\"HRW_albjady\" /><ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_sentenced\" />\n\n==Responses and criticisms==\n{{expand section|date=April 2018}}\nThe United Nations Special Rapporteur on Counter Terrorism, [[Ben Emmerson]], criticized Saudi Arabia for violating human rights in the name of fighting terrorism during his visit to Saudi Arabia from 30 April to 4 May 2017. According to the report, Saudi Arabia uses its terrorism tribunal and counterterrorism law to unjustly prosecute human rights defenders, writers, and peaceful critics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/05/26/saudi-arabia-counterterrorism-apparatus-targets-rights-activists|title=Saudi Arabia: Counterterrorism Apparatus Targets Rights Activists|date=2017-05-26|publisher=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-11-19|language=en |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725145038/https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/05/26/saudi-arabia-counterterrorism-apparatus-targets-rights-activists|archivedate=25 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adhrb.org/2017/05/adhrb-welcomes-rapporteur-terrorisms-observations-saudi-visit/|title=ADHRB Welcomes Rapporteur on Terrorism's Observations After Saudi Visit|date=2017-05-08|publisher=Americans for Democracy & Human Rights in Bahrain|access-date=2017-11-19|language=en-US |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015110839/http://www.adhrb.org/2017/05/adhrb-welcomes-rapporteur-terrorisms-observations-saudi-visit/|archivedate=15 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the U.N. Third Millennium Summit in [[New York City]], King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah bin Abdul Aziz]] defended Saudi Arabia's position on human rights, saying \"It is absurd to impose on an individual or a society rights that are alien to its beliefs or principles.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud|title=Statement by Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz, King of Saudi Arabia, during the U.N. Third Millennium Summit|url=https://www.un.org/millennium/webcast/statements/saudi.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|date=6 September 2000}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Minister of Foreign Affairs issued a statement via Twitter on 2 August 2018 expressing [[Canada]]'s concern over the recent arrest of [[Samar Badawi]], a human rights activist and sister of imprisoned Saudi blogger [[Raif Badawi]], and called for the release of Saudi human rights activists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2018/08/05/saudi-arabia-to-expel-canadian-ambassador-and-freeze-trade-in-human-rights-dispute.html|title=Saudi Arabia expels Canadian ambassador, freezes trade in human rights dispute|author=Jon Gambrell|publisher=The Associated Press|website=Toronto Star|date=5 August 2018}}</ref> In response to Canada's criticism, [[Canada\u2013Saudi Arabia relations|Saudi Arabia expelled]] Canada's ambassador and froze all new trade with Canada.<ref>{{cite news |title='We don't have a single friend': Canada's Saudi spat reveals country is alone |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/11/canada-saudi-arabia-support-us |work=The Guardian |date=11 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. refuses to back Canada in Saudi Arabia dispute |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-us-sidesteps-getting-involved-in-escalating-saudi-canada-dispute/ |work=The Globe and Mail |date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA joint statement released by 36 countries at the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] in [[Geneva]] in March 2019, condemned the [[Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|murder of the Saudi journalist]] [[Jamal Khashoggi]], called for the release of Saudi women\u2019s rights activists detained in May 2018, and urged the kingdom to stop using counterterrorism regulations to target dissidents and human rights activists.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/07/un-call-free-saudi-women-activists|title=UN: A Call to Free Saudi Women Activists|accessdate=7 March 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> The letter, which is the first collective rebuke of the kingdom, demanded the release of prominent women activists, including [[Loujain al-Hathloul]], [[Hatoon al-Fassi]] and [[Samar Badawi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/07/middleeast/saudi-arabia-criticism-intl/index.html|title=Saudi Arabia criticized over human rights by 36 countries|accessdate=7 March 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, following increased pressure from non-profit organization [[Human Rights Foundation]], [[Nicki Minaj]] pulled out of the Jeddah World Fest, Saudi Arabia in support of the nation\u2019s suppressed women and LGBTQ community.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/08/human-rights-group-asks-nicki-minaj-cancel-performance-saudi-arabia/|title=Human rights group asks Nicki Minaj to cancel performance in Saudi Arabia|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> Minaj said, \u201cI could make one mistake & go to jail in a diff country where women have no rights,\u201d after learning about the constant abuse of human rights in the nation. The organization lauded Minaj\u2019s decision and urged other artists of the likes of [[Steve Aoki]] and [[Liam Payne]] from performing in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/arts/music/nicki-minaj-saudi-arabia.html|title=Nicki Minaj Cancels Saudi Show After Complaints From Human Rights Groups|work=The New York Times|accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, ahead of Saudi [[Spanish Super Cup]] due to be held in January 2020, Spanish broadcaster [[RTVE]] said that it will not bid for the hosting rights of the tournament because of human rights concern, especially women rights in the field of sports. \"It's a country where until very recently women couldn't go to watch football,\" the broadcasting service said. [[RFEF]] President [[Luis Rubiales]], defended the claims and said, he could assure women would be allowed to enter without any restrictions.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.begadistrictnews.com.au/story/6493694/spanish-state-tv-shuns-super-cup-in-jeddah/?cs=2439|title=Spanish state TV shuns Super Cup in Jeddah |accessdate=15 November 2019|website=Bega District News}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Human Rights Watch]] alongside 11 other international rights group organizations wrote a joint letter to the [[Amaury Sport Organization]] following its decision to move [[Dakar Rally]] to [[Saudi Arabia]]. The rights group in their letter accused Saudi Arabia of violating women's rights in the nation and asked the French organizer to denounce the persecution of women\u2019s rights, as well as adopt the human rights policy. \"The Amaury Sport Organisation and race drivers at the Dakar Rally should speak out about the Saudi government\u2019s mistreatment of women\u2019s rights activists for advocating for the right to drive,\u201d the statement from the Human Rights Watch global initiatives director read. However, Saudi human rights group Al Qst asked Amaury Sport Organisation not to consider the plea.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/international-coalition-urges-amaury-sport-organisation-to-adopt-human-rights-policy-ahead-of-saudi-hosted-dakar-rally|title=International coalition urges Amaury Sport Organisation to adopt human rights policy ahead of Saudi-hosted Dakar Rally|accessdate=13 January 2020|website=Business & Human Resource Research Centre}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Meghan MacLaren]] withdrew from Saudi leg of Ladies European Tour due to be held in March 2020. The golfer cited she cannot ignore what organizations like [[Amnesty International]] have highlighted. \u201cI\u2019ve decided not to play based on what I think sport is being used to do in [[Saudi Arabia]],\" she said while emphasizing on the appalling human rights record of the nation.\u201cWe take for granted a lot of the choices and freedom we have available to us, but I try to make my decisions based on who I am as a person, not just a golfer,\" statement from her interview further read.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.nationalclubgolfer.com/news/meghan-maclaren-explains-saudi-snub/|title='It\u2019s a huge tournament but this is about more than golf'|accessdate=29 January 2020|website=National Club Golfer}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[Legal system of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[LGBT rights in Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Shi'a Islam in Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Human rights in Muslim-majority countries]]\n*[[Human rights in the Middle East]]\n*[[Timeline of first women's suffrage in majority-Muslim countries]]\n*[[Hack of Jeff Bezos' phone]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n\n<!-- political prisoners summary -->\n\n<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia's political prisoners: towards a third decade of silence |publisher=[[Islamic Human Rights Commission]] |date=2011-09-30 |url=http://ihrc.org.uk/attachments/article/9867/Saudi%20Report%20A4-v04.pdf |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203081209/http://www.ihrc.org.uk/attachments/article/9867/Saudi%20Report%20A4-v04.pdf |archivedate=2011-12-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\">{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Giglio |title=Saudi's Surprise Renegades |date=2011-05-01 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/05/01/saudi-s-surprise-renegades.html |accessdate=2012-07-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120602070507/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/05/01/saudi-s-surprise-renegades.html |archivedate=2012-06-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"aljaz_20March\">{{cite news |title=Saudi protest ends with arrests |date=21 March 2011 |publisher=Al Jazeera English |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320112126999266.html |accessdate=21 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321131829/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320112126999266.html |archivedate=21 March 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"HRW_Dec2011_protests\">{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia: Renewed Protests Defy Ban |date=2011-12-30 |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2011/12/30/saudi-arabia-renewed-protests-defy-ban |accessdate=2012-01-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108013013/http://www.hrw.org/news/2011/12/30/saudi-arabia-renewed-protests-defy-ban |archivedate=2012-01-08}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"presstv_RiyadhMakkah28Jul2012\">{{cite news |pages= |title=Saudi anti-regime protesters stage rallies in Riyadh, Mecca |date=2012-07-29 |publisher=[[Press TV]] |url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2012/07/29/253276/riyadh-mecca-see-fresh-protest-rallies/ |accessdate=2012-07-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731204015/http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2012/07/29/253276/riyadh%2Dmecca%2Dsee%2Dfresh%2Dprotest%2Drallies/ |archivedate=2012-07-31}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"presstv_9Aug2012\">{{cite news |author=AGB/MA/AZ |title=Saudi protesters call for prisoners' release |date=2012-08-10 |publisher=[[Press TV]] |url=http://www.presstv.com/detail/2012/08/10/255462/saudis-call-for-prisoners-release/ |accessdate=2012-08-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812072347/http://presstv.com/detail/2012/08/10/255462/saudis-call-for-prisoners-release/ |archivedate=2012-08-12}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ANHRI_19aug2012alHair\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Dispensing a Peaceful Demonstration after Assaulting Prisoner's Wife and Four of Her Children due to A video Segment |publisher=[[Arabic Network for Human Rights Information|ANHRI]] |date=2012-08-28 |url=http://www.anhri.net/en/?p=9263 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-08-31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902102232/http://www.anhri.net/en/?p=9263 |archivedate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"GulfNews_noprisonersinKSA\">{{cite news |title=Saudi campaigner goes on trial |date=2012-09-01 |newspaper=[[Gulf News]] |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/saudi-campaigner-goes-on-trial-1.1068937 |accessdate=2012-09-01 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902003017/http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/saudi-campaigner-goes-on-trial-1.1068937 |archivedate=2012-09-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"BBC_10to30k\">{{cite news |first=Sue Lloyd |last=Roberts |pages= |title=Saudi Arabia show of force stifles 'day of rage' protests |date=2011-03-11 |publisher=BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9422550.stm |accessdate=2012-09-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906000312/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9422550.stm |archivedate=2012-09-06}}</ref>\n\n<!-- CDHRAP -->\n<ref name=\"WISER_CDHRAP_NGO\">{{cite web|author1=World Index of Social |author2=Environmental Responsibility |authorlink=WiserEarth |title=Committee for the Defense of Human Rights in the Arabian Peninsula CDHRAP |language=French |publisher=[[WiserEarth]] |date=2006-01-18 |url=http://fr.wiserearth.org/organization/view/9199489bcfdeb80f04933a85e75f434e |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-01-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106231728/http://fr.wiserearth.org/organization/view/9199489bcfdeb80f04933a85e75f434e |archivedate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ColumbiaLawSchool_CDHRAP\">{{cite web |last=Arthur W. Diamond Law Library |title=Middle East organizations and web resources |publisher=[[Columbia Law School]] |year=2008 |url=http://www.hrcr.org/regional/middle.html |doi= |accessdate=2012-01-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316195212/http://www.hrcr.org/regional/middle.html |archivedate=2012-03-16}}</ref>\n\n<!-- ACPRA -->\n<ref name=\"AI_2012_charges\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia ramps up clampdown on human rights activists |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=2012-06-18 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-ramps-clampdown-human-rights-activists-2012-06-18 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-07-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120802015219/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-ramps-clampdown-human-rights-activists-2012-06-18 |archivedate=2012-08-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"alkarama_charges\">{{cite web | title =Saudi Arabia: Prominent Human Rights Defender Risks 5 Years of Prison for cooperating with the UN | publisher =[[Alkarama]] | date =2012-06-29 | url =http://en.alkarama.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=961:saudi-arabia-prominent-human-rights-defender-risks-5-years-of-prison-for-cooperating-with-the-un&catid=33:communiqu&Itemid=179 | format = | doi = | accessdate =2012-07-20 | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120922095741/http://en.alkarama.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=961:saudi-arabia-prominent-human-rights-defender-risks-5-years-of-prison-for-cooperating-with-the-un&catid=33:communiqu&Itemid=179 | archivedate =2012-09-22}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Society for Development and Change -->\n<ref name=\"presstv_created_sep2011\">{{cite news\n |pages       = \n |title       = Saudi activists form political group\n |date        = 2011-09-13\n |publisher   = [[Press TV]]\n |url         = http://presstv.com/detail/198910.html\n |accessdate  = 2012-01-15\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120224223404/http://presstv.com/detail/198910.html\n |archivedate = 2012-02-24\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<!-- ESOHR, ALQST -->\n<ref name=\"ESOHR_AboutUs\">{{cite web| last1 =| first1 =| last2 =| first2 =| authorlink =| title =About us| publisher =[[European Saudi Organisation for Human Rights]]| year =| url =https://www.esohr.org/en/?page_id=315| format =| doi =| accessdate =2018-08-25| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20180825074008/https://www.esohr.org/en/?page_id=315| archivedate =2018-08-25}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ESOHR_ListOf23\">{{cite web| last1 =| first1 =| last2 =| first2 =| authorlink =| title =The list of the twenty three (23)| publisher =[[European Saudi Organisation for Human Rights]]| date =2013-08-30| url =https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=707| format =| doi =| accessdate =2018-08-25| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20180825074024/https://www.esohr.org/en/?p=707| archivedate =2018-08-25}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"DW_Awamiya2017\">{{cite web | last1 = von Hein | first1 = Matthias | authorlink =  | title = Is Saudi Arabia waging war on its Shiite minority? | publisher = [[Deutsche Welle]] | date = 2017-08-10 | url = https://www.dw.com/en/is-saudi-arabia-waging-war-on-its-shiite-minority/a-40045513 | format =  | doi =  | accessdate = 2018-08-25 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20180825041303/https://www.dw.com/en/is-saudi-arabia-waging-war-on-its-shiite-minority/a-40045513 | archivedate = 2018-08-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RSF_createdAug2014\">{{cite news | last1= | first1= | last2= | first2= | pages= | language = | title= alqst.org | date= | publisher= [[Reporters Without Borders]] | url= https://rsf.org/en/alqstorg |accessdate=2018-10-28 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181028201805/https://rsf.org/en/alqstorg |archivedate= 2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"MEE_YAssiri_founding\">{{cite news | last1= | first1= | last2= | first2= | pages= | language = | title= The Saudi air force officer who became a human rights activist | date= 2015-03-05 | publisher= [[Middle East Eye]] | url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/in-depth/features/yahya-assiri-saudi-human-rights-1788490662 |accessdate=2018-10-28 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20181029152034/https://www.middleeasteye.net/in-depth/features/yahya-assiri-saudi-human-rights-1788490662 |archivedate= 2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Fr24_ADC\">{{cite news\n |first       = Mahamadou\n |last        = Sawaneh\n |pages       = \n |title       = Sectarian protests flare anew in Saudi Arabia\n |date        = 2011-10-07\n |publisher   = [[France 24]]\n |url         = http://observers.france24.com/content/20111007-sectarian-protests-flare-anew-saudi-arabia-shiia-sunni-royal-family-east-province\n |accessdate  = 2012-01-15\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120104023310/http://observers.france24.com/content/20111007-sectarian-protests-flare-anew-saudi-arabia-shiia-sunni-royal-family-east-province\n |archivedate = 2012-01-04\n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"indep_oct_livefire\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-police-open-fire-on-civilians-as-protests-gain-momentum-2365614.html |title=Saudi police 'open fire on civilians' as protests gain momentum |work=The Independent |first=Patrick |last=Cockburn |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2012-01-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125070933/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-police-open-fire-on-civilians-as-protests-gain-momentum-2365614.html |archivedate=2012-01-25 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n<!-- male guardianship -->\n\n<ref name=\"CNN_right_to_travel\">{{cite news | first1= Mohammed | last1= Jamjoom | first2= Tricia | last2= Escobedo | pages=  | language=  | title= Saudi woman activist demands right to travel | date= 10 July 2009 | publisher= [[CNN]] | url= http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/07/10/women.saudi/index.html |accessdate= 15 February 2009 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180527120650/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/meast/07/10/women.saudi/index.html |archivedate= 27 May 2018 |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"HRW2016\">{{cite web| last =| first =| authorlink =| title =Boxed In \u2014 Women and Saudi Arabia's Male Guardianship System| publisher =[[Human Rights Watch]]| date =16 July 2016| url =https://www.hrw.org/report/2016/07/16/boxed/women-and-saudi-arabias-male-guardianship-system |format =| doi =| accessdate =22 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826080422/https://www.hrw.org/report/2016/07/16/boxed/women-and-saudi-arabias-male-guardianship-system |archivedate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Guardian_2016_petition\">{{cite news| title=Thousands of Saudis sign petition to end male guardianship of women| date=26 September 2016| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/26/saudi-arabia-protest-petition-end-guardianship-law-women| accessdate=22 May 2018| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409111804/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/sep/26/saudi-arabia-protest-petition-end-guardianship-law-women| archivedate=9 April 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\n<!-- unconnected reference: is the following useful somewhere?\n[http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/02/07/509481/Saudi-Arabia-repression-dissidents-activists-Human-Rights-Watch Saudi Arabia repression dissidents activists Human Rights]\n-->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author=Laube, Lydia | title=Behind the Veil: A Nurse's Arabian Nightmare | publisher=Eye Books | year=2003 | isbn=1-903070-19-8 | oclc=51994153}}\n* {{cite book | author1=Mitchell, Sandy |author2=Hollingsworth, Mark | title=Saudi Babylon: Torture, Corruption and Cover-up Inside the House of Saud | publisher=Mainstream Publishing | year=2006 | isbn=1-84596-185-4 | oclc=225546299}}\n* {{cite book | author=Sasson, Jean| title=Princess: A True Story of Life Behind the Veil in Saudi Arabia  | publisher=Windsor-Brooke Books | year=2001 | isbn=0-9676737-4-7 | oclc=46766141}}\n* {{cite book | author=Jones, John Paul| title=If Olaya Street Could Talk: Saudi Arabia- The Heartland of Oil and Islam  | publisher=The Taza Press |date=2007 |isbn=978-0-9790436-0-4}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090213055649/http://www.un.org/webcast/unhrc/archive.asp?go=090206 Review of Saudi Arabia] by the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s [[United Nations Human Rights Council#Universal Periodic Review|Universal Periodic Review]], February 6, 2009\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/news/reportsfromabroad/durham/20071218.html Where Saudis will send their most dangerous]\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/ailib/intcam/saudi/ |title= Amnesty International \u2013 Saudi Arabia: End Secrecy, End Suffering |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070202011603/http://www.amnesty.org/ailib/intcam/saudi/ |archivedate=2007-02-02}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.salafimanhaj.com/pdf/SalafiManhaj_Saudi.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207145859/http://www.salafimanhaj.com/pdf/SalafiManhaj_Saudi.pdf |archive-date=2007-02-07 |title=Does Saudi Arabia Preach Intolerance in the West?}}\n* [http://www.cdhr.info/ Center for Democracy and Human Rights in Saudi Arabia]\n\n{{Saudi Arabia topics}}\n{{Asia topic|Human rights in}}\n{{Human rights in the Middle East}}\n{{Segregation by type|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human Rights In Saudi Arabia}}\n[[Category:Human rights in Saudi Arabia| ]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabia articles needing attention]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian law]]\n[[Category:Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia| ]]\n[[Category:Anti-Shi'ism in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Sectarianism| ]]\n[[Category:Sectarian violence| ]]\n[[Category:Shia\u2013Sunni sectarian violence]]\n[[Category:Controversies in Saudi Arabia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:Ensaf Haidar, wife of Raif Badawi speaking in 2015.jpg|thumb|[[Ensaf Haidar]], who is the wife of [[Raif Badawi]], was sentenced to 15 years in prison and 1,000 lashes for \"insulting Islam\" and \"blasphemy\".]]\nThe state of '''human rights in Saudi Arabia''' is consistently ranked as one of the worst in the world. The Saudi government, which enforces [[Wahhabism|Wahhabi sharia law]] under the [[Absolute monarchy|absolute rule]] of the [[House of Saud]], have been accused of and denounced by various international organizations and governments for violating multiple human rights within the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2004/41731.htm|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices \u2013 2004|author=Unattributed|first=|date=February 28, 2005|work=|accessdate=2008-06-02|publisher=US Department of State, Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labour}}</ref> The [[totalitarian]] regime ruling the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia is consistently ranked among the \"worst of the worst\" in [[Freedom House]]'s [[Freedom in the World|annual survey of political and civil rights]].<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/sites/default/files/inline_images/Worst%20of%20the%20Worst%202010.pdf Worst of the Worst 2010. The World's Most Repressive Societies]. freedomhouse.org</ref> Qorvis [[MSLGROUP|MSLGroup]], a U.S. subsidiary of [[Publicis Groupe]], has been working with [[Saudi Arabia]] amidst its executions of political protesters and opponents for more than a decade to [[Whitewashing (censorship)|whitewash]] its record of [[human rights abuses]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Chris|title=PR firm accused of helping Saudi Arabia 'whitewash' its human rights record|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/pr-firm-accused-of-helping-saudi-arabia-whitewash-its-human-rights-record-a6937271.html|accessdate=18 May 2016|work=[[The Independent]]|date=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Supplemental Statement Pursuant to the Foreign Agents Registration Act of 1938|url=http://www.fara.gov/docs/5483-Supplemental-Statement-20150504-19.pdf|website=fara.gov|publisher=[[Foreign Agents Registration Act]]|accessdate=18 May 2016|page=12|date=5 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nSaudi Arabia is one of approximately 30 countries in the world with [[judicial corporal punishment]]. In Saudi Arabia's case this includes [[amputation]]s of [[hands]] and feet for [[robbery]], and [[flogging]] for lesser crimes such as \"sexual deviance\" and [[drunkenness]].  In the 2000s, it was reported that women were sentenced to lashes for adultery; the women were actually victims of rape, but because they could not prove who the perpetrators were, they were deemed guilty of committing adultery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/story?id=3899920|title=Exclusive: Saudi Rape Victim Tells Her Story|author=ABC News|work=ABC News|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> The number of lashes is not clearly prescribed by law and is varied according to the discretion of judges, and ranges from dozens of lashes to several hundred, usually applied over a period of weeks or months.  In 2004, the [[United Nations Committee Against Torture]] criticized Saudi Arabia over the [[amputations]] and [[flogging]]s it carries out under [[Sharia]]. The Saudi delegation responded defending \"legal [[traditions]]\" held since the inception of Islam 1,400 years ago and rejected interference in its legal system.\n\nThe courts continue to impose sentences of flogging as a principal or additional punishment for many offences. At least five defendants were sentenced to flogging of 1,000 to 2,500 lashes. Flogging was carried out in prisons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnestyusa.org/research/reports/annual-report-saudi-arabia-2013?page=3 |title=Annual Report: Saudi Arabia 2013 &#124; Amnesty International USA |publisher=Amnestyusa.org |date=2013-05-23 |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Mazen Abdul-Jawad was sentenced to 1,000 lashes and five years in prison for bragging on a Saudi TV show about his sexual exploits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/6269161/Saudi-man-jailed-and-gets-1000-lashes-for-talking-about-sex.html|title=Saudi man jailed and gets 1,000 lashes for talking about sex|date=7 October 2009|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesundaily.my/node/150525|title=Saudi man gets 1,000 lashes and five years for TV sex boasts|website=www.thesundaily.my|access-date=2016-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161123060151/http://www.thesundaily.my/node/150525|archive-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Saudi blogger [[Raif Badawi]]'s sentence was increased to 1,000 lashes and ten years' imprisonment after he was accused of [[apostasy]] in 2012. The lashes were due to take place over 20 weeks. The first round (50) were administered on January 9, 2015, but the second round has been postponed due to medical problems. The case was internationally condemned and put a considerable amount of pressure on the Saudi legal system.\n\nIn October 2015, [[United Kingdom|UK]] pensioner and cancer victim Karl Andree, then 74, faced 360 lashes for home brewing alcohol.  His family feared the punishment could kill him. However, he was released and returned home in November that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34513096 |title=UK pensioner Karl Andree faces 360 lashes over Saudi wine |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, a Saudi man was sentenced to 2,000 lashes, ten years in prison and a fine of 20,000 [[Saudi riyal|riyal]]s (US $5,300) for making tweets critical of Islam, and denying the existence of [[God]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.vice.com/article/saudi-arabia-sentenced-man-to-10-years-in-prison-and-2000-lashes-for-atheist-tweets|title=Saudi Arabia Sentenced a Man to 10 Years in Prison and 2,000 Lashes for Atheist Tweets|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/saudi-court-sentences-man-to-10-years-2000-lashes-for-atheist-tweets/|title=Saudi court sentences man to 10 years, 2,000 lashes for atheist tweets|website=PBS NewsHour}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the official Twitter account of the Saudi Arabia prosecutors issued a warning to punish those who share anything satirical on social media that \"affects public order, religious values and public morals\". The punishment included a five-year prison term and a fine of 3 million riyals (US $800,000). The government of Saudi Arabia arrested a few intellectuals, businessmen and activists last year for the same reason.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-09-04/jail-sentence-steep-fines-for-disrupting-saudi-public-order|title=Saudi Arabia Threatens Prison Time for Satire 'Disturbing Public Order'|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Torture==\nWhile Saudi Arabia's Criminal Procedure Code prohibits \"torture\" and \"undignified treatment\" (art. 2) in practice torture and using torture to extract forced confessions of guilt remains common.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/|title=Saudi Arabia 2017/2018|website=www.amnesty.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2016/04/26/un-committee-against-torture-review-saudi-arabia|title=UN Committee against Torture: Review of Saudi Arabia|date=26 April 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/378927-saudi-arabia-maids-abuse/|title=Torture, abuse, & harassment: ex-housemaids describe horrors of working in Saudi Arabia to RT|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/society/2017/5/2/hundreds-of-tortured-bangladeshi-women-flee-saudi-arabia|title=Hundreds of 'tortured' Bangladeshi women flee Saudi Arabia|first=Diana|last=Alghoul|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/11/19/indonesia.saudi.maid.abuse/index.html|title=Indonesian maid dies after abuse in Saudi Arabia, rights group says|author1=Kathy Quiano |author2=Moni Basu|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsfirst.org/blog/saudi-arabia-s-record-torturing-those-who-dare-critique-it|title=Saudi Arabia's Record of Torturing Those Who Dare to Critique It|website=Human Rights First}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Amnesty International]], security forces continued to torture and ill- treat detainees to extract confessions to be used as evidence against them at trial. According to the organization, 32 defendants accused of spying for Iran were subjected to torture and forced to confess. Detainees were held incommunicado and denied access to their families.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/| title= SAUDI ARABIA 2016/2017 |access-date=2017-11-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a UN panel that visited Saudi Arabia after the kingdom\u2019s invitation to conduct an inspection, revealed that the country has been systematically using anti-terror laws to justify torture.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-torture-political-dissidents-anti-terror-laws-un-mohammad-bin-salman-a8388226.html|title=Saudi Arabia using anti-terror laws to detain and torture political dissidents, UN says|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=7 June 2018}}</ref> The report found that Saudis, who have been exercising their right to freedom of expression peacefully and calmly in the kingdom, have been systematically persecuted by the authorities.<ref>{{cit web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/un-accuses-saudi-arabia-of-using-anti-terror-laws-to-justify-torture|title=UN accuses Saudi Arabia of using anti-terror laws to justify torture|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=6 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Walid Fitaihi]] is a [[physician]] who studied and worked in the USA in the 1980s.<ref name='A1'>{{cite news |last1=Bohn |first1=Kevin |last2=Robertson |first2=Nic |title=Family of dual US-Saudi citizen being held in Saudi Arabia believes he has been tortured |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/03/politics/walid-fitaihi-us-citizen-saudi-arabia/index.html |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=CNN |publisher=edition.cnn.com |date=3 March 2019}}</ref> He was born in 1964 in [[Jeddah]], [[Saudi Arabia]]. He went back to Saudi Arabia in 2006. Dr. Fitaihi was arrested at the [[Ritz Carlton]] hotel in November 2017 and moved to [[al-Ha'ir Prison|al-Hair prison]] south of the capital.<ref name='A1'/><ref name='A2'>{{cite news |last1=Dahan |first1=Nadine |title=Famous Saudi doctor moved to high-security jail, source says |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/famous-saudi-doctor-moved-high-security-jail-source-says |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=middleeasteye |publisher=middleeasteye.net |date=1 February 2018}}</ref> The Ritz-Carlton hotel was used to hold many of the prominent prisoners of the [[Saudi government]] in 2017, according to Saudi activists.<ref name='A2'/>\n[[Aljazeera]] reported, Dr.Fitaihi told a friend he was \"blindfolded, stripped of his underwear and bound to a chair\".<ref name='A4'>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia tortured US citizen: Report |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/saudi-arabia-reportedly-tortured-citizen-nyt-190302191550541.html |accessdate=16 March 2019 |agency=Aljazeera |publisher=aljazeera.com |date=3 March 2019}}</ref><ref name='A7'>{{cite news |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=David D. |title=Saudi Arabia Is Said to Have Tortured an American Citizen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/02/world/middleeast/saudi-arabia-torture-american-citizen.html |accessdate=17 March 2019 |agency=nytimes |newspaper=nytimes.com |date=2 March 2019}}</ref> The daily report also said that, the Saudi government tortured him with electrical shocks, \"what appears to have been a single session of torture that lasted about an hour\".<ref name='A4'/><ref name='A7'/> Reports also said, he was whipped so severely, he could not sleep on his back for days.<ref name='A4'/><ref name='A7'/>\n\nIn August 2019, a news article released in ''[[The Independent]]'' reported that more than 100 female migrants of Bangladeshi descent and some 45 male migrants fled from [[Saudi Arabia]] following psychological and [[sexual harassment]] from employers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/saudi-arabia-bangladesh-women-migrants-abuse-sexual-harrasment-brac-a9080701.html|title=More than 100 Bangladeshi migrant women 'abused and harassed' return home from Saudi Arabia|accessdate=28 August 2019|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Capital punishment; right to representation==\n{{Further|Capital punishment in Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:AliMohammedAlNimrSchoolPhoto.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ali Mohammed Baqir al-Nimr|Ali al-Nimr]] was arrested at the age of 17 for his participation in the [[2011\u201312 Saudi Arabian protests|2011 Arab Spring protests]], and was sentenced to death by beheading at the age of 18.]]\nSaudi Arabia regularly engages in [[capital punishment]], including public executions by [[decapitation|beheading]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Rights group condemns Saudi beheadings|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/27184784|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2008-10-14}}</ref> The death penalty can be imposed for a wide range of offenses,<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi system condemned |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2003/aug/09/saudiarabia.brianwhitaker |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 August 2003 |accessdate=27 July 2011 |location=London |first=Brian |last=Whitaker}}</ref> including murder, rape, armed robbery, repeated drug use, [[apostasy]],<ref name= BBCexecutioner>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2966790.stm |title=Saudi executioner tells all |date=5 June 2003 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> adultery,<ref name= FRD306>{{cite book |title=Saudi Arabia A Country Study |last=Federal Research Division |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-4191-4621-3 |page=304}}</ref> witchcraft and sorcery<ref name= Miethe>{{cite book |title=Punishment: a comparative historical perspective  |last=Miethe |first=Terance D. |author2=Lu, Hong |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-521-60516-8 |page=63}}</ref> and can be carried out by beheading with a sword,<ref name= BBCexecutioner/> [[stoning]] or firing squad,<ref name= FRD306/> followed by crucifixion.<ref name= Miethe/> In 2005 there were 191 executions, in 2006 there were 38, in 2007 there were 153, and in 2008 there were 102.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International Report 2009, Saudi Arabia |url=http://thereport.amnesty.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/saudi-arabia#death-penalty |publisher=Amnesty International |accessdate=2009-08-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724104756/http://thereport.amnesty.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/saudi-arabia |archivedate=2009-07-24}}</ref>\n\nA spokesman for the [[National Society for Human Rights]], an organisation which is funded by the Saudi Government, said that the number of executions is rising because crime rates are rising, that prisoners are treated humanely, and that the [[Decapitation|beheading]]s deter crime, saying, \"Allah, our creator, knows best what's good for His people...Should we just think of and preserve the rights of the murderer and not think of the rights of others?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;jsessionid=45BQVYBAZNEV1QFIQMGCFFWAVCBQUIV0?xml=/news/2007/07/16/wsaudi116.xml|title=Saudis prepare to behead teenage maid|author=Tim Butcher|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2008-10-14 | location=London | date=July 16, 2007|author-link=Tim Butcher}}</ref>\n\n[[Saudi Arabian police]] and immigration authorities routinely abuse people who are stopped or detained, especially workers from developing countries. Earlier in November 2013, the authorities received criticism for the way they have planned and handled the crackdown on illegal workers. Saudi authorities \u2013 in some cases with the help of citizens \u2013 rounded up many illegal workers and physically abused them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/kumera-genet/beyond-outrage-how-the-af_b_4319840.html | work=Huffington Post |first=Kumera |last=Genet |title=Beyond Outrage: How the African Diaspora Can Support Migrant Worker Rights in the Middle East |date=2013-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/saudi-services-suffer-under-visa-clampdown-525713.html|title=Saudi services suffer under visa clampdown|work=Arabian Business|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2019, Saudi Arabia carried out [[2019 Saudi Arabia mass execution|mass executions of 37 imprisoned civilians]] who had been convicted mostly on the basis of confessions obtained under torture or written by the accused's torturers.<ref>{{cite news | last1= Qiblawi | first1= Tamara | last2= Balkiz | first2= Ghazi | pages= | language = | title= Exclusive: Saudi Arabia said they confessed. But court filings show some executed men protested their innocence |trans-title = | date= 2019-04-26 | publisher= [[CNN]] | url= https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/26/middleeast/saudi-executions-court-documents-intl/index.html |accessdate= 2019-04-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190426055318/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/26/middleeast/saudi-executions-court-documents-intl/index.html |archivedate= 2019-04-26}}</ref> Most of the executed belonged to the country's [[Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia|Shia minority]].<ref name=\"midd\">{{cite web |url=https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/saudi-executions-dozens-killed-included-some-arrested-juveniles |title=Saudi executions: Dozens killed included some arrested as juveniles |publisher=[[Middle East Eye]] |date=23 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Human trafficking==\n{{Main|Human trafficking in Saudi Arabia}}\nSaudi Arabia is a notable destination country for men and women trafficked for the purposes of [[slavery|slave labour]] and commercial sexual exploitation. Men and women from [[Central Asia]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Africa]], and many other countries voluntarily travel to Saudi Arabia as domestic servants or other low-skilled labourers, but some subsequently face conditions indicative of involuntary servitude.<ref name=\"factbook\">{{cite web|title=Trafficking In Persons|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/print_2196.html|website=cia.gov|publisher=[[The World Factbook]]|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nWomen, primarily from Asian and African countries are trafficked into Saudi Arabia for commercial sexual exploitation; others were kidnapped and forced into prostitution after running away from abusive employers.<ref name=\"factbook\"/>\n\n===Sexual slavery===\nSome Saudi men have also used contracted \"temporary marriages\" in countries such as Mauritania, Yemen, and Indonesia as a means by which to sexually exploit migrant workers. Females are led to believe they are being wed in earnest, but upon arrival in Saudi Arabia subsequently become their husbands' sexual slaves, are forced into domestic labor and, in some cases, prostitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2014/226806.htm |title=Saudi Arabia |publisher=State.gov |date=2014-06-20 |accessdate=2015-12-04}}</ref> Prostitution is illegal in Saudi Arabia.\n\n== Women's rights ==\n{{Main|Women's rights in Saudi Arabia}}\n\n===Guardianship system, segregation, and restrictions===\nSaudi women face [[discrimination]] in many aspects of their lives, such as the [[justice system]], and under the [[Wali (Islamic legal guardian)|male guardianship system]] are effectively treated as [[minor (law)|legal minors]].<ref name=\"HRW2016\" /> Although they make up 70% of those enrolled in universities, for social reasons, women make up 5% of the workforce in Saudi Arabia,<ref>Al-Sharq Al-Awsat (London), July 23, 2006, translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> the lowest proportion in the world.\nThe treatment of women has been referred to as \"[[sex segregation]]\",<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.hri.ca/pdfs/HRT%20Spring,%20Volume%208,%20No.%201,%202001.pdf \n |accessdate=2007-08-21 \n |title=Human Rights Tribune \u2013 ed. Spring 2001 \n |work=Human Rights Tribune \n |date=Spring 2001 \n |publisher=International Human Rights Documentation Network \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002083608/http://www.hri.ca/pdfs/HRT%20Spring%2C%20Volume%208%2C%20No.%201%2C%202001.pdf \n |archivedate=2008-10-02 \n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.nostatusquo.com/ACLU/dworkin/WarZoneChaptIIIA.html\n|title=A Feminist Looks at Saudi Arabia\n|year=1978\n|author=Andrea Dworkin\n|publisher=Andrea Dworkin on nostatusquo.com\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref>\"gender [[apartheid]]\",<ref name=Handrahan>{{cite journal |author=Handrahan LM |title=Gender Apartheid and Cultural Absolution: Saudi Arabia and the International Criminal Court |publisher=Human Rights Internet |journal=Human Rights Tribune' |volume=8 |issue=1 |date=Spring 2001}} {{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/the-australian-who-has-become-a-prisoner-of-gender-apartheid-20091113-ier0.html|title= The Australian who has become a prisoner of gender apartheid |date=November 14, 2009|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=March 6, 2010}}</ref> and of some women being \"prisoners\" of their male relatives.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> Implementation of a government resolution supporting expanded employment opportunities for women met resistance from within the labor ministry,<ref>Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia), May 18, 2006 translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> from the religious police,<ref>Al-Watan (Saudi Arabia), June 26, 2006 translated at [http://memri.org/bin/latestnews.cgi?ID=IA30006#_edn1 Public Debate in Saudi Arabia on Employment Opportunities for Women]</ref> and from the male citizenry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islamlight.net/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=2519&Itemid=27%5D|title=:: \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0646\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a|website=www.islamlight.net}}</ref>\n\nIn many parts of Saudi Arabia, it is believed that a woman's place is in the home caring for her husband and family, yet there are some women who do not adhere to this view and practice, and some run the house instead of the husband himself. Moreover, there is also some type of segregation at homes, such as different entrances for men and women.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\">{{cite news|title= Women Speak Out In Saudi Arabia |url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/03/23/60minutes/main682565.shtml |publisher= CBS News |date=March 24, 2005|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\nWomen's rights are at the heart of calls for [[Reform movement|reform]] in Saudi Arabia \u2013 calls that are challenging the kingdom's political status quo.<ref name=\"cbsnews1\"/> Local and international women's groups are also pushing governments to respond, taking advantage of the fact that some rulers are eager to project a more progressive image to the West. Since 2009, women and their male supporters have been organizing an [[Saudi anti male-guardianship campaign|anti male-guardianship campaign]].<ref name=\"CNN_right_to_travel\" /><ref name=\"Guardian_2016_petition\" /> Female leaders of this movement have been imprisoned without charge. Women in general who challenge the guardianship system may be sent to shelters for troubled women, where according to human rights activists they face torture and sexual abuse.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2019/02/01/mohammed-bin-salman-saudi-arabia-entertainment/|title=Mohammed bin Salman Is Running Saudi Arabia Like a Man Who Got Away With Murder|first=Sarah|last=Aziza|date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Men are free to abuse women in Saudi Arabia, with reports of women being locked in their rooms for months or threatened with starvation or shooting for offenses such as getting the wrong kind of haircut or being in a relationship with a man the family has not approved.<ref name=\"onpoint\" />  Women cannot file police reports without the permission of a male guardian, and may end up being imprisoned by the government for complaining.<ref name=\"onpoint\" />  Women are prohibited from certain professions (such as [[optometry]]) and may be prohibited from mixing with men at work, but according to the government as of 2017 compose 30% of workers in the private sector<ref name=\"bi\" /> (which is 40% of GDP).\n\nThe presence of powerful businesswomen\u2014still a rare sight\u2014in some of these groups helps get them heard.<ref name=\"economist1\">{{cite news|title= Women in the Middle East, A weak breeze of change |url= http://www.economist.com/world/africa/displaystory.cfm?story_id=10632747 |newspaper= The Economist |date=February 2, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-26}}</ref> Prior to 2008, women were not allowed to enter hotels and furnished apartments without a chaperone or [[mahram]]. With a 2008 Royal Decree, however, the only requirement for a woman to be allowed to enter hotels is a national ID card, and (as with male guests) the hotel must inform the nearest police station of their room reservation and length of stay.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/jan/25/yehey/top_stories/20080125top4.html\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402064855/http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2008/jan/25/yehey/top_stories/20080125top4.html\n|archivedate=2009-04-02\n|date=January 25, 2008\n|title=Saudi prince assures RP govt they respect rights of women\n|author=Jomar Canlas, Reporter\n|newspaper=The Manila Times\n|accessdate=2008-01-25}}</ref> In April 2010, a new, optional ID card for women was issued which allows them to travel in countries of the [[Cooperation Council for the Arab States of the Gulf|Gulf Cooperation Council]]. The cards include [[GPS tracking unit|GPS tracking]], fingerprints and features that make them difficult to forge. Women do not need male permission to apply for the card, but do need it to travel abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Saudi women get ID cards for GCC travel|url=http://www.menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.asp?StoryId=1093319416|accessdate=21 September 2010|newspaper=The Peninsula|date=4 May 2010}} {{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Proponents argue that new female identity cards enable a woman to carry out her activities with ease, and prevent forgeries committed in the name of women.\n\nWomen first joined the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia]] in 2013, occupying thirty seats.<ref name=\"saudigazette.com.sa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130225154468 |title=Women on 3 Shoura panels |author=Saudi Gazette |publisher= |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218023529/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130225154468 |archivedate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, that year three women were named as deputy chairpersons of three committees. Dr. Thurayya Obeid was named Deputy Chairwoman of the Human Rights and Petitions Committee, Dr. Zainab Abu Talib, Deputy Chairwoman of the Information and Cultural Committee, and Dr. Lubna Al-Ansari, Deputy Chairwoman of the Health Affairs and Environment Committee.<ref name=\"saudigazette.com.sa\"/>\n\n[[File:Loujain Alhathloul.jpg|thumb|upright|Women's rights activist [[Loujain al-Hathloul]] was arrested in May 2018]]\nIn 2013 the Directorate General of Passports allowed Saudi women married to foreigners to sponsor their children, so that the children can have residency permits (iqamas) with their mothers named as the sponsors, and have the right to work in the private sector in Saudi Arabia while on the sponsorship of their mothers, and the mother can also bring her children who are living abroad back to Saudi Arabia if they have no criminal records. Foreign men married to Saudi women were also granted the right to work in the private sector in Saudi Arabia while on the sponsorship of their wives on condition that the title on their iqamas should be written as \"husband of a Saudi wife\" and that they should have valid passports enabling them to return to their homes at any time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152985 |title=Women married to foreigners can now sponsor kids, spouse |author=Saudi Gazette |publisher= |accessdate=5 March 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730233947/http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/index.cfm?method=home.regcon&contentid=20130213152985 |archivedate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Saudi women married to foreigners, however, still face difficulty in passing their nationality to their children.\n\nAlso in 2013, Saudi Arabia registered its first female trainee lawyer, Arwa al-Hujaili.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=58013|title=.:Middle East Online::New victory for Saudi women: First female lawyer registered :.|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>  In Saudi courts, the testimony of women is weighted half that of a man's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/pictures/outrageous-facts-about-saudi-arabia/|title=15 outrageous facts about Saudi Arabia|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[CIA world factbook]], 82.2% of females are literate, in comparison to 90.8% literacy rates in males.<ref name=\"CIA Saudi\">{{cite web| title =CIA The World Factbook, Saudi Arabia|work=CIA| publisher =| date= September 20, 2007| url =https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/sa.html| doi =|accessdate=2008-06-02 }}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2018, the Saudi government changed several policies, allowing women to drive with the permission of their guardian, attend sporting events in gender-segregated area, participate in sports (including exercising on public streets), and eliminated the need for male permission to receive education, get healthcare, or open a business.<ref name=\"bi\" /> It began offering physical education for girls and said it would start licensing female-only gyms.<ref name=\"bi\" /> The government opened the military to women in March, who can serve if they meet certain physical and educational requirements, continue to live with their male guardian in the province of service, and get male permission.<ref name=\"bi\" /> It also granted divorced women the ability to retain custody of children without petitioning.<ref name=\"bi\" /> Male permission is still required to apply for a passport, travel, marry, divorce, or leave jail.<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/womens-rights-in-saudi-arabia-driving-ban-2018-3|title=Saudi Arabian women can now drive \u2014 here are the biggest changes they've seen in just over a year |publisher= Businessinsider|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> Men and women are also still segregated on public transport, beaches, and pools.<ref name=\"bi\" /> In practice, some doctors still require male permission before providing services,<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> and male permission may be needed to rent an apartment or file a legal claim.<ref name=\"bi\" /> In 2019, the Saudi government has been taken new measures to release male gardianship. Thus, women will be soon allowed to travel abroad without the need of getting the permission of their male guardians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudis-plan-to-ease-travel-restrictions-on-women-11562837401|title=Saudis Plan to Ease Travel Restrictions on Women|last=Said|first=Summer|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, two prominent female human rights activists, [[Samar Badawi]] and [[Nassima al-Sada]], were arrested for challenging Saudi Arabia's male guardianship laws.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/08/saudi-arabia-two-more-women-human-rights-activists-arrested-in-unrelenting-crackdown/|title=Saudi Arabia: Two more women human rights activists arrested in unrelenting crackdown |publisher= Amnesty International|accessdate=1 Aug 2018}}</ref> According to [[Amnesty International]], several arrested womens' rights activists detained without charge in Dhahban Prison are enduring torture by electrocution, flogging, hanging from the ceiling, sexual assault.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/11/saudi-arabia-reports-of-torture-and-sexual-harassment-of-detained-activists/ |title=Saudi Arabia: Reports of torture and sexual harassment of detained activists  |date=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, under the predominant male guardianship system, a Saudi woman lost a legal battle to marry the man she wanted to because he played a musical instrument, many conservative Muslims in the kingdom consider music to be \u201charam\u201d (forbidden). The male relative of the woman did not allow her to marry the man of her choice citing religious incompatibility as the man played [[oud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-45724710?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.com/news/topics/cwlw3xz0zl4t/saudi-arabia&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=Saudi woman 'barred from marrying man who played musical instrument'|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nSaudi Arabia is not a party to the [[International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights]], which among many other issues prohibits forced marriages. However, it is part of the Human Rights council.\n\nThe [[World Economic Forum]] in its [[Global Gender Gap Report]] 2018 ranked Saudi Arabia 141 out of 149 countries on gender equality.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/reports/the-global-gender-gap-report-2018|title=The Global Gender Gap Report 2018|accessdate=17 December 2018|publisher=World Economic Forum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/with-spotlight-back-on-saudi-women-s-rights-loujain-al-hathloul-s-fate-remains-unknown-1.4981281|title=With spotlight back on Saudi women's rights, Loujain al-Hathloul's fate remains unknown|accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the government also stated that women can start working in the military. In the past they could only work in police.<ref>https://m.khaleejtimes.com/region/saudi-arabia/saudi-women-can-now-join-the-armed-forces</ref>\n\n===Driving===\n{{main|Women to drive movement}}\nSaudi Arabia was the only country in the world where women were forbidden to drive motor vehicles until June 2018.<ref name=bashraheel/> The motoring ban was not in statute law, but was an \"informal\" religious [[fatwa]] imposed by conservative Muslim clerics<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia women drive cars in protest at ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-13809684|work=17 June 2011|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 October 2013|date=2011-06-17}}</ref> in order to maintain the country's tradition of gender segregation, although this religious view has changed in recent years.<ref name= Alarabia>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2010/05/25/109562.html|title=Women driving issue needs no fatwa: Saudi cleric|date=May 25, 2010|website=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062a}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, when 47 Saudi women drove cars through the streets of Riyadh in protest against the ban, protestors were punished. \"All the drivers, and their husbands, were barred from foreign travel for a year. Those women who had government jobs were fired, once their employers found out. And from hundreds of mosque pulpits, they were denounced by name as immoral women out to destroy Saudi society.\"<ref name=NPR>{{cite web|last=Murphy|first=Caryle|title=Saudi Women Reunite To Remember Driving Protest|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=97541372|work=December 16, 2008|publisher=NPR|accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhen the driving ban was enforced, women complained that \"we can't move around without a male.\"<ref name=BBC/> Many could not afford chauffeurs, and the few buses that do operate in cities and towns across the Kingdom do not follow a set schedule.<ref name=bashraheel>{{cite news|title= Women's transport: Solutions needed|author=Laura Bashraheel|url= http://www.arabnews.com/node/325728|newspaper=[[Arab News]]|date=June 27, 2009|accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref> On October 26, 2013, a group of women started a movement to defy the ban by driving themselves. However, on October 23, in a \"rare and explicit restating of the ban\", Interior Ministry Spokesman General Mansur al-Turki warned, \"It is known that women in Saudi are banned from driving and laws will be applied against violators and those who demonstrate support.\"<ref name=Casey>{{cite web|last=Casey|first=Mary|title=Saudi Arabia issues warning against women's driving campaign|url=http://mideast.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/10/25/saudi_arabia_issues_warning_against_women_s_driving_campaign|work=October 25, 2013|publisher=Foreign Policy magazine|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref> In December 2014, two women were arrested and sentenced to almost a month of prison for defying the female driving ban.<ref name=\"chronicle.fanack.com\">{{cite web|last1=Fanack|title=Saudi Arabia's Human Rights Record Under International Fire|url=https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/saudi-arabias-human-rights-record/|website=fanack.com|accessdate=13 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518082508/https://chronicle.fanack.com/saudi-arabia/history-past-to-present/saudi-arabias-human-rights-record/|archivedate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nWomen are allowed to fly aircraft, though they must be chauffeured to the airport.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia gets its first woman pilot|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/003200701121543.htm|newspaper=The Hindu|date=2007-01-12|accessdate=2008-06-02 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071026003928/http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/003200701121543.htm |archivedate = October 26, 2007|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> A Saudi woman made news in 2007 when she became the first woman to get her pilot's licence. The woman, [[Hanadi al-Hindi]] works for Saudi Prince [[Al-Waleed bin Talal|Al Waleed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/region/saudi-arabia-s-first-female-pilot-soars-high-2013-05-05-1.505229|title=Saudi Arabia's first female pilot soars high|last=Staff|date=5 May 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[Hisham Fageeh]], a Saudi living in the US, has created a video which makes a reference to the Government's rules which prevented women from driving. The video was released the same day many women in Saudi Arabia staged a nationwide protest against the Government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euronews.com/2013/10/26/no-woman-no-drive-saudi-women-battle-to-take-the-wheel/|title='No Woman, No Drive': Saudi women battle to take the wheel|work=euronews|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a Saudi woman working in neighbouring UAE was arrested as she tried to enter Saudi Arabia. She had her passport taken from her and was forced to wait at the Saudi-UAE border without any food or water. She claimed that her UAE drivers licence was valid in all GCC countries, but the Saudi border authorities refused to acknowledge its legitimacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2014/12/saudi-woman-arrested-driving-2014121165739368209.html|title=Saudi woman 'arrested' for driving|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/25/women-charged-saudi-arabia-driving-ban-terror-court| title=Two women referred to 'terror' court for driving in Saudi Arabia| work=the Guardian|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a royal decree was issued to allowing women to drive.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaouette|first=Nicole|last2=Labott|first2=Elise|date=27 September 2017|title=Saudi Arabia to let women drive at last|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/26/politics/saudi-arabia-woman-drive/index.html|website=CNN politics|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System, Inc.|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> The first driving license was issued to a Saudi woman in June 2018 and the ban on driving was lifted on June 24, 2018.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-44367981| title=Saudi Arabia issues first driving licences to women| date=5 June 2018| website=bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-44576795| title=Saudi Arabia's ban on women driving officially ends| date=24 June 2018| website=bbc.com}}</ref> Between the announcement and the lifting of the ban, the leaders of the Women to Drive campaign who violated the ban were arrested and tortured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-accused-of-torturing-women-activists-in-widening-crackdown-on-dissent-1542743107|title=Saudi Arabia Accused of Torturing Women\u2019s-Rights Activists in Widening Crackdown on Dissent|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMale permission is still required to travel outside the home, so many women in conservative families are still not allowed to drive.<ref name=\"onpoint\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/onpoint/2019/01/17/rahaf-mohammed-alqunun-asylum-canada-saudi-arabia-women|title=After Saudi Teen Granted Aslyum, A Look At Life For Women In The Kingdom|website=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\n==Racism==\n{{main|Racism in Saudi Arabia}}Racism in Saudi Arabia extends to allegations of imprisonment, physical abuse, rape,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jan/13/saudi-arabia-treatment-foreign-workers|title=Saudi Arabia's treatment of foreign workers under fire after beheading of Sri Lankan maid|last=Chamberlain|first=Gethin|date=13 January 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 January 2013}}</ref> overwork and wage theft, especially of foreign workers who are given little protections under the law.\n\n===Antisemitism===\n{{main|Antisemitism in Saudi Arabia}}Saudi Arabian media often attacks Jews in books, news articles, at their Mosques and with what some describe as antisemitic satire. Saudi Arabian government officials and state religious leaders often promote the idea that Jews are conspiring to take over the entire world; as proof of their claims they publish and frequently cite ''[[The Protocols of the Elders of Zion]]'' as factual.<ref>[http://www.edume.org/reports/10/38.htm CMIP report: The Jews in World History according to the Saudi textbooks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928005805/http://www.edume.org/reports/10/38.htm |date=2007-09-28 }}. ''The Danger of World Jewry'', by Abdullah al-Tall, pp. 140\u2013141 (Arabic). ''Hadith and Islamic Culture'', Grade 10, (2001) pp. 103\u2013104.</ref><ref>2006 Saudi Arabia's Curriculum of Intolerance, Report by Center for Religious Freedom of Freedom House. 2006</ref>\n\n==Rights of foreigners==\n=== Migrant workers' rights ===\n{{main|Kafala system#Saudi Arabia}}\nAccording to the 2016 [[Amnesty International]] annual report, Saudi authorities detained and deported hundreds of thousands of irregular migrants, while tens of thousands were fired without having been paid for months and were left stranded without food, water or exit visas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/countries/middle-east-and-north-africa/saudi-arabia/report-saudi-arabia/|title=Saudi Arabia 2016/2017|website=www.amnesty.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref>\n\n===Stateless people===\nThere are 70,000 [[Statelessness|stateless]] people in Saudi Arabia, also known as [[Bedoon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refugeesinternational.org/blog/stateless-saudi-driven-self-immolation|title=Blog \u2013 Stateless Saudi Driven to Self-Immolation \u2013 Refugees International|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424140108/http://refugeesinternational.org/blog/stateless-saudi-driven-self-immolation|archive-date=24 April 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some stateless are Yemenis who moved to Saudi Arabia, before the borders were in place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/07/18/saudi-but-stateless-born-on-margins-society.html|title=Saudi but stateless: born on the margins of society|date=25 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThis is also prevalent in neighbouring UAE, Kuwait, Qatar and Bahrain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21710679-many-are-left-stateless-result-silence-dissidents-gulf-states-are|title=To silence dissidents, Gulf states are revoking their citizenship}}</ref>\n\n=== Labors Rights ===\nEvery summer, the Saudi Ministry of Labor and Social Development enforce a 3-months midday outdoor work ban. The main aim of this ban is to protect labors from being directly exposed to the sun and high-temperature. Labor' either Saudi Nationals or foreigners, are welcomed to file any violations through the ministry's portal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/article/568463/SAUDI-ARABIA/Three-month-mid-daywork-ban-from-June-15|title=Three-month mid-day work ban from June 15|date=2019-06-09|website=Saudigazette|language=English|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\n==Sectarianism and freedom of religion==\n{{Main|Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia}}\nSaudi Arabian law does not recognize religious freedom, and the public practice of non-Muslim religions is actively prohibited.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/nea/136079.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100315154836/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/nea/136079.htm |archive-date=2010-03-15 |title=2009 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[United States Department of State]]}}</ref>\n\nNo law specifically requires citizens to be Muslims, but article 12.4 of the Naturalization Law requires that applicants attest to their religious affiliation, and article 14.1 requires that applicants get a certificate endorsed by their local cleric.<ref name=IRFR>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127357.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031224344/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127357.htm |archive-date=October 31, 2009|title=2009 International Religious Freedom Report 2009: Saudi Arabia|date=October 26, 2009|publisher=[[United States Department of State]]}}</ref> The Government has declared the Quran and the Sunna (tradition) of the Prophet Muhammad to be the country's constitution. Neither the Government nor society in general accepts the concepts of separation of religion and state, and such separation does not exist. The legal system is based on Shari'a (Islamic law), with Shari'a courts basing their judgments largely on a code derived from the Quran and the Sunna. According to Human Rights Watch, Saudi Arabia \"systematically discriminates against its Muslim religious minorities, in particular Shia and Ismailis\",<ref name=HRW-2013>{{cite web|title=World Report 2013, Saudi Arabia|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2013/country-chapters/saudi-arabia?page=3|work=2013|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> but the Government permits Shi'a Muslims to use their own legal tradition to adjudicate noncriminal cases within their community.<ref name=IRFR/>\n\nIn 2014, Saudi Arabia enacted new \"anti-terrorism\" legislation. [[Human Rights Watch]] criticized the broad language of the legislation and related government decrees, which have been used to prosecute and punish peaceful political activists and dissidents.<ref name=\"Withnall\">Adam Withnall, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-declares-all-atheists-are-terrorists-in-new-law-to-crack-down-on-political-dissidents-9228389.html Saudi Arabia declares all atheists are terrorists in new law to crack down on political dissidents], ''Independent'' (April 1, 2014).</ref> HEW stated, \"these recent laws and regulations turn almost any critical expression or independent association into crimes of terrorism.\"<ref name=\"Withnall\"/> A number of prominent [[human rights activists]] were detained under the new law, including [[Waleed Abulkhair]] and [[Mikhlif Alshammari]].<ref name=\"Withnall\"/> Interior Ministry regulations also defined \"calling for atheist thought in any form, or calling into question the fundamentals of the Islamic religion on which this country is based\" as terrorism.<ref name=\"Withnall\"/>\n\n===International law===\n\nSaudi Arabia abstained from the United Nations vote adopting the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], saying it contradicted [[sharia law]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Nisrine Abiad |title=Sharia, Muslim states and international human rights treaty obligations: a comparative study |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dex7TKuoUhgC |year=2008 |publisher=BIICL |isbn = 978-1-905221-41-7 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dex7TKuoUhgC&pg=PA60 60\u201365]}}</ref>\nIt is not a party to the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]], which includes freedom of religion.  The country holds a reservation to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child]] against any provisions that are in conflict with sharia law;<ref name=untreaty>United Nations Treaty Collection. ''[http://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-11&chapter=4&lang=en Convention on the Rights of the Child] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211151110/http://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=TREATY&mtdsg_no=IV-11&chapter=4&lang=en |date=11 February 2014 }}''. Retrieved 2 October 2015.</ref> Article 14 gives freedom of \"thought, conscience and religion\" to children. <!-- Unclear what its position was on the [[UN Declaration on the Elimination of All Forms of Intolerance and of Discrimination Based on Religion or Belief]]. -->\n\nSaudi Arabia and some of the Gulf states have been carrying out airstrikes on the Yemen, violating international laws and arresting anyone that criticises them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/05/09/asia/saudi-airstrikes-yemen/index.html|title=U.N. rep accuses Saudis of violating international law|author=Mariano Castillo|website=CNN|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45812399|title=The Jamal Khashoggi story so far|date=2018-12-11|access-date=2019-06-19|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/10/26/18000880/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-mbs-dissidents-imprisoned|title=While the world focuses on Khashoggi, dozens of journalists and activists in Saudi Arabia are still behind bars|last=Underwood|first=Alexia|date=2018-10-26|website=Vox|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations of Apartheid===\n[[Image:Christian Bypass.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Road sign on a highway into Mecca, stating that one direction is \"Muslims only\" while another direction is \"obligatory for non-Muslims\". [[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|Religious police]] are stationed beyond the turnoff on the main road to prevent non-Muslims from proceeding into Mecca and Medina.<ref name=mackeymecca>[[Sandra Mackey]]'s account of her attempt to enter Mecca in {{cite book|last=Mackey|first=Sandra|title=The Saudis: Inside the Desert Kingdom|year=1987|pages=63\u201364|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=0-393-32417-6}}</ref>]]\n''Saudi Arabia and the apartheid<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/opinions/2001/12/22/saudi-arabias-apartheid/6dc54ab8-37bc-4a87-86f4-c0b489fc8b8e/|title=Saudi Arabia's Apartheid|date=22 December 2001|publisher=|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frontpagemag.com/fpm/219517/saudi-arabia-middle-easts-real-apartheid-state-daniel-greenfield|title=Saudi Arabia: The Middle East's Real Apartheid State|date=23 February 2014|publisher=}}</ref> analogy'' is a comparison of [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Religious segregation|treatment of minorities and non-Muslim foreigners]] with [[South Africa]]'s treatment of non-whites during its [[apartheid era]], or the description of Saudi [[Gender segregation and Muslims|treatment of women under Sharia Law]] with the concept of [[Gender apartheid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/middleeast/201804071063314007-feminism-saudi-society-gender-apartheid/|title=Despite Rising Feminism in Saudi Society, \"Gender Apartheid\" Is Still There|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n\n===Christians===\n{{Main|Christianity in Saudi Arabia|Persecution of Christians#Saudi Arabia}}\nAs an Islamic state, Saudi Arabia gives preferential treatment for Muslims. During [[Ramadan]], eating, drinking, or smoking in public during daylight hours is not allowed.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=52719&d=11&m=10&y=2004&pix=kingdom.jpg&category=Kingdom\n|title=Non-Muslims Urged to Respect Ramadan\n|author=P.K. Abdul Ghafour\n|newspaper=Arab News\n|date=October 11, 2004\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref> Foreign schools are often required to teach a yearly introductory segment on Islam.\nSaudi religious police have detained Shi'ite pilgrims participating in the [[Hajj]], allegedly calling them \"[[kafir|infidels]] in Mecca\".<ref>{{cite news\n |url          = http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21680\n |title        = Saudi religious police accused of beating pilgrims\n |publisher    = Middle East Online\n |date         = August 7, 2007\n |accessdate   = 2008-06-02\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928023448/http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21680\n |archive-date = 2007-09-28\n}}</ref> The restrictions on the Shi'a branch of Islam in the Kingdom along with the banning of displaying Jewish, Hindu and Christian symbols have been referred to as apartheid.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bascio|first=Patrick|title=Defeating Islamic Terrorism: An Alternative Strategy|publisher=Branden Books|year=2007|page=60|isbn=978-0-8283-2152-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bqJjhalQ3wkC&pg=PA60|accessdate=March 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government has gone further than stopping Christians from worshipping in publicly designated buildings to even raid private prayer meetings among Christian believers in their own homes.  On December 15, 2011, Saudi security forces arrested 35 Ethiopian Christians in Jeddah who were praying in a home, beating them and threatening them with death. When the Ethiopian workers' employers asked security forces for what reason they were arrested, they said \"for practising Christianity\".  Later, under mounting international pressure, this charge was changed to \"mixing with the opposite sex\".\n<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.persecution.org/2011/12/17/42-ethiopian-christians-arrested-in-saudi-arabia\n|title=42 Ethiopian Christians Arrested in Saudi Arabia\n|publisher=International Christian Concern\n|date=December 17, 2011\n|accessdate= 2011-12-24}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.persecution.org/2011/12/21/saudi-arabia-arrests-ethiopian-christians-for-mixing-with-opposite-sex/\n|title=Saudi Arabia Arrests Ethiopian Christians For \"Mixing With Opposite Sex\"\n|publisher=International Christian Concern\n|date=2011-12-21}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, Saudi religious police detained more than 41 individuals after storming a house in the Saudi Arabian province of al-Jouf.  They were accused of \"plotting to celebrate Christmas,\" according to a December 26 statement released by the police branch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/14500 |title=Saudi detains dozens for \"plotting to celebrate Christmas\" |publisher=Al Akhbar English |date=2012-12-27 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101160358/http://english.al-akhbar.com/node/14500/ |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Proselytizing by non-Muslims, including the distribution of non-Muslim religious materials such as [[Bible]]s, is illegal in Saudi Arabia.\n\n===Shia Muslims===\n{{Main|Anti-Shi'ism#Saudi Arabia|Shia Islam in Saudi Arabia}}\nThe [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] government has often been viewed as an active oppressor of Shia Muslims because of the funding of the Wahabbi ideology which denounces the Shia faith.<ref name=syedjaffar/>\n\nIn 1988 [[fatwas]] passed by the country's leading cleric, [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Baaz|Abdul-Aziz ibn Baz]]  denounced the [[Shias]] as [[Apostates from Islam|apostates]]. Another by [[Abdullah Ibn Jibreen|Abdul-Rahman al-Jibrin]], a member of the Higher Council of Ulama is on record as saying\n\n<blockquote>Some people say that the rejectionists (''Rafidha'', i.e. Shia) are Muslims because they believe in God and [[Muhammad|his prophet]], pray and fast. But I say they are heretics. They are the most vicious enemy of Muslims, who should be wary of their plots. They should be boycotted and expelled so that Muslims be spared their evil.<ref name=HAKIM>[https://www.mail-archive.com/osint@yahoogroups.com/msg35080.html&#91;osint&#93; A top Saudi cleric declares Shiites to be infidels, calls on Sunnis to drive them out] {{dead link|date=December 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}} 22 Jan 2007 (originally in iht.com)</ref></blockquote>\n\nAccording to Vali Nasr, al-Jibrin's sanctioning of the killing of Shia was reiterated in Wahhabi religious literature as late as 2002.\n\nAccording to a 2009 [[Human Rights Watch]] report, Shia citizens in Saudi Arabia \"face systematic discrimination in religion, education, justice, and employment\".<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/en/news/2009/09/02/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally]|hrw.org| 2009/09/02</ref>\n\n[[Saudi Arabia]] has  no [[Shia]] cabinet ministers, [[mayors]] or police chiefs, according to another source, [[Vali Nasr]], unlike other countries with sizable [[Shia]] populations (such as [[Iraq]] and [[Lebanon]]). Shia are kept out of \"critical jobs\" in the armed forces and the security services, and not one of the three hundred [[Shia]] girls' schools in the Eastern Province has a [[Shia]] principal.\n\nPakistani columnist Mohammad Taqi has written that \"the Saudi regime is also acutely aware that, in the final analysis, the Shiite grievances ... stem from socioeconomic deprivation, as a result of religious repression and political marginalization bordering on [[Apartheid in South Africa|apartheid]].\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Mohammad Taqi |title=Saudi Arabia: the prized domino |date=March 10, 2011 |newspaper=Daily Times (Pakistan) |url=http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/editorial/10-Mar-2011/comment-saudi-arabia-the-prized-domino-dr-mohammad-taqi |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606211020/http://archives.dailytimes.com.pk/editorial/10-Mar-2011/comment-saudi-arabia-the-prized-domino-dr-mohammad-taqi |archivedate=June 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTestifying before the US [[Congressional Human Rights Caucus]], [[Ali al-Ahmed]], Director of the [[Institute for Gulf Affairs]], stated\n\n<blockquote>Saudi Arabia is a glaring example of [[religious apartheid]]. The religious institutions from government clerics to judges, to religious curriculums, and all religious instructions in media are restricted to the Wahhabi understanding of Islam, adhered to by less than 40% of the population. The Saudi government communized Islam, through its monopoly of both religious thoughts and practice. Wahhabi Islam is imposed and enforced on all Saudis regardless of their religious orientations. The Wahhabi sect does not tolerate other religious or ideological beliefs, Muslim or not. Religious symbols by Muslims, Christians, Jewish and other believers are all banned. The Saudi embassy in Washington is a living example of religious apartheid. In its 50 years, there has not been a single non-Sunni Muslim diplomat in the embassy. The branch of [[Imam Mohamed Bin Saud University]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]] instructs its students that Shia Islam is a [[Jewish conspiracy]].<ref>Human Rights in Saudi Arabia: The Role of Women, Congressional Human Rights Caucus, Testimony of Ali Al-Ahmed, Director of the Saudi Institute, June 4, 2002.</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn November 2014 at [[al-Dalwah]] village in the eastern province of [[Al-Ahsa Governorate|al-Ahsa]], three unknown masked gunmen [[2014 al-Dalwah attack|opened fire]] at a Husseiniya, or Shi'ite religious center, killing eight and injuring dozens.<ref name=\"HRW killings\">{{cite web|last1=Coogle|first1=Adam|title=Dispatches: Killings of Saudi Shia a Wakeup Call|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/11/06/dispatches-killings-saudi-shia-wakeup-call|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile the government and the official media and religious establishment strongly condemned the attack, a handful of articles in the Saudi press argued that the attack \"had not come out of nowhere\", that there was anti-Shi'ite incitement in the kingdom on the part of \"the religious establishment, preachers, and even university lecturers \u2013 and that it was on the rise\".<ref name=memri>{{cite web|title=Saudi Columnists: There Is Anti-Shi'ite Incitement In Our Country|url=http://www.memri.org/report/en/0/0/0/0/0/0/8330.htm|accessdate=14 December 2014|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi government has refused to allow Shia teachers and students exemption from school to partake in activities for the [[Day of Ashura]], one of the most important religious days for Shia Muslims which commemorates the martyrdom of [[Muhammad]]'s grandson, [[Husayn bin Ali]].<ref>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica</ref>  In 2009, during Ashura commencements, Shia religious and community leaders were arrested.\n\nShiites are banned from building mosques and other religious centers, and are forced to perform Friday prayers in  homes (Al-Hassan).  In the Eastern city of [[Al-Khobar]], whose population is predominately Shia, there are no Shia mosques.<ref name=\"HRW\">[https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/09/02/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally]\" | [[Human Rights Watch]] |  3 Sept. 2009.</ref>  Saudi Arabia's religious police mandate prayers and all those in public buildings during prayer time are required to stop what they are doing to pray.  Because there are minor differences between the way that Shiites and Sunnis pray and between prayer times, Shiites are forced to either pray the Sunni way or take a break from work.\n\nIn 2009 a group of Shiites on their way to perform [[hajj]] pilgrimage (one of the five pillars of Islam that all able-bodied Muslims are required to perform once in their lives) in Mecca were arrested by Saudi religious police.<ref name=\"HRW\"/> Between February 20 and 24, 2009, Shia pilgrims from the heavily Shia Eastern Province who had come to Medina for the anniversary of the prophet Muhammad's death clashed with Sunni religious police at the Baqi' cemetery over doctrinal differences concerning the rituals surrounding commemoration of the dead. Security forces shot a 15-year-old pilgrim in the chest, and an unknown civilian stabbed a Shia religious sheikh in the back with a knife, shouting \"Kill the rejectionist [Shia].\" The authorities denied that anyone had been wounded, and played down the ensuing arrests of Shia pilgrims.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nReligious police have arrested Shia Women in the Eastern Province for matters as trivial as organizing classes for Quranic studies and selling clothing for religious ceremonies as if they were involved in political activities which are not allowed in KSA.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nIn the  eastern city of Dammam  where three quarters of the 400,000 residents are Shia, there are no Shia mosques or prayer halls, no Shia call to prayer broadcast on TV, and no cemeteries for Shia.\n\nLate 2011, a Shiite pilgrim was charged for being \"involved with blasphemy\" and sentenced to 500 lashes and 2 years in jail.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16064123 Australian faces lashes for blasphemy in Saudi Arabia]| 7 December 2011 |bbc news</ref> Also late 2011, a prominent Shiite Canadian cleric, [[Usama al-Attar]].<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/10/20111031226131935.html Saudi police arrest Canadian imam at Hajj] aljazeera.com| 31 Oct 2011</ref> He was released on the same day, declaring the arrest entirely unprovoked.<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/10/20111031175454687101.html Saudi police release Canadian Shia imam]| aljazeera.com| Last Modified: 31 Oct 2011</ref>\n\nMuch of education in Saudi Arabia is based on Sunni Wahhabi religious material.  From a very young age, students are taught that Shiites are not Muslims and that Shiism is a conspiracy hatched by the Jews, and so Shiites are worthy of death.<ref name=al-Hassan>[http://tryme3000.20megsfree.com/mystory2-eng.htm Discrimination against Shia Muslims in Saudi Arabia: The Old and New Reality] by Dr. Mohamed J. Al-Hassan ([[King Saud University]])</ref>  Government Wahhabi scholars, such as Abdulqader Shaibat al-Hamd, have proclaimed on state radio that Sunni Muslims must not \"eat their [Shia] food, marry from them, or bury their dead in Muslims' graveyards\".<ref name=al-Hassan/>\n\nThe government has restricted the names that [[Shias]] can use for their children in an attempt to discourage them from showing their identity. [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] textbooks are hostile to Shiism, often characterizing the faith as a form of heresy worse than [[Christianity]] and [[Judaism]].\n\nBecause anti-Shia attitudes are engrained from an early age, they are passed down from generation to generation.  This prejudice is found not only in textbooks, but also within the teachers in the classroom, and even in the university setting.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  (Wahhabi) teachers frequently tell classrooms full of young Shia schoolchildren that they are heretics.<ref name=syedjaffar>{{cite web|last=syedjaffar|title=The Persecution of Shia Muslims in Saudi Arabia|url=http://ireport.cnn.com/docs/DOC-1015700|work=August 4, 2013|publisher=CNN Report|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Nasr 2006, p. 237\">Nasr, ''Shia Revival'', (2006), p. 237</ref> Teachers who proclaim that Shiites are atheists and deserve death have faced no repercussions for their actions, barely even receiving punishment.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  At a seminar about the internet, held in King Abdulaziz City of Science and Technology, professor Dr. Bader Hmood Albader explained that the internet was beneficial to society, but that there were many Shia websites claiming to be Muslim websites, which needed to be stopped.<ref name=al-Hassan/>\n\nMuch discrimination occurs in the Saudi workforce as well.  Shiites are prohibited from becoming teachers of religious subjects, which constitute about half of the courses in secondary education.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Shiites cannot become principals of schools.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Some Shiites have become university professors but often face harassment from students and faculty alike.<ref name=al-Hassan/>  Shiites are disqualified as witnesses in court, as Saudi Sunni sources cite the Shi'a practise of 'Taqiyya'- wherein it is permissible to lie while they are in fear or at risk of significant persecution. Shia cannot serve as judges in ordinary court, and are banned from gaining admission to military academies,<ref name=\"HRW\"/> and from high-ranking government or security posts, including becoming pilots in Saudi Airlines.<ref>Meyer, Henry. \"[http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-02-20/saudi-arabia-risks-shiite-unrest-in-wake-of-bahrain-turmoil.html Saudi Arabia Risks Shiite Unrest in Wake of Bahrain Turmoil] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502172057/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-02-20/saudi-arabia-risks-shiite-unrest-in-wake-of-bahrain-turmoil.html |date=May 2, 2011 }} | Businessweek | 20 Feb. 2011.</ref>\n\n[[File:Dawoud Al Marhoon.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Dawoud al-Marhoon]], sentenced to death in September 2015]]\n[[Amir Taheri]] quotes a Shi'ite businessman from Dhahran as saying \"It is not normal that there are no Shi'ite army officers, ministers, governors, mayors and ambassadors in this kingdom. This form of religious apartheid is as intolerable as was apartheid based on race.\" <ref>Taheri, Amir. Apartheid, Saudi Style, New York Post, May 22, 2003.</ref>\n\n[[Human Rights Watch]] reports that Shiites want to be treated as equals and desire to be free from discrimination (Human Rights Watch).  However, the Shia minority is still marginalized on a large scale.<ref name=\"HRW\"/>\n\nThe Saudi government has often been viewed as an active oppressor of Shias<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/08/24/anti-shia-bias-driving-saudi-arabia-unrest|title=Anti-Shia Bias Driving Saudi Arabia Unrest|date=24 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> because of the funding of the Wahabbi ideology which denounces the Shia faith.  In 1988 [[fatwas]] passed by the country's leading cleric, [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Baaz|Abdul-Aziz ibn Baz]] denounced the [[Shias]] as [[Apostates from Islam|apostates]].<ref>[http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20141209181117/http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PolicyFocus70FinalWeb.pdf ''With Neighbors Like These Iraq and the Arab States on Its Borders'', edited by David Pollock, Washington Institute Policy Focus No 70, June 2007], p33.\n\nThis cited ''A Top Saudi Cleric Declares Shiites to Be Infidels, Calls on Sunnis to Drive Them Out'', Associated Press, 21 January 2017.</ref> [[Abdullah Ibn Jibreen|Abdul-Rahman al-Jibrin]], a member of the Higher Council of Ulama sanctioned the killing on Shiites in 1994. According to Vali Nasr, this was still be reiterated in Wahhabi religious literature as late as 2002.<ref name=\":0\">Nasr, ''Shia Revival'', (2006) p. 236</ref> By 2007 al-Jibrin wrote that [Shiites] \"are the most vicious enemy of Muslims, who should be wary of their plots.\"<ref name=\":0\" />  According to a 2009 [[Human Rights Watch]] report, Shia citizens in Saudi Arabia \"face systematic discrimination in religion, education, justice, and employment\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/09/03/saudi-arabia-treat-shia-equally|title=Saudi Arabia: Treat Shia Equally|date=2009-09-03|newspaper=Human Rights Watch|language=en|access-date=2017-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Saudi Arabia executed the prominent Shiite cleric [[Sheikh Nimr]], who had called for pro-democracy demonstrations, along with 47 other Saudi citizens [[2016 Saudi Arabia mass execution|sentenced]] by the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] on terrorism charges.<ref>{{cite web | title=Saudi execution of Shia cleric sparks outrage in Middle East |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/02/saudi-execution-of-shia-cleric-sparks-outrage-in-middle-east |work=[[The Guardian]]| date=2 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SKEW7RtQ_U|title='It's like war here': Saudi govt cracks down on Shia town as Riyadh welcomes Trump|last=RT|date=19 May 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fDeDA9JRRrA|title=20,000 residents flee deadly Saudi offensive|last=PressTV|date=10 August 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CfwFS_Ynn7g|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S3U8jHg-HNA|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X0W5z-6zKt8|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> in response to protests against the government, the predominantly Shia town of [[Al-Awamiyah]] has been put under full siege by the Saudi military. Residents are not allowed to enter or leave, and military indiscriminately shells the neighborhoods with [[airstrike]]s, [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.abna24.com/news/a-h-b-world-assembly/abwas-satement-on-condemnation-of-al-sauds-crimes-in-awamiyah_845264.html|title=ABWA's satement on condemnation of Al Saud's crimes in Awamiyah|last=ABNA24|date=31 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> and [[artillery]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.abna24.com/news/middle-east/saudi-forces-shell-homes-in-awamiyah-two-killed-video-pics_844374.html|title=Saudi forces shell homes in Awamiyah, Two killed / Video & Pics|first=PressTV|last=ABNA24|date=26 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> fire along with [[sniper]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ifpnews.com/exclusive/snipers-injure-scores-civilians-saudi-arabias-qatif/|title=Snipers Injure Scores of Civilians in Saudi Arabia's Qatif|date=14 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> shooting residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/05/17/522264/Saudi-regime-forces-kill-Shia-man-Awamiyah-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces shot dead youth in restive Qatif|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://217.218.67.231/Detail/2017/05/18/522334/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-Shia-Qatif-Eastern-Province-crackdown|title=PressTV-Saudi regime offensive on Shia town enters week 2|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/388885-saudi-raid-siege-shiite-awamiyah/|title='You might get shot any time': Saudi forces raid Shia town as Riyadh welcomes Trump|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://en.abna24.com/news/middle-east/saudi-shia-town-under-siege-from-kingdom's-security-services-for-sixth-day_829902.html {{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> Dozens of Shia civilians were killed, including a three year old and<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/awamiyah-saudi-arabia-boy-killed-sniper-gun-shot-wounds-family-shot-at-open-fire-qatif-shia-nimr-al-a7886136.html|title=Three-year-old dies from wounds after Saudi security forces 'open fire on family'|publisher=}}</ref> a two-year-old children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://217.218.67.231/Detail/2017/05/12/521648/Saudi-kill-child-Shia-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces kill toddler, young man in Qatif|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.almanar.com.lb/260170|title=Saudi Forces Raid Al-Masoura in Awamiyah, Open Fire, Destroy Houses|publisher=}}</ref> The Saudi government claims it is fighting terrorists in al-Awamiyah.\n\nResidents also reported soldiers shooting at homes, cars and everyone in streets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/399222-saudi-forces-awamiyah-demolition/|title='Almost like war zone': Saudi 'renovation' of Shiite town decried as attempt to drive residents out|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/saudi-arabia-siege-town-own-citizens-government-kingdom-military-government-awamiyah-qatif-a7877676.html|title=Inside the Saudi town that's been under siege for three months by its own government|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the crackdown the Saudi government demolished several historical sites and many other buildings and houses in Qatif.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/saudi-awamiya-un-idINKBN18K1S0|title=U.N. slams erasing of \"cultural heritage\" in Saudi Arabia|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/06/14/525294/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-UN-Eastern-Province|title=PressTV- Saudi forces intensify attacks on Shia town|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/05/24/523077/UN-Saudi-Arabia-Shia-cultural-heritage|title=PressTV-'Riyadh erasing cultural heritage in Shia town'|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2017, Saudi authorities began refusing to give emergency services to wounded civilians. Saudi Arabia has also not provided humanitarian help to trapped citizens of Awamiyah.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al-Musawara neighborhood totally destroyed, Saudi Arabia says|url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/30097-al-musawara-neighborhood-totally-destroyed-saudi-arabia-says|website=Shiite News|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, it was reported that the Saudi government demolished 488 buildings in Awamiyah. This demolition came from a siege of the city by the Saudi government, as it continued to try to prevent the citizens of the city from gaining their rights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia demolishes 500 residential buildings in Awamiya|url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/30140-saudi-arabia-demolishes-500-residential-buildings-in-awamiya|website=Shiite News|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n20,000 residents were forced to flee from their homes to survive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-security-awamiya-idUSKBN1AJ217|title=Saudi man killed trying help citizens flee Awamiya: sources|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://presstv.ir/Detail/2017/08/11/531369/UN-Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah|title=PressTV-UN finally breaks silence on Saudi razing of town|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nPresident of Quran Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/06/25/526476/Saudi-Arabia-Awamiyah-Qatif|title=PressTV-Saudi forces kill head of Quran council in Qatif|publisher=}}</ref> and two cousins of executed [[Nimr al-Nimr]] were also killed by Saudi security forces in [[Qatif]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamidkarbalai.com/2017/03/saudi-regime-forces-kill-sheikh-nimrs.html|title=Saudi regime forces kill Sheikh Nimr's cousins in Qatif: Report|publisher=|access-date=2017-08-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806221347/http://www.hamidkarbalai.com/2017/03/saudi-regime-forces-kill-sheikh-nimrs.html|archive-date=2017-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/03/28/515921/Saudi-forces-shooting-Qatif-Eastern-Province-Sheikh-Nimr-cousins-killed|title=PressTV-'Saudi forces kill Nimr's cousins in Qatif'}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Saudi forces raided and \"violently ransacked\" the home of a Shia activist that had been executed the previous year. Saudi forces also arrested Zuhair Hussain bu Saleh, a Shia cleric, for organizing congregational prayers in his home in the city of [[Khobar]]. The Saudi government forbids Shia Muslims in Khobar from setting up a Mosque and gathering for worship.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saudi regime forces raid executed activist's home in Shia-populated Qatif |url=http://www.shiitenews.org/index.php/saudi-arab/item/34928-saudi-regime-forces-raid-executed-activist-s-home-in-shia-populated-qatif |website=Shiite News |publisher=Shiitenews.com |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Saudi authorities announced in May 2019, the decision to extend the jailterm for a cleric, Sheikh Mohammad bin Hassan al-Habib, known for challenging the systematic discrimination of Shia minorities in Saudi Arabia. Hassan al-Habib has been serving a seven-year prison sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/05/03/saudi-arabia-second-case-against-jailed-shia-cleric|title=Saudi Arabia: Second Case Against Jailed Shia Cleric|accessdate=3 May 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n===\"Magic, witchcraft and sorcery\"===\n{{Main|Witchcraft#Saudi Arabia}}\n{{See also||Religious discrimination against Neopagans}}\nAccording to Sarah Leah Whitson, Middle East director at [[Human Rights Watch]] in 2009, \"Saudi judges have harshly punished confessed `witches` for what at worst appears to be fraud, but may well be harmless acts.\"<ref name=HRW-2009>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia: Witchcraft and Sorcery Cases on the Rise|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/11/24/saudi-arabia-witchcraft-and-sorcery-cases-rise|work=November 24, 2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  In 2009 the Saudi \"[[Committee for the Promotion of Virtue and the Prevention of Vice (Saudi Arabia)|religious police]]\" established a special \"Anti-Witchcraft Unit\" to educate the public, investigate and combat [[witchcraft]].<ref name=MILLER/>\n\nAmong the people executed in Saudi for magic and sorcery (and often other charges) are Egyptian pharmacist Mustafa Ibrahim (beheaded in 2007 in Riyadh), Muree bin Ali bin Issa al-Asiri (found in possession of [[talisman]]s, and executed in [[Najran Region|Najran province]] in June 2012), Amina bin Salem Nasser<ref name=Telegraph>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia execution of 'sorcery' woman condemned|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/saudiarabia/8952641/Saudi-Arabia-execution-of-sorcery-woman-condemned.html|accessdate=13 Dec 2011|newspaper=Daily Telegraph|date=19 February 2014|location=London}}</ref> (executed in December 2011 in [[Al Jawf Region|Jawf]]), and Abdul Hamid Bin Hussain Bin Moustafa al-Fakki (a Sudanese migrant worker executed in a car park in [[Medina]] on September 20, 2011).<ref name=bbc-sorcery>{{cite news|title=Saudi man executed for 'witchcraft and sorcery'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-18503550|work=19 June 2012|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 February 2014|date=2012-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Execution Central: Saudi Arabia's Bloody Chop-Chop Square|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/453240/20130403/saudi-arabia-chop-square-beheading.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102124924/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/articles/453240/20130403/saudi-arabia-chop-square-beheading.htm|archivedate=2013-11-02}}</ref> [[Ali Hussain Sibat]], a Lebanese host of a popular fortune-telling TV program, was arrested while in Saudi in May 2008 on [[Umrah]] and sentenced to death but finally released sometime in 2011 or 2012.<ref name=Hilleary>{{cite web|last=Hilleary|first=Cecily|title=Saudi Arabia Morality Police Declare War on Witches |url=http://middleeastvoices.voanews.com/2012/03/saudi-arabia-morality-police-declare-war-on-witches-10918/|work=30 March 2012|publisher=Middle East Voices|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nMany convicted of magic receive lesser punishments of lashes and/or prison. In 2011, the \"Anti-Witchcraft Unit\" processed over 586 cases of magical crime.<ref name=Jacobs/> In 2012 there were 215 witchcraft arrests made.<ref name=Llanos>{{cite web|last=Llanos|first=Miguel|title=Saudi Arabia's religious police department has an Anti-Witchcraft Unit to combat sorcery. Arrests are on the rise and the penalty can be as severe as death.|url=http://news.msn.com/world/witchcraft-arrests-in-saudi-arabia-on-the-rise|work=8/20/13|publisher=MSN News|accessdate=20 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225175229/http://news.msn.com/world/witchcraft-arrests-in-saudi-arabia-on-the-rise|archive-date=25 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The majority of these offenders are foreign domestic workers from Africa and Indonesia.<ref name=Jacobs/>\nForeign domestic workers who bring unfamiliar traditional religious or folk customs are a disproportionately affected by the anti-witchcraft campaign according to Human Rights Watch researchers Adam Coogle and Cristoph Wilcke.  Saudis assume folk practices are \"some kind of sorcery or witchcraft\"<ref name=MILLER>{{cite news|last=MILLER|first=DAVID E.|title=Saudi Arabia's 'Anti-Witchcraft Unit' breaks another spell|url=http://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Saudi-Arabias-Anti-Witchcraft-Unit-breaks-another-spell|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|quote=We hear time and again of foreigners, such as Ethiopians or Nigerians, accused of sorcery in Saudi Arabia because of traditional practices from their countries of origin. ... They are usually apprehended by the religious police, brought to court, and let off with a warning or lashes. [Cristoph Wilcke]|date=2011-07-20}}</ref><ref name=Jacobs>{{cite journal|last=Jacobs|first=Ryan|title=Saudi Arabia's War on Witchcraft|journal=The Atlantic|date=August 19, 2013|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/08/saudi-arabias-war-on-witchcraft/278701/|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> and widespread belief in witchcraft means it can be invoked as a defense in Sharia courts against workers complaining of mistreatment by Saudi employers.<ref name=Jacobs2>{{cite journal|last=Jacobs|first=Ryan|title=Saudi Arabia's War on Witchcraft|journal=The Atlantic|date=August 19, 2013|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/08/saudi-arabias-war-on-witchcraft/278701/|quote=\"If there's an employer dispute \u2013 say the migrant domestic worker claims she wasn't paid her wages or her conditions are unlivable \u2013 a lot of times what happens unfortunately is the defendant makes counterclaims against the domestic worker,\" Coogle said. \"And a lot of times they'll make counterclaims of sorcery, witchcraft, and that sort of thing.\"|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  Humans Rights Watch believes that the conviction of a Syrian national, `Abd al-Karim Mara'I al-Naqshabandi \u2013 executed in 1996 for undertaking `the practice of works of magic and spells and possession of a collection of polytheistic and superstitious books`\u2014was actually resulted from a dispute with his employer Prince Salman bin Sa'ud bin `Abd al`Aziz, a nephew of [[Fahd of Saudi Arabia|King Fahd]].\n<ref>''A Fury For God : the Islamist Attack on America'' by Malise Ruthven, 2002 p.178-9</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title     = 'Flawed Justice: the Execution of 'Abd al-Karim Maria'I al-Naqshbandi'\n |publisher = Human Rights Watch\n |date      = October 1997\n |url       = http://hrw.org/reports/1997/saudi/\n|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20010719090112/http://hrw.org/reports/1997/saudi/\n|archive-date = 2001-07-19\n}}</ref>\n\n== Freedom of press and communication ==\n{{main|Censorship in Saudi Arabia}}\n\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]] in 2017 Saudi Arabia continued to repress pro-reform activists and peaceful [[dissident]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2018/country-chapters/saudi-arabia|title=World Report 2018: Rights Trends in Saudi Arabia|first1=Human Rights Watch {{!}} 350 Fifth|last1=Avenue|first2=34th Floor {{!}} New|last2=York|first3=NY 10118-3299 USA |last3=t 1.212.290.4700|date=9 January 2018|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\n[[File:London protest against Saudi Arabia's detention of prisoner of conscience Raif Badawi.jpg|thumb|A protest outside the [[Embassy of Saudi Arabia, London|Saudi Arabian Embassy]] in London against detention of [[Raif Badawi]], 13 January 2017]]\nSpeech, the press and other forms of communicative media, including television and radio broadcasting and Internet reception, are actively censored by the government to prevent political dissent and anything deemed, by the government, to be offensive to Wahhabi culture or Islamic morality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/filtering/saudiarabia/|title=Documentation of Internet Filtering in Saudi Arabia|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a prominent Saudi [[Blogging in Arab countries|blogger]] and reformist, [[Fouad al-Farhan]], was jailed for posting comments online that were critical of Saudi business, religious and media figures, signifying a move by the government to step up its censorship of the Internet within its borders.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/meast/02/27/saudi.blogger/index.html|title=No freedom for 'dean of Saudi bloggers'|publisher=|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> He was released on April 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0428/p07s02-wome.html|title=Saudi official: why popular blogger Farhan was jailed|author=The Christian Science Monitor|work=The Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOnline social media has increasingly come under government scrutiny for dealing with the \"forbidden\" topics. In 2010 a Saudi man was fined and given jail time for his sexually suggestive YouTube video production. That same year another man was also jailed and ordered to pay a fine for boasting about his sex life on television.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/10/saudi-man-arrested-for-se_n_493473.html |title=Saudi Man Arrested For Sexually Suggestive YouTube Video (VIDEO) |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |accessdate=2013-01-02 |first=Adam |last=Taylor |date=2010-03-10}}</ref>\n\n''D+Z'', a magazine focused on development, reports that hundreds were arrested in order to limit freedom of expression. Many of these individuals were held without trial and in secret. The torture of these prisoners was also found to be prevalent.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joseph |last=Miller |title=Open secrets |date=March 2003 |work=D+Z |publisher=Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Internationale Zusammenarbeit (GIZ) GmbH |url=http://www.inwent.org/ez/articles/192821/index.en.shtml |accessdate=2011-04-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221070951/http://www.inwent.org/ez/articles/192821/index.en.shtml |archivedate=2011-02-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2012, blogger [[Raif Badawi]] was charged with apostasy, which carries the death penalty. Badawi is the editor and of co-founder of Free Saudi Liberals, a website for religious discussion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/12/22/net-us-saudi-website-apostasy-idUSBRE8BL0DA20121222|title=Saudi website editor could face death for apostasy-rights group|date=Dec 22, 2012|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg130812>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-12/saudi-court-condemns-editor-to-600-lashes-with-breaks.html|title=Saudi Court Condemns Editor to 600 Lashes With Breaks|date=August 12, 2013|newspaper=Bloomberg|author=Jeremy Gerard}}</ref> The organization Human Rights Watch has called for charges against him to be dropped.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Eric Goldstein |author2=deputy Middle East director |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2012/12/22/saudi-arabia-website-editor-facing-death-penalty |title=Saudi Arabia: Website Editor Facing Death Penalty &#124; Human Rights Watch |publisher=Hrw.org |date=2012-12-22 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> He had been sentenced to seven years in prison and 600 lashes for \"insulting Islam\", but this sentence was changed to 1,000 lashes, 10 years in prison, and additionally a fine of 1,000,000 Saudi riyals. The lashes are due to be administered every Friday for 20 weeks, 50 lashes at a time, but have not continued past the first flogging. The second flogging has been postponed more than twelve times; previous postponements were due to health reasons, but the reason behind the most recent postponement is unknown.\n\nSaudi novelist and political analyst [[Turki al-Hamad]] was arrested December 24, 2012 after a series of tweets on religion and other topics. The arrest was ordered by Saudi Interior Minister Prince [[Mohammed bin Nayef|Muhammad bin Nayef]]; however the charges against al-Hamad were not announced.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/saudi-novelist-arrested-tweets-criticizing-islam |title=Saudi novelist arrested for tweets criticizing Islam |publisher=Al Akhbar English |date=2012-12-26 |accessdate=2013-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101054807/http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/saudi-novelist-arrested-tweets-criticizing-islam |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has since been freed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/saudi-arabia/detained-saudi-writer-turki-al-hamad-freed-1.1193165|title=Detained Saudi writer Turki Al Hamad freed| date=June 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Abdullah al-Hamid at the ninth hearing session.JPG|thumb|170px|[[Abdullah al-Hamid]] has been imprisoned seven times for supporting the establishment of a [[constitutional monarchy]] in Saudi Arabia. He has been serving an 11-year jail sentence since 2013.]]\nIn July 2015, [[Waleed Abulkhair]], a prominent human rights lawyer, founder of Monitor of Human Rights in Saudi Arabia and recipient of 2012 of the Palm prize for human rights, was sentenced to 15 years of prison by a special criminal court in Riyadh for vague offences such as \"setting up an unlicensed organization.\"<ref name=\"chronicle.fanack.com\"/><ref name=\"hrw2\">{{ cite web | url = https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/04/17/saudi-arabia-free-prominent-rights-activist | title = Saudi Arabia: Free Prominent Rights Activist| publisher = [[Human Rights Watch]] | accessdate = 2014-04-17 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 17, 2015, [[Ashraf Fayadh]], a [[Palestinian refugee#Saudi Arabia|Palestinian]] poet and [[contemporary art]]ist, was sentenced to death for committing apostasy. Fayadh was detained by the country's religious police in 2013 in [[Abha]], in southwest Saudi Arabia, and then rearrested and tried in early 2014. He was accused of having promoted [[Atheism and Islam|atheism]] in his 2008 book of poems ''Instructions Within''. However, the religious police failed to prove that his poetry was atheist propaganda and Fayadh's supporters believe he is being punished by hardliners for posting a video online showing a man being lashed in public by the religious police in Abha. Adam Coogle, a Middle East researcher for Human Rights Watch, said Fayadh's death sentence showed Saudi Arabia's \"complete intolerance of anyone who may not share government-mandated religious, political and social views\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batty|first1=David|title=Saudi court sentences poet to death for renouncing Islam|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/20/saudi-court-sentences-poet-to-death-for-renouncing-islam?CMP=share_btn_tw|accessdate=21 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=McDowall|first1=Angus|last2=Evans|first2=Dominic|title=Saudi court sentences Palestinian poet to death for apostasy: HRW|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/11/20/us-saudi-rights-idUSKCN0T913X20151120#tMy7vQtVcR9dHHDm.97|accessdate=21 November 2015|work=[[Reuters]]|date=20 November 2015|location=[[Riyadh]]}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2015, [[Culture of Saudi Arabia#Literature|Saudi Arabian writer]] and commentator [[Zuhair Kutbi]] was sentenced to four years in prison without clear charges following an interview at the [[Rotana Group#Rotana TV channels|Rotana Khaleejia]] TV channel in which he discussed his ideas for peaceful reform in Saudi Arabia to become a [[constitutional monarchy]], and talked about combatting [[Freedom of religion in Saudi Arabia|religious]] and [[political repression]]. Kutbi's lawyer and son said half the sentence was suspended, but that he was also banned from writing for 15 years and travelling abroad for five, and fined US$26,600.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saudi Arabia 'jails reformist writer Zuhair Kutbi'|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-35154411|accessdate=1 April 2016|work=[[BBC]]|date=21 December 2015|page=bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Saudi Arabia: Prominent Writer Detained \u2013 Discussed Peaceful Reform in TV Interview|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/08/10/saudi-arabia-prominent-writer-detained|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|accessdate=1 April 2016|location=[[Beirut]]|date=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nFebruary 2017, [[Human Rights Watch]] issued a report regarding the violation of freedom of speech in Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/02/07/509481/Saudi-Arabia-repression-dissidents-activists-Human-Rights-Watch|title=PressTV-Saudi Arabia steps up repression in 2017: HRW|publisher=}}</ref> According to the report, since 2010, at least 20 prominent Saudi dissidents were sentenced to a long prison term or a travel ban for some years; the offenses ranged from breaking allegiance with the ruling family{{clarify|date=February 2019}} to participating in protests demanding rights be respected. According to the report, the government has been trying to silence people expressing dissenting views regarding religion, politics, and human rights. On April 17, 2011, Nadhir al-Majed, a prominent 39-year-old writer, was arrested at school and detained for 15 months. On January 18, 2017, he was sentenced to seven years in prison and a seven-year travel ban; he has also not been permitted to call his family or receive visits. The conviction was based on \"his participation in protests in 2011 over discrimination against [[Shia Islam|Shia]]\" and \"his communication with international media and human rights organizations\", supporting the right of Shia in the country. On 10 January, Abdulaziz al-Shubaily, a human rights activist, was re-sentenced to eight years in prison, an eight-year ban on using social media after his release and an eight-year travel ban; the charges included \"his incitement against the government and judiciary\" as well as \"his communication with international agencies against his government\". He remains free on bail, however. On 8 January, Essam Koshak, 45, was detained without charge; he used social medial to highlight Saudi Arabia's repression of dissident writers, activists, and advocates for their release. Since 2014, nearly all Saudi dissidents have been sentenced to a long jail term based on their activism in addition to arrest of all the activists associated with the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]], which was dissolved on March 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/06/saudi-arabia-intensified-repression-writers-activists|title=Saudi Arabia: Intensified Repression of Writers, Activists|date=2017-02-06|newspaper=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-02-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the [[Right Livelihood Award]] awarded three jailed Saudi human rights activists with the \"alternative Nobel prize\" award. [[Abdullah al-Hamid]], [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani]] and [[Waleed Abu al-Khair]] were jointly awarded one million kronor cash award \"for their visionary and courageous efforts, guided by universal human rights principles, to reform the totalitarian political system in Saudi Arabia.\" {{As of|2018|09}}, al-Hamid and al-Qahtani, founding members of the [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]], were serving prison sentences of 11 and 10 years respectively, according to the charges for \"providing inaccurate information to foreign media, founding and operating an unlicensed human rights organization\"; while al-Khair, a lawyer and activist, was serving a sentence of 15 years for \"disobeying the ruler\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/09/24/world/europe/ap-eu-sweden-alternative-nobel.html|title=3 Saudi Human Rights Activists Awarded 'Alternative Nobel'|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a Saudi American journalist, Jamal Khashoggi was murdered inside a foreign embassy. He was a critic of Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In June 2019, a 101-page report by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|OHCHR]] accused the kingdom of Saudi Arabia for the premeditated [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/19/jamal-khashoggi-killing-saudi-crown-prince-mohammed-bin-salman-evidence-un-report|title='Credible evidence' Saudi crown prince liable for Khashoggi killing \u2013 UN report|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> The same year, British media group, [[The Guardian]], claimed that it was being targeted by a cybersecurity unit in Saudi Arabia. The unit was directed to hack into the email accounts of the journalists probing into the various crises involving the royal court. The claim was made based on what is said to be a confidential internal order, signed in the name of [[Saud al-Qahtani]], a close aide of the crown prince [[Mohammed bin Salman]] also named in the murder of Khashoggi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/19/guardian-told-it-was-target-of-saudi-hacking-unit-after-khashoggi-killing|title=Guardian told it was target of Saudi hacking unit after Khashoggi killing|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, ''[[The Guardian]]'' revealed that [[Saudi Arabia]] had been allegedly [[Espionage|spying]] its citizens in the [[US]]. The [[Media of the United Kingdom|British media]] cited that the nation has been readily exploiting the weakness in global mobile telecom network called [[Signalling System No. 7|SS7]], and informed that the data reviewed by them shows millions of covert tracking requests for the US location of Saudi-registered phones since November 2019.<ref>{{cite_web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/29/revealed-saudis-suspected-of-phone-spying-campaign-in-us |title=Revealed:Saudis suspected of phone spying campaign in US |accessdate=29 March 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Extraterritorial harassment, forced repatriation, and killing==\n[[File:Jamal Khashoggi in March 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right| [[Jamal Khashoggi]] was murdered by Saudis in Turkey, because of his opposition to the government ]]\n\nAbout 1200 people fled Saudi Arabia and sought asylum in other countries in 2017, including many women fleeing forced marriages or abusive male family members.<ref name=\"silence\">{{cite magazine |magazine= [[The New Yorker]] |author=Sarah Aziza |date=15 Jan 2019 |title=The Saudi Government's Global Campaign to Silence Its Critics}}</ref>  The Saudi government has frozen bank accounts, arrested family members, and revoked official documents in an attempt to get fleeing citizens to return to the country or to a Saudi embassy.<ref name=\"silence\" /> Students studying abroad have been threatened with termination of scholarships in response to criticism of the Saudi government on social media, and in 2018 some studying in Canada were de-funded after the Canadian government criticized human rights in Saudi Arabia.<ref name=\"silence\" /> Women who have successfully gained asylum in Western countries report fearing for their personal safety after being harassed by Saudi government agents on social media, and sometimes in person, warning them that they will be sorry for their actions or be punished.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> Occasionally they are asked to go to Saudi embassies for no stated reason.<ref name=\"onpoint\" /> One woman, unlike most, reported going to the embassy to try to end harassment of a firm she had left to her business partners, but she said authorities attempted to get her to return, threatened her, and said the business would continue to have problems as long as she remained in Germany.<ref name=\"silence\" />\n\nThe Saudi government is suspected of being behind the disappearance of its critic Naser al-Sa\u2019id from Lebanon in 1979.\nHuman rights activist Loujan al-Hathloul was forcibly repatriated from the United Arab Emirates in 2017, jailed for a short time, banned from future international travel, and then disappeared after being arrested again in 2018. Her husband was forcibly repatriated from Jordan.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jamal Khashoggi Wasn't the First \u2014 Saudi Arabia Has Been Going After Dissidents Abroad for Decades |date=12 Oct 2018 |author=Sarah Aziza |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/10/12/jamal-khashoggi-saudi-arabia-dissidents/ |website=[[The Intercept]]}}</ref> In 2016, three women and seven children who fled to Lebanon were arrested by Lebanese police and returned to Saudi Arabia minutes after using a bank card.<ref name=\"silence\" />\n\n[[File:Lastknowphotoofdinaali2.jpg|thumb|Last known photo of [[Dina Ali]] (left), on April 10, 2017]]\n\nIn April 2017, 24-year-old [[Dina Ali]] attempted to flee from Saudi Arabia to Australia via the Philippines to escape a [[forced marriage]]. Despite her pleas for international assistance over social media, airport personnel in the Philippines blocked her from boarding her flight to Sydney, and handed her over to Saudi authorities. She was duct taped and forcibly repatriated to Saudi Arabia, where she feared her family would kill her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/forcibly-reptriated-saudi-woman-my-family-will-kill-me/a-38445701|title=Forcibly repatriated Saudi woman: 'My family will kill me' |date= 16 April 2017|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Rahaf Mohammed]] attempted a similar flight from a forced marriage, traveling to Australia via Kuwait and Thailand. She also said that her family threatened to kill her for leaving Islam (which is also a capital offense in Saudi Arabia). After her passport was taken and authorities in Manilla acted at the request of the Saudi government to stop her travel, she barricaded herself in her hotel room and pleaded on social media for international assistance.  The [[UNHCR]] and the government of Canada intervened, and Rahaf travelled successfully to Canada via South Korea. Other Saudi women have done the similar things.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/death-threats-for-sydney-activist-behind-saudi-women-s-driving-breakthrough|title=Death threats for Sydney activist behind Saudi women's driving breakthrough|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2018, [[Jamal Khashoggi]] entered the Saudi consulate in [[Istanbul]] in order to deal with paperwork related to his marriage. A veteran Saudi journalist who had become a vocal critic of Saudi regime, upon arrival Khashoggi [[killing of Jamal Khashoggi|was assassinated]] and dismembered.<ref name=\"bbc_khashoggi_181025\" /> In the previous September, Khashoggi had fled Saudi Arabia after the arrests of other Saudi intellectuals, clerics and activists, fearing that he too would be arrested or banned from travelling.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/02/world/middleeast/journalist-saudi-consulate-istanbul.html|title=Journalist Detained in Saudi Consulate in Istanbul|work=The New York times|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/friends-fear-for-safety-of-prominent-saudi-writer-jamal-khashoggi/2018/10/02/f4d1cfbc-c66a-11e8-9c0f-2ffaf6d422aa_story.html?noredirect=on|title=Friends fear for safety of prominent Saudi writer Jamal Khashoggi|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> On 3 October, a Saudi official claimed that Khashoggi had been neither detained nor killed, saying \"He is not in the consulate nor in Saudi custody.\" [[Ibrahim Kalin]], Turkish presidential spokesman, said \"According to the information we have, this person who is a Saudi citizen is still at the Saudi consulate in Istanbul.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45744764|title=Jamal Khashoggi: Mystery over missing Saudi journalist deepens|work=BBC News|accessdate= 4 October 2018}}</ref> Three weeks after Khashoggi went missing, Saudi authorities acknowledged that he had been killed at the consulate and that his body was removed from the consulate. The killing was described as \"murder\" and \"a tremendous mistake\" by Saudi Foreign Minister [[Adel al-Jubeir]]. On 25 October 2018, one of the Saudi public prosecutors told the media that Khashoggi's murder was \"premeditated\".<ref name=\"bbc_khashoggi_181025\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45812399|title=Jamal Khashoggi: All you need to know about Saudi journalist's death|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 December 2019, [[Saudi Arabia]] sentenced five people to death for the [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]], while charged three others with a prison term of 24 years. The sentences did not include the names of previously accused masterminds, Mohammed al-Otaibi and Former royal adviser [[Saud al-Qahtani]]. Qahtani, who was under investigation earlier, was released with no evidence found against him.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/23/saudi-arabia-sentences-five-to-death-for-of-jamal-khashoggi|title=\nSaudi Arabia sentences five to death for murder of Jamal Khashoggi|accessdate=23 December 2019|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== Political freedom ==\n{{See also|Saudi Arabian municipal elections, 2005|Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia}}\n[[File:Secretary Pompeo Meets with Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman (30421982117).jpg|thumb|On 16 October 2018, Saudi Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] met with U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] to discuss the [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]], who was a vocal critic of the Saudi regime.]]\nThe 1990s marked a slow period of political liberalization in the kingdom as the government created a written constitution, and the advisory ''[[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Consultative Council]]'', the latter being an appointed delegation of Saudi scholars and professionals that are allowed to advise the king.  Some political dissidents were released from prison, after agreeing to disband their political parties.  In 2005, adult male citizens were allowed to vote for some municipal seats, although plans for future elections, which may include adult women, have been put on hold indefinitely.\n\n[[List of political parties in Saudi Arabia|Political parties are banned]], but some political dissidents were freed in the 1990s on the condition that they disband their political parties.  Today, only the [[Green Party of Saudi Arabia]] remains, although it is an illegal organization.  Trade unions are also banned, but the government has granted permission for Saudi citizens to form some private societies, which are allowed to do some humanitarian work within the kingdom.\n\nPublic demonstrations or any public act of dissent are forbidden.  In April 2011, during the [[2011\u20132012 Saudi Arabian protests]], the kingdom made it a crime to publish any criticism harming the reputation of government or religious leaders, or which harms the interests of the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/05/23/136570798/saudis-impatient-for-kings-promised-reforms|title=Saudis Impatient For King's Promised 'Reforms'|accessdate=2011-06-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]] annual report 2016, [[Saudi Arabia]] continued to prosecute pro-reform activists and dissidents. Saudi Arabia's terrorism court sentenced Waleed Abu al-Khair, prominent activist, to 15 years. He was convicted on charges concerning his peaceful criticism of the human rights situation in his country. In July, authorities arrested Zuhair Kutbi, an activist, because of his discussion to a peaceful reform in media. In September 2015, all of banned \u2013Saudi Civil Political Rights Association (ACPRA) founders were jailed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2016/country-chapters/saudi-arabia|title=Saudi Arabia|date=2016-01-12|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===Political prisoners===\n{{main|Political prisoners in Saudi Arabia}}\nDissidents have been detained as [[political prisoners in Saudi Arabia]] during the 1990s, 2000s and 2010s.<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\" /> Protests and [[sit-in]]s calling for political prisoners to be released took place during the [[2011\u20132012 Saudi Arabian protests]] in many cities throughout Saudi Arabia,<ref name=\"aljaz_20March\" /><ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\" /><ref name=\"HRW_Dec2011_protests\" /><ref name=\"presstv_RiyadhMakkah28Jul2012\" /><ref name=\"presstv_9Aug2012\" /> with security forces firing live bullets in the air on 19 August 2012 at a protest at [[al-Ha'ir Prison]].<ref name=\"ANHRI_19aug2012alHair\" /> {{As of|2012}}, recent estimates of the number of political prisoners in [[Mabahith]] prisons range from an estimate of zero by the [[Ministry of Interior]]<ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\" /><ref name=\"GulfNews_noprisonersinKSA\" /> to 30,000 by the [[United Kingdom|UK]]-based [[Islamic Human Rights Commission]]<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\" /> and the [[BBC]].<ref name=\"BBC_10to30k\" />\n\nAllegedly [[Jamal Khashoggi|Khashoggi]] was not the only dissident on Saudi's list to be abducted. Another Saudi prince, Khaled bin Farhan al-Saud, living in exile in [[Germany]], told [[The Independent]] that a similar kidnapping was planned against him by the Saudi authorities 10 days prior. \u201cOver 30 times the Saudi authorities have told me to meet them in the Saudi embassy but I have refused every time. I know what can happen if I go into the embassy. Around 10 days before Jamal went missing they asked my family to bring me to Cairo to give me a cheque. I refused,\u201d said Saud.  Five other royals, grandsons of [[Ibn Saud|King Abdul-Aziz]] were detained, when they raised their voice about Khashoggi's disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/jamal-khashoggi-missing-khaled-farahan-saudi-arabia-crown-prince-mbs-mohammad-bin-salman-a8579746.html|title=Dissident Saudi royal claims he was targeted with plan to 'disappear him' just days before journalist vanished\n|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, a prominent Saudi cleric, Ahmed al-Amari, was detained by the Saudi authorities over the allegations of being associated with scholar and Saudi royal family critic [[Safar al-Hawali]]. Amari was held in solitary confinement since then. In January 2019, Amari died suffering a brain hemorrhage.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-saudi-arrests/saudi-cleric-detained-in-crackdown-dies-activists-idUSKCN1PF1QM|title=Saudi cleric detained in crackdown dies: activists|accessdate=21 January 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the [[Washington Post]] reported that about eight citizens of [[Saudi Arabia]] were detained within two weeks for making critical comments against the kingdom. Rights groups have condemned the act by calling it an escalation of an ongoing crackdown on dissent.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2019/11/26/saudi-arabias-crackdown-dissent-keeps-going-here-are-latest-arrests/|title=Saudi Arabia\u2019s crackdown on dissent keeps going. Here are the latest arrests.|accessdate=26 November 2019|website=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n==Human rights organizations==\n[[File:King Salman bin Abdulaziz of Saudi Arabia bids farewell to President Barack Obama at Erga Palace in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.jpg|thumb|[[Human Rights Watch]] criticized U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] for not addressing human rights concerns in Saudi Arabia.<ref>\"[https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/03/31/dispatches-obama-refuses-talk-human-rights-saudi-arabia Dispatches: Obama Refuses to Talk Human Rights in Saudi Arabia]\". Human Rights Watch. March 31, 2014.</ref>]]\n\n===Independent===\nThe [[Committee for the Defense of Human Rights in the Arabian Peninsula]] is a Saudi Arabian human rights organization based in [[Beirut]] since 1992.<ref name=\"WISER_CDHRAP_NGO\" /><ref name=\"ColumbiaLawSchool_CDHRAP\" />\n\nThe [[Human Rights First Society]] applied unsuccessfully for a governmental licence in 2002, but was allowed to function informally.<ref name=\"USStateD_2002licence\">{{cite web |title=2008 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[United States State Department]] |date=2009-02-25 |url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402081759/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archivedate=2011-04-02}}</ref> The [[Association for the Protection and Defense of Women's Rights in Saudi Arabia]] was created in 2007 and is also unlicensed.<ref name=\"USStateD_APDWRSA_nolicence\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175245/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119126.htm |archive-date=2009-02-26 |title=2008 Human Rights Report: Saudi Arabia |publisher=State.gov |date=2009-02-25 |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (ACPRA) was created in 2009.<ref name=\"acpra_founding\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association (ACPRA) (An Establishing Declaration) \u2014 Riyadh, Saudi Arabia \u2014 Monday, October 12, 2009 |publisher=[[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] |date=2009-10-12 |url=http://www.acpra.net/news_view_5.html |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010032401/http://www.acpra.net/news_view_5.html |archivedate=October 10, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> One of its co-founders, [[Mohammed Saleh al-Bejadi]], was [[arbitrary arrest|arbitrarily arrested]] by [[Mabahith]], the internal security agency, on 21 March 2011, during the [[2011 Saudi Arabian protests]].<ref name=\"acpra_albjady_arrested\">{{cite web| title =ACPRA demands the immediate unconditional release of its co-founder, Mohammed Al-Bjady| publisher =[[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]]| date=March 2011| url =http://www.acpra.net/news.php?action=list&cat_id=12| format =| doi =| accessdate =2011-03-24| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110314210519/http://www.acpra.net/news.php?action=list&cat_id=12| archivedate =2011-03-14}}</ref><ref name=\"hrfs_aims\">{{cite web |title=Human Rights First Society \u2013 Human Rights Monitoring and Advocacy in Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[Human Rights First Society]] |date=March 2011 |url=http://hrfssaudiarabia.org/ |format= |doi= |accessdate=2011-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302192030/http://hrfssaudiarabia.org/ |archivedate=2011-03-02}}</ref> Al-Bejadi was charged in the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] in August 2011 for \"insurrection against the ruler, instigating demonstrations, and speaking with foreign [media] channels.\"<ref name=\"HRW_albjady\">{{cite web |title=World Report 2012: Saudi Arabia |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |year=2012 |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2012/world-report-2012-saudi-arabia |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126034621/http://www.hrw.org/world-report-2012/world-report-2012-saudi-arabia |archivedate=2012-01-26}}</ref> Another co-founder, [[Mohammad Fahad al-Qahtani]], was charged for his human rights activities in June 2012.<ref name=\"AI_2012_charges\" /><ref name=\"alkarama_charges\" />\n\nSixteen people who tried to create a human rights organization in 2007 were arrested in February 2007, charged in August 2010, and convicted on 22 November 2011 of \"forming a secret [organization], attempting to seize power, incitement against the King, financing terrorism, and money laundering\" and sentenced by the Specialized Criminal Court to 5\u201330 years' imprisonment, to be followed by travel bans.<ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_sentenced\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia: Lengthy sentences for reformists a worrying development |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=2011-11-23 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-lengthy-sentences-reformists-worrying-development-2011-11-23 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302224042/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-lengthy-sentences-reformists-worrying-development-2011-11-23 |archivedate=2012-03-02}}</ref> They appealed on 22 January 2012.<ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_to_appeal\">{{cite web |title=Reform activists in Saudi Arabia must receive fair appeal hearings |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=2012-01-25 |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/reform-activists-saudi-arabia-must-receive-fair-appeal-hearings-2012-01-25 |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304144526/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/reform-activists-saudi-arabia-must-receive-fair-appeal-hearings-2012-01-25 |archivedate=2012-03-04}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Society for Development and Change]] was created in September 2011<ref name=\"presstv_created_sep2011\" /> and campaigns for equal [[human rights]] for [[Shia]] in [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"Fr24_ADC\" /> The organisation calls for a [[constitution]] and elected [[legislature]] for [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Eastern Province]].<ref name=\"indep_oct_livefire\" /> The [[European Saudi Organisation for Human Rights]], which started operating around 2013,<ref name=\"ESOHR_ListOf23\" /> campaigns for Saudi human rights in general, including reports on what its leader Ali Adubisi describes as the Saudi government's \"war\" against the Eastern Province.<ref name=\"DW_Awamiya2017\" /><ref name=\"ESOHR_AboutUs\" /> [[ALQST]] is a Saudi human rights organisation created in August 2014 by [[Yahya Assiri]], with a Saudi-based team for collecting evidence and a London-based team for reports and human rights campaigning.<ref name=\"RSF_createdAug2014\" /><ref name=\"MEE_YAssiri_founding\" />\n\n===Government-associated===\nIn 2004, the [[National Society for Human Rights]], associated with the Saudi government, was created.<ref name=\"karavali_hrfs_on_elections\">{{cite news |pages= |title=Saudi polls, aid sweeteners not enough: activists |date=2011-03-24 |publisher=[[Karavali Times]] |url=http://www.karavalitimes.com/middle-east/saudi-polls-aid-sweeteners-not-enough-activists/ |accessdate=2011-03-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321193438/http://www.karavalitimes.com/middle-east/saudi-polls-aid-sweeteners-not-enough-activists/ |archivedate=2012-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"ksa_embassy_NSHR\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/2004News/Press/PressDetail.asp?cIndex=193|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061121163639/http://www.saudiembassy.net/2004News/Press/PressDetail.asp?cIndex=193 |title=First independent human rights organization in Saudi Arabia|archivedate=November 21, 2006}}</ref> Most of the commission's directors are members of the Saudi \"religious and political establishment\" according to [[John R. Bradley]].<ref name=bradley-expo->{{cite book|last=Bradley|first=John R.|title=Saudi Arabia Exposed : Inside a Kingdom in Crisis|url=https://archive.org/details/saudiarabiaexpos00brad|url-access=registration|date=2005|publisher=Palgrave |page=[https://archive.org/details/saudiarabiaexpos00brad/page/165 165] |quote= }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Rights Commission (Saudi Arabia)|Human Rights Commission]] is a government organization established in September 2005. It claims to be fully independent from the government in performing its responsibilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrc.gov.sa/en-us/aboutHRC/AboutHRC/Pages/HRCvision.aspx|title=Human Rights Commission|last=|first=|date=|website=Human Rights Commission|access-date=}}</ref> In March 2019 it opposed international investigation of the 2 October 2018 [[assassination of Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref name=\"NPR_commission_opposes_investigation\">{{cite news | last1=Romo | first1=Vanessa | last2= | first2= | pages= | language = | title= Saudi Arabia Rejects Calls For Independent Investigation Into Khashoggi Killing |trans-title = | date= 2019-03-14 | newspaper= [[NPR]] | url= https://www.npr.org/2019/03/14/703590542/saudi-arabia-rejects-calls-for-independent-investigation-into-khashoggi-killing |accessdate= 2019-10-15 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191014221210/https://www.npr.org/2019/03/14/703590542/saudi-arabia-rejects-calls-for-independent-investigation-into-khashoggi-killing |archivedate= 2019-10-14 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== LGBT rights ==\n{{Main|LGBT rights in Saudi Arabia|Death penalty for homosexuality}}\n[[LGBT]] [[Human rights|rights]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] are unrecognized. [[Homosexuality]] is frequently a taboo subject in Saudi Arabian society and is punished with imprisonment, [[corporal punishment]] and [[capital punishment]]. [[Transgender]] people are generally associated with homosexuality and doctors are banned by the Saudi Ministry of Health from giving [[hormone replacement therapy]] to transgender people seeking to medically transition.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}} In 2017, two [[transgender]] Pakistanis were tortured to death by Saudi police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/transgender-pakistani-saudi-arabia-tortured-death-amna-meeno-11-custody-lgbt-rights-human-a7607446.html|title=Two transgender Pakistanis 'tortured to death' by police in Saudi Arabia|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== HIV/AIDS ==\nBy law, all Saudi citizens who are infected with HIV or AIDS are entitled to free medical care, protection of their privacy and employment opportunities. However, most hospitals will not treat patients who are infected, and many schools and hospitals are reluctant to distribute government information about the disease because of the strong taboos and stigma that are attached to how the virus can be spread.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.arabnews.com/?page=1&section=0&article=68051&d=7&m=8&y=2005\n|title=AIDS? What AIDS?\n|publisher=Arab news\n|author1=Manal Quota |author2=Maryam Yamani |date=August 7, 2005\n|accessdate=2008-06-02}}</ref>\n\nUntil the late 1990s, information on [[HIV]]/[[AIDS]] was not widely available to the public, but this has started to change.  In the late 1990s, the government started to recognize [[World AIDS Day]] and allowed information about the disease to be published in newspapers.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}  The number of people living in the kingdom who were infected was a closely guarded secret.  However, in 2003 the government announced the number of known cases of HIV/AIDS in the country to be 6,700, and over 10,000 in June 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/08/world/middleeast/08saudi.html\n|title=Saudi Arabia Begins to Face Hidden AIDS Problem\n|newspaper=New York Times\n|author=Hassan M. Fattah|date=August 8, 2006\n}}</ref>\n\n==International conventions==\nThe Kingdom of Saudi Arabia ratified the [[International Convention against Torture]] in October 1997 according to the Office of the UN High Commissioner for Human Rights. The Human rights of Saudi Arabia are specified in article 26 of the [[Basic Law of Saudi Arabia]]. Recently created human rights organisations include [[Human Rights First Society]] (2002),<ref name=\"USStateD_2002licence\" /> [[Association for the Protection and Defense of Women's Rights in Saudi Arabia]] (2007),<ref name=\"USStateD_APDWRSA_nolicence\" /> [[Saudi Civil and Political Rights Association]] (2009)<ref name=\"acpra_albjady_arrested\" /><ref name=\"hrfs_aims\" /> and the government-associated [[National Society for Human Rights]] (2004).<ref name=\"karavali_hrfs_on_elections\" /><ref name=\"ksa_embassy_NSHR\" /> In 2008, the [[Consultative Assembly of Saudi Arabia|Shura Council]] ratified the [[Arab Charter on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saudiembassy.net/2008News/News/RigDetail.asp?cIndex=7698|title=Shura Council ratifies Arab Charter on Human Rights}}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2011, the [[Specialized Criminal Court]] was used to charge and sentence human rights activists.<ref name=\"HRW_albjady\" /><ref name=\"AI_alRashudi16_sentenced\" />\n\n==Responses and criticisms==\n{{expand section|date=April 2018}}\nThe United Nations Special Rapporteur on Counter Terrorism, [[Ben Emmerson]], criticized Saudi Arabia for violating human rights in the name of fighting terrorism during his visit to Saudi Arabia from 30 April to 4 May 2017. According to the report, Saudi Arabia uses its terrorism tribunal and counterterrorism law to unjustly prosecute human rights defenders, writers, and peaceful critics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/05/26/saudi-arabia-counterterrorism-apparatus-targets-rights-activists|title=Saudi Arabia: Counterterrorism Apparatus Targets Rights Activists|date=2017-05-26|publisher=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2017-11-19|language=en |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725145038/https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/05/26/saudi-arabia-counterterrorism-apparatus-targets-rights-activists|archivedate=25 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adhrb.org/2017/05/adhrb-welcomes-rapporteur-terrorisms-observations-saudi-visit/|title=ADHRB Welcomes Rapporteur on Terrorism's Observations After Saudi Visit|date=2017-05-08|publisher=Americans for Democracy & Human Rights in Bahrain|access-date=2017-11-19|language=en-US |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015110839/http://www.adhrb.org/2017/05/adhrb-welcomes-rapporteur-terrorisms-observations-saudi-visit/|archivedate=15 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the U.N. Third Millennium Summit in [[New York City]], King [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|Abdullah bin Abdul Aziz]] defended Saudi Arabia's position on human rights, saying \"It is absurd to impose on an individual or a society rights that are alien to its beliefs or principles.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud|title=Statement by Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz, King of Saudi Arabia, during the U.N. Third Millennium Summit|url=https://www.un.org/millennium/webcast/statements/saudi.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|date=6 September 2000}}</ref>\n\nCanadian Minister of Foreign Affairs issued a statement via Twitter on 2 August 2018 expressing [[Canada]]'s concern over the recent arrest of [[Samar Badawi]], a human rights activist and sister of imprisoned Saudi blogger [[Raif Badawi]], and called for the release of Saudi human rights activists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2018/08/05/saudi-arabia-to-expel-canadian-ambassador-and-freeze-trade-in-human-rights-dispute.html|title=Saudi Arabia expels Canadian ambassador, freezes trade in human rights dispute|author=Jon Gambrell|publisher=The Associated Press|website=Toronto Star|date=5 August 2018}}</ref> In response to Canada's criticism, [[Canada\u2013Saudi Arabia relations|Saudi Arabia expelled]] Canada's ambassador and froze all new trade with Canada.<ref>{{cite news |title='We don't have a single friend': Canada's Saudi spat reveals country is alone |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/11/canada-saudi-arabia-support-us |work=The Guardian |date=11 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. refuses to back Canada in Saudi Arabia dispute |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-us-sidesteps-getting-involved-in-escalating-saudi-canada-dispute/ |work=The Globe and Mail |date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA joint statement released by 36 countries at the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] in [[Geneva]] in March 2019, condemned the [[Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|murder of the Saudi journalist]] [[Jamal Khashoggi]], called for the release of Saudi women\u2019s rights activists detained in May 2018, and urged the kingdom to stop using counterterrorism regulations to target dissidents and human rights activists.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/07/un-call-free-saudi-women-activists|title=UN: A Call to Free Saudi Women Activists|accessdate=7 March 2019|publisher=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> The letter, which is the first collective rebuke of the kingdom, demanded the release of prominent women activists, including [[Loujain al-Hathloul]], [[Hatoon al-Fassi]] and [[Samar Badawi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/07/middleeast/saudi-arabia-criticism-intl/index.html|title=Saudi Arabia criticized over human rights by 36 countries|accessdate=7 March 2019|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, following increased pressure from non-profit organization [[Human Rights Foundation]], [[Nicki Minaj]] pulled out of the Jeddah World Fest, Saudi Arabia in support of the nation\u2019s suppressed women and LGBTQ community.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/07/08/human-rights-group-asks-nicki-minaj-cancel-performance-saudi-arabia/|title=Human rights group asks Nicki Minaj to cancel performance in Saudi Arabia|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> Minaj said, \u201cI could make one mistake & go to jail in a diff country where women have no rights,\u201d after learning about the constant abuse of human rights in the nation. The organization lauded Minaj\u2019s decision and urged other artists of the likes of [[Steve Aoki]] and [[Liam Payne]] from performing in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/arts/music/nicki-minaj-saudi-arabia.html|title=Nicki Minaj Cancels Saudi Show After Complaints From Human Rights Groups|work=The New York Times|accessdate=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, ahead of Saudi [[Spanish Super Cup]] due to be held in January 2020, Spanish broadcaster [[RTVE]] said that it will not bid for the hosting rights of the tournament because of human rights concern, especially women rights in the field of sports. \"It's a country where until very recently women couldn't go to watch football,\" the broadcasting service said. [[RFEF]] President [[Luis Rubiales]], defended the claims and said, he could assure women would be allowed to enter without any restrictions.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.begadistrictnews.com.au/story/6493694/spanish-state-tv-shuns-super-cup-in-jeddah/?cs=2439|title=Spanish state TV shuns Super Cup in Jeddah |accessdate=15 November 2019|website=Bega District News}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Human Rights Watch]] alongside 11 other international rights group organizations wrote a joint letter to the [[Amaury Sport Organization]] following its decision to move [[Dakar Rally]] to [[Saudi Arabia]]. The rights group in their letter accused Saudi Arabia of violating women's rights in the nation and asked the French organizer to denounce the persecution of women\u2019s rights, as well as adopt the human rights policy. \"The Amaury Sport Organisation and race drivers at the Dakar Rally should speak out about the Saudi government\u2019s mistreatment of women\u2019s rights activists for advocating for the right to drive,\u201d the statement from the Human Rights Watch global initiatives director read. However, Saudi human rights group Al Qst asked Amaury Sport Organisation not to consider the plea.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/international-coalition-urges-amaury-sport-organisation-to-adopt-human-rights-policy-ahead-of-saudi-hosted-dakar-rally|title=International coalition urges Amaury Sport Organisation to adopt human rights policy ahead of Saudi-hosted Dakar Rally|accessdate=13 January 2020|website=Business & Human Resource Research Centre}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, [[Meghan MacLaren]] withdrew from Saudi leg of Ladies European Tour due to be held in March 2020. The golfer cited she cannot ignore what organizations like [[Amnesty International]] have highlighted. \u201cI\u2019ve decided not to play based on what I think sport is being used to do in [[Saudi Arabia]],\" she said while emphasizing on the appalling human rights record of the nation.\u201cWe take for granted a lot of the choices and freedom we have available to us, but I try to make my decisions based on who I am as a person, not just a golfer,\" statement from her interview further read.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.nationalclubgolfer.com/news/meghan-maclaren-explains-saudi-snub/|title='It\u2019s a huge tournament but this is about more than golf'|accessdate=29 January 2020|website=National Club Golfer}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n*[[Legal system of Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[LGBT rights in Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Shi'a Islam in Saudi Arabia]]\n*[[Human rights in Muslim-majority countries]]\n*[[Human rights in the Middle East]]\n*[[Timeline of first women's suffrage in majority-Muslim countries]]\n*[[Hack of Jeff Bezos' phone]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n\n<!-- political prisoners summary -->\n\n<ref name=\"IHRC_3rd_decade_silence\">{{cite web |title=Saudi Arabia's political prisoners: towards a third decade of silence |publisher=[[Islamic Human Rights Commission]] |date=2011-09-30 |url=http://ihrc.org.uk/attachments/article/9867/Saudi%20Report%20A4-v04.pdf |format= |doi= |accessdate=2012-02-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203081209/http://www.ihrc.org.uk/attachments/article/9867/Saudi%20Report%20A4-v04.pdf |archivedate=2011-12-03}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DailyBeast_qahtani_profile\">{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Giglio |title=Saudi's Surprise Renegades |date=2011-05-01 |website=[[The Daily Beast]] |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/05/01/saudi-s-surprise-renegades.html |accessdate=2012-07-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120602070507/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/05/01/saudi-s-surprise-renegades.html |archivedate=2012-06-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"aljaz_20March\">{{cite news |title=Saudi protest ends with arrests |date=21 March 2011 |publisher=Al Jazeera English |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320112126999266.html |accessdate=21 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321131829/http://english.aljazeera.net/news/middleeast/2011/03/2011320112126999266.html |archived